<HEADLINE> FIFA Set to Reverse Provision for Over-23 Players </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, November 12 (Xinhua) -- All soocer players taking part
in the next summer Olympic Games will be under the age of 23.
</P>
<P>
FIFA, soccer's world governing body, said on Wednesday that
soccer in the Olympics may revert to being restricted only to
players under the age.
</P>
<P>
The FIFA committee responsible for Olympic soccer proposed
dropping the provision that allows teams to field three players
over 23.
</P>
<P>
The committee said it would ask FIFA's executive board to
reinstate the rule limiting the competition to players under 23.
If approved as expected, the rule will be in effect for the 2000
Olympics in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's announcement will further strain relations between
FIFA and the International Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
The provision allowing three over-age players was brought in
for the 1996 Atlanta Games at the urging of the IOC, which hoped
to increase the level of what has mostly been a youth competition.
</P>
<P>
But FIFA, which is eager to protect the supremacy of its own
World Cup, said it believes the Olympic competition is attractive
enough as an under-23 event.
</P>
<P>
Most European countries fielded under-23 teams anyway in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
The FIFA committee also announced the allocation of berths for
the Sydney competition.
</P>
<P>
Australia qualifies automatically as host, as does defending
champion Nigeria. There will be four more spots for Africa, two
for South America, two for the CONCACAF region and three for
Asia. The third team to qualify from Asia will contest a playoff
against the top team from Oceania.
</P>
<P>
For the women's tournament, the eight finalists will consist of
Australia and the top seven from the 1998 World Cup in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
The qualifying period will run from August 1, 1998 to April
2000.
</P>
<P>
The men's Olympic final will be played at the main Olympic
stadium in Sydney, with the women's final at the Sydney Football
Ground. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
