<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bertrand Remains No. 1 Overall at OOCL Yachting Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Although it was a day for
American Jeff Madrigali who took the fourth race, Australia's
America's Cup legend John Bertrand remained atop of the field at
the 1997 Oriental Overseas Container Line Ltd. (OOCL) Etchells
World Yachting Championships here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a day of light winds, a few new names emerged in the top
positions of Race 4, with Madrigali taking the first place,
followed by Australian Ian Johnson and Denmark's two-time Olympic
champion Poul-Richard Hoj-Jensen.
</P>
<P>
Australian sailmaker and ex-Dennis Connor crew, Michael Coxon,
second in Race 3 on Tuesday, was given a tie for the second place
after winning a protest today.
</P>
<P>
Madrigali got a much needed first place after his
disqualification yesterday due to a lost protest. Australian
Johnson, the second placer today, was a previous unknown in the
championships' first three races.
</P>
<P>
Coxon's fellow sailmaker and countryman Noel Drennan was
fifth. Another sailmaker, American Jud Smith, was sixth, just
ahead of Hong Kong's Mark Thornburrow.
</P>
<P>
Regatta leader Bertrand, who competed five times and won once
in the America's Cup, finished eighth. But race rules allow one
discard out of the six races.
</P>
<P>
Another Etchells champion and America's Cup veteran Colin Beashel
finished twelveth.
</P>
<P>
In the overall regatta standigs, it is Bertrand, Drennan, Coxon,
Hoj-Jensen and then Beashel.
</P>
<P>
Thursday is a lay day, giving the 30 boats and 91 crew members
a much deserved rest. Sailing starts again on Friday with Race 5
and the final race is set for Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The OOCL World Championships is the last leg of the OOCL World
Series. Skippers are competing for the OOCL World Series Trophy,
based on their accumulated points over the three-year, four
regatta series. 
</P>
</TEXT>
