<HEADLINE> Philippine Ruling Party Probes Vote-Buying Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine ruling
Lakas-NUCD party has started to investigate alleged vote buying in
last Sunday's consultation meeting for selecting a presidential
candidate for the 1998 polls, a presidential aide said today.
</P>
<P>
Presidential adviser for political affairs Gabriel Claudio, who
is also the ruling party's deputy secretary-general, confirmed
that the party's 16-member ad hoc electoral committee has acted to
look into the reported scandal on the order of President Fidel
Ramos.
</P>
<P>
Claudio said the committee is coordinating closely with the
eight contenders for the party's nomination, their supporters and
participants in the consultation meeting, to verify these reports.
</P>
<P>
The reports said that Jose de Venecia, speaker of the House of
Representatives, and former defense secretary Renato S. de Villa
were allegedly engaged in buying votes of participants at Sunday's
caucus, the first round of the party's nomination consultations.
</P>
<P>
Both de Villa and de Venecia have denied engaging in bribery
and other forms of inducement to gain the support of party
members.
</P>
<P>
They said the pre-caucus meetings with caucus participants and
some party leaders were conducted in an open and transparent
manner.
</P>
<P>
Claudio said no formal complaints or evidence had been filed
with or received by the party's electoral committee.
</P>
<P>
Claudio blasted the opposition for playing up and taking
advantage of such unverified reports to discredit the on-going
consultation process and undermine the unity of the ruling party.
</P>
<P>
The ruling party will hold the second round of consultations
this Sunday, during which party members will choose the party's
presidential bet through secret balloting.
</P>
<P>
Based on the results of the meetings, Lakas Chairman Ramos will
finally nominate the party's presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
Also today, the opposition Struggle of Patriotic Filipino
Masses announced that it had decided to defer its national
convention from late November to December or early January.
</P>
<P>
The party, the country's largest opposition group, is expected
to choose its presidential candidate between Senator Edgardo
Angara and Vice President Joseph Estrada.
</P>
<P>
Political observers here said that the opposition is now trying
to monitor the movements of the ruling party and learn from its
mistakes in the nomination process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
