<HEADLINE> Political Stability Key to Investment: Namibia's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 12 (Xinhua) -- There is need for southern
African countries to maintain political stability if the region
is to attract further investment in mining, Namibia's General
Manager of the Chamber of Mines John Rogers said today.
</P>
<P>
Rogers told the two-day regional mining conference which
started in Harare Tuesday that the political stability prevailing
in the region is conducive to attracting investors.
</P>
<P>
He said political upheavals often contributed to lack of clear
policies toward the establishment of businesses apart from the
inherent insecurity they posed to investors.
</P>
<P>
Rogers cited vast deposits of mineral wealth in Angola and
Mozambique which had not been exploited due to prolonged civil
wars.
</P>
<P>
''It is encouraging, therefore, that political stability is
increasing in the region which is essential for long-term
commitment needed by mining companies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Rogers said there is need for governments in the region to
continue improving the investment climate.
</P>
<P>
''Political stability and clear fiscal policies will encourage
mining companies to invest in exploration activities which,
hopefully, will result in the development of mines,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the region's economy could grow further by producing
finished mineral products as opposed to semi-finished products.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that mining contributes to approximately 10
percent of the region's gross domestic product, while accounting
for 60 percent of foreign exchange earnings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
