<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Countries Try to Rebuild "Silk Road" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Asian countries along the old
"silk road" will have a first regional conference next week in
Turkmenistan to draft a transit transport framework agreement.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from Afghanistan, Armenia, Azerbaidjan, China,
Georgia, Iran, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Pakistan, Russia,
Tajikistan, Turkey, Turkmenistan and Uzbekistan will take part in
the conference convened by the United Nation Conference on Trade
and Development (UNCTAD) and financed by the UN Development
Program.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the conference to be held on November 18-20 in
Ashgabad, Turkmenistan, is to lay the basis for a solid regional
regulatory framework that will make transit operations in Central
Asia efficient and cost effective, thus promoting the external
trade of the sub-region and bolstering its economic growth, the
UNCTAD said in a press release here today.
</P>
<P>
The UNCTAD secretariat has prepared a blueprint for a transit
transport framework agreement that will provide an effective
institutional framework for the region-wide coordination of
transit transport policies. This will include the harmonization of
technical standards of regional transport networks, as well as the
simplifying and harmonizing of customs procedures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
