<HEADLINE> Russia, China to Skirt U.S. Dollar with Mutual Payments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, November 12 (Xinhua) -- It is possible for Russia and
China to conduct mutual investments and settlements without using
the U.S. dollar, President of the Russian Union of Industrialists
and Entrepreneurs Arkady Volsky said here today.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was made at the first meeting of the
Russian-Chinese Committee for Peace and Development in the 21st
Century in Beijing on November 10, Volsky told Interfax Tuesday
upon the completion of Russian President Boris Yeltsin's China
tour.
</P>
<P>
He said the proposal that the price of the yuan be set in
roubles sparked arguments; it was decided to calculate the figure
based on "labor input."
</P>
<P>
The main purpose of the new structure is to help the two
countries handle, within the context of economic reforms, specific
tasks, primarily those related to the development of
Russian-Chinese economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the bilateral Committee's 1998 work plan has not
been finalized due to the large number of proposals submitted by
both sides, Volsky explained.
</P>
<P>
He said the Committee's efforts to boost economic links between
the two countries has already led to positive changes.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Russia's May Tea Association held talks. As a
result, China may recover its leading position with regard to tea
exports to Russia, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
