<HEADLINE> No Progress in Peace Prevents Egypt From Doha </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa today blamed the impasse in the Mideast process for Egypt's
decision of non-participation in a controversial economic meeting
slated to open in Qatar Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Moussa made the statement after a meeting with President Hosni
Mubarak, Prime Minister Kamal el-Ganzouri and other key cabinet
members to assess the current situation in the domestic and
regional arena.
</P>
<P>
Egypt Tuesday decided to boycott the imminent Middle East and
North Africa economic conference as it saw little chance of
breaking up the Israeli-Palestinian crisis which has been in place
since March due to Israel's construction of a Jewish settlement in
Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on his meeting here Tuesday with the Palestinian
peace negotiators who attended the latest round of talks with the
Israelis in Washington, Moussa described the situation as "critical"
and downplayed hopes for a breakthrough in the stalled talks.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said over the coming two days, U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright will hold talks with Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, in
London and Bern.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that there will be progress, but let's ask ourselves
as Egyptian diplomats: what is next?" Moussa said, voicing his
pessimism.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Moussa said the present peace stalemate,
Israeli negative policies and the lack of progress on all tracks
of the peacemaking were behind Egypt's decision not to take part
in the Doha conference.
</P>
<P>
In an interview granted this morning to the BBC, Moussa said "a
grave situation and unjustified backtracking" obliged Egypt to
adopt this decision.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt's non-participation decision does not aim to embarrass
anyone but rather it aims at addressing a sound message at a
proper time," Moussa said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
