<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern Africa to Experience Water Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The drought-prone southern
African region is projected to experience a crippling decline of
fresh water supply between now and 2050, according to a book
released here today.
</P>
<P>
The book by the U.S.-based International Food Policy Research
Institute is entitled ''Achieving Food Security in Southern
Africa: New Challenges and Opportunities''.
</P>
<P>
It says the water shortages could push the region to the brink
of disaster unless steps are taken to regulate water supply.
</P>
<P>
Countries experience water stress when their fresh water
resources are between 1,000 and 1,600 cubic meters per person and
are in serious trouble if resources drop below 1,000 cubic meters
per capita.
</P>
<P>
The book says Zimbabwe's fresh water resources are projected
to fall from 2,323 cubic meters per capita in 1990 to 864 cubic
meters per capita in 2050.
</P>
<P>
The situation would not be so bad in Namibia which is said to
have ''relative abundance of fresh water resources of 6,672 cubic
meters per capita in 1990 projected to drop to 2,162 by the year
2050''.
</P>
<P>
''Such declines could have serious effect on food production
in the region,'' the book says. ''Agriculture is by far the
biggest consumer of water resources and the most inefficient
user.
</P>
<P>
''Projections are that Africa will need to triple its
agricultural production in the period 1990 to 2025 to achieve
food security for its growing population,'' the book says.
</P>
<P>
According to the book, steps should be taken now to regulate
water supply to ensure that farming in the region begins to grow
enough food for the population.
</P>
<P>
The southern Africa region includes Angola, Botswana, Lesotho,
Madagascar, Malawi, Mauritius, Mozambique, Namibia, South Africa,
Swaziland, Tanzania, Zambia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The region is this year facing threat of an El Nino-induced
drought. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Proposes Conclusion of EU-US Veterinary Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BRUSSELS, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission, the
European Union (EU)'s executive body, today decided to conclude
its veterinary agreement with the United States for animals and
animal products.
</P>
<P>
The objective of the agreement is to facilitate the trade of
live animals and animal products by establishing a mechanism for
the recognition of equivalent sanitary measures on both sides.
</P>
<P>
The proposal, which will be put to the European Council of
Ministers for final approval, was put forward by Franz Fischler,
EU commissioner for agriculture and rural development, according
to a press release issued Wednesday in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
The recognition by an importing country of sanitary measures
applied by an exporting country could permit greater efficient
utilization of inspection and verification, the EU noted.
</P>
<P>
Mr. Fischler's proposal includes lists of those commodities
for which equivalence is recognized.
</P>
<P>
The total trade between the EU and the U.S. in the products
covered by this draft agreement for 1995 was about 1.5 billion
U.S. dollars in each direction.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations of similar agreements are under way with New
Zealand, the Czech Republic, Australia, Canada, Uruguay, Chile and
Argentina. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
