<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EMU Seen 90 Percent Likely to Be Launched in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 12 (Xinhua) -- European Economic and Monetary
Union (EMU) is 90 percent likely to be launched on time, a Reuters
poll showed today.
</P>
<P>
This is the highest prediction since the survey began a year
ago, according to the mean prediction from 47 Europe-based
economists and think-tanks.
</P>
<P>
As EMU's chances reached new heights, the likelihood of more
countries joining in the first wave on January 1999 also climbed,
the survey, conducted between November 5 and 10, showed.
</P>
<P>
All 47 experts said that Spain and Portugal would like to join
EMU in the first wave.
</P>
<P>
Italy's chances have soared over the past year. Just 7 percent
of respondents saw Italy in the first wave in November 1996 -- now
that figure has soared to 91 percent in the latest survey.
</P>
<P>
Finland has always been a likely member, although one
contributor to the poll still felt it would fail to make the grade
in January 1999.
</P>
<P>
But most polled experts felt Finland would choose to enter
along with Austria, Belgium, France, Germany, Ireland, Italy,
Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Spain and Portugal.
</P>
<P>
Only Sweden, Britain, Denmark and Greece were deemed no-hopers
in the race to join EMU in 1999.
</P>
<P>
British Finance Minister Gordon Brown has effectively ruled out
British membership during the current parliament. But he told
business leaders Monday that the government would act so that
Britain could join EMU soon after the next election -- due by 2002
-- if it wanted to.
</P>
<P>
The Labor government has promised to hold a referendum on the
issue, but Britons are traditionally Euro-sceptic and many experts
feel it will be an uphill battle to convince the country to sign
up to a single currency in 2002.
</P>
<P>
Denmark has already opted out of EMU while the Swedish
government has said it does not plan to join from the start,
leaving the door open for eventual membership later. The survey
showed they too were likely to join three years after the launch
of EMU.
</P>
<P>
Greece sees itself joining the single currency by the end of
2001 and experts in the survey believed it to join EMU in summer
of that year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
