<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Somali Doctors Offer to Help Flood Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, November 12 (Xinhua) -- A group of doctors today
announced that they would volunteer to serve the flood victims in
Southern Somalia as the heavy rains of the Deyr season continue
with rivers bursting their banks.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting by the medical staff of Dr Hassan Jiis Memorial
Hospital, the doctors have unanimously agreed to send five
doctors and 15 nurses to southern Somalia in an effort to save
the lives of hundreds of thousands of flood victims by providing
emergency medical assistance.
</P>
<P>
However, the doctors underlined that the essential drugs and
logistics are beyond the capacity of their hospital.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Abdi Mohamed Elmi Hangul, the director of the hospital,
said his team is the first to respond to what he called the human
holocaust resulted from the floods and the endemic malaria.
</P>
<P>
Hangul appealed to the international community to assist them
with tents, medicine and food to help the flood victims.
</P>
<P>
In a similar response, a local Islamic committee for the
coordination of the humanitarian efforts has called on Somali
scholars to start a campaign to collect food, clothes and
house-hold utensils for the flood victims of the country.
</P>
<P>
The committee has urged the flood-affected villagers to form
their own committees to coordinate the humanitarian efforts.
"Moslems should not remain back seated and wait for international
assistance all the time," said a statement issued in Mogadishu
today.
</P>
<P>
The statement signed by three Moslem scholars said the Sheikhs
should start a public awareness campaign with the participation
of the women groups and the business community. "the women should
volunteer to walk from house to house to collect what each family
can afford," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The floods in the Southern regions of Somalia are believed to
have affected nearly one million people and claimed the lives of
more than 100 people including children and the elderly since the
beginning of the Deyr season more than a month ago.
</P>
<P>
Both Jubba and Shabelle, the two rivers of Somalia, have burst
their banks and destroyed dozens of riverside villages and
thousands of hectares of farmland.
</P>
<P>
The largest affected town so far is Beledweyne where the fate
of 170 patients in the main hospital remains unknown.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that serious public reaction is
attracted since the Ethiopian fighting with the Al-Itihad Moslen
fundamentalists became dormant early in the year when the mosques
in the capital called for Holy Jihad against the "Ethiopian
invaders". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
