<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Full Text of Li's Speech at Reception in Tokyo (Part Two) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China and Japan, close neighbors separated by only a strip of
water, are important countries in Asia and the world. With
profound changes in the world and the growing trend of
multipolarization, China and Japan should establish and develop
long-term, stable and friendly cooperative ties, which are not
only in the fundamental interests of the two peoples, but
conducive to peace and development in the Asia-Pacific region and
the world at large. China and Japan should treat their relations
from a long-term and strategic perspective and guide the
developmental direction of their ties. I think the basic
principles of guiding the development of Sino-Japanese ties should
read as follows:
</P>
<P>
-- Mutual respect and non-interference into each other's
internal affairs. Respect the other's choice of its developing
path, which is made according to its national conditions. Surpass
the differences of the two countries on social systems, values and
ideologies. Develop bilateral friendly ties on the basis of the
Five Principles of Peaceful Coexistence.
</P>
<P>
-- To seek common ground while reserving differences, and
properly handle the differences. Strictly adhere to the principles
enshrined in the Sino-Japanese Joint Statement and the China-Japan
Treaty of Peace and Friendship. Remove disturbances, properly
solve the existing problems and problems likely to occur in the
future between the two countries through peaceful consultations
and from a strategic perspective of maintaining friendly ties
between the two countries. The differences between the two
countries should not become obstacles in the way of developing
bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
-- To increase dialogues and promote mutual
understanding. Increase the dialogues and exchanges between the
two countries at all levels and in different fields. Enhance
mutual trust and expand common understanding through timely
exchanges of views on issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
-- Mutual benefit and developing economic cooperation. Expand
the economic and trade cooperation between the two countries from
a long-term perspective and on the basis of equality and mutual
benefit. Further raise the level of cooperation and achieve common
development through an exchange of each other's experience and
advantages.
</P>
<P>
-- To look into the future and develop bilateral friendship
from generation to generation. Carry forward the tradition of
friendly cooperation between the two countries and educate the
young generation with correct historic concepts so as to have the
Sino-Japanese friendship passed on from generation to generation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
