<HEADLINE> Mandela to Visit Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 12 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela will visit Saudi Arabia at the weekend, the
Department of Foreign Affairs said today.
</P>
<P>
The scheduled visit, from November 16 to 17, is aimed at
promoting trade and investment, the president's office said, but
declined to give details.
</P>
<P>
Public Enterprises Minister Stella Sigcau, Defense Minister
Joe Modise and Mineral and Energy Affairs Minister Penuell Maduna
will accompany Mandela during his visit to Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
In addition to meeting Saudi Monarch King Fahd, Mandela will
also meet other members of the royal family and other senior
government ministers.
</P>
<P>
Sigcau, Modise, Maduna and Deputy Foreign Affairs Minister
Aziz Pahad would in turn discuss various issues of bilateral
concern with their Saudi counterparts, the Foreign Affairs
Department said.
</P>
<P>
Relations between South Africa and Saudi Arabia had improved
significantly since the establishment of diplomatic relations in
October 1994, it noted.
</P>
<P>
Local press earlier this year reported that South Africa was
offering to buy oil from Saudi Arabia as a counter trade
arrangement in a proposed seven billion Rand (146 million U.S.
Dollars) arms deal, but neither government has confirmed this.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the volume of trade between the two
countries has increased fourfold from 251 million Rand (more than
50 million U.S. Dollars) in 1994 to 1.36 billion Rand (283
million U.S. Dollars) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia is also becoming increasingly important as a
supplier of crude oil to South Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
