<HEADLINE> Iraq: More US Violations of Air Space </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Iraq said today that there
have been an escalated violations by U.S. war and spy planes of
its air space.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference here, Foreign Minister Mohammed Saeed
al-Sahhaf also called for Arab support for Iraq in the
Iraq-U.S. standoff and accused the U.S. for blackmailing the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
There have been 984 violations of air space in both north and
south Iraq by U.S. planes since 29 October, he said, adding a TR-1
spy plane has joined the U2 reconnaissance plane already in
operation over Iraq in a daily mission.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that Iraq will shoot down one of the planes if
necessary.
</P>
<P>
He has sent letters to the United Nations in protest against
such escalation of sovereignty breaches against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister called for Arabs' awareness of the
U.S. "dangerous games" which is blamed for the current crisis in
the region.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has announced to expel U.S. citizens of the U.N. inspection
team in charge of destruction of mass destructive weapons saying
they are spys, but its has suspended action pending a
U.N. position towards the crisis. The U.S. has threatened with
military action and been pushing for a Security Council resolution
denouncing Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. is creating such a crisis to divert people's
attention from listening to Iraq's just call for lifting of the
seven-year-old U.N. sanctions which were imposed after the 1990
invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
He said Arab countries like Egypt, Jordan and Syria have
adopted very good stance in support of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Sahhaf also called on Arab countries not to allow the U.S. to
use their territories as bases for launching attacks on Iraq. He
expressed appreciation to a number of countries which have refused
to let the U.S. to do so.
</P>
<P>
He also said that his country is in contact with U.N. Security
Council members, who have complained of "blackmailing and
pressure" from the U.S. for reaching a resolution hostile to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraq will "definitely" expel American inspectors if the
Security Council reaches a tough resolution toward it, he said,
but without giving details.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. sanctions cannnot be lifted until the inspectors
verify that Iraq has eliminated all its weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
He also said Iraq is ready to "answer any U.S. aggression,"
adding history has proved that U.S. would launch an aggression
against another country without permission from anyone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
