<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Final Efforts Being Made for Diplomatic Solution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Diplomats are still
making their final consultations for a diplomatic solution to the
arms inspection crisis in Iraq although the United Nations
Security Council is going to meet this noon to schedule a vote on
a draft resolution on imposing new measures against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of some of the Security Council members have
been persuading Iraq to rescind an order late last month to expel
Americans from the U.N. arms inspection team.
</P>
<P>
They have also insisted that Security Council resolution
contain no use or threat of military forces to punish Iraq for its
order.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Anne Gazeau-Secret stressed
earlier in the day that the U.N. resolution "does not in any way
foresee the use of force" against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Sergey Lavrov, Russian ambassador to the United Nations, said
late Tuesday that Russia "cannot accept any use of force because
it leads us nowhere."
</P>
<P>
But the United States and Britain have been making efforts to
persuade other Security Council members to join their
condemnations against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-Britain draft resolution condemns Iraq's actions,
including threatening to shoot down American-piloted U-2 spy
planes operating in support of the U.N. weapons inspection team.
</P>
<P>
It demands that Iraq rescind its decision and cooperate
unconditionally with the U.N. Special Commission in charge of
scrapping Iraq's chemical, biological and missile stocks under the
1991 Gulf War cease-fire agreement.
</P>
<P>
The two states are also seeking to impose a travel ban on Iraqi
officials responsible for disrupting U.N. weapons inspections in
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
However, Iraq said earlier today that it would not bow to an
"oppressive" U.N. resolution.
</P>
<P>
Underlining its resolve, Iraqi officials have reportedly barred
for the ninth time in 10 days American members of the U.N.
monitoring teams from taking part in its work.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has said that the ban on Americans would remain unless
inspectors were neutral and a timetable was set for lifting the
U.N. sanctions imposed when Iraq invaded Kuwait in 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
