<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Full Text of Li's Speech at Reception in Tokyo (Part Three) Friends, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
We are at a historically important turn of the century. Society
has experienced unforgettable times in the 20th century. Two world
wars left deep wounds and misfortune to mankind. The postwar
period saw civil wars and turmoil and many other regional
conflicts accompanied by a Cold War that lasted more than 40 years.
</P>
<P>
People of the whole world have paid a heavy price for pursuing
and defending peace. To our great comfort, the world has scored a
great economic victory overall in development and social progress
during the postwar decades.
</P>
<P>
Though the Cold War has ended, the world is still far from
peaceful as irrational international political and economic
disorder remains. The relations between the North and the South
hemispheres have not been improved and many countries are still
undeveloped with their people living in poverty and deplorable
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
Thus peace and development are not only the theme of today's
world but also the world of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
China, the biggest developing country, and Japan, a developed
country, should enhance their coordination and cooperation in
regional and world affairs to contribute to peace and development
regionally and in the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
It is good for all nations that Japan chose a way of peaceful
development after World War II. It scored economic success and saw
its status in the international community enhanced.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Violence Still Rampant in Karachi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The killing of four American
citizens and their Pakistani driver by unidentified gunmen in
Karachi today has sounded a fresh warning that violence is still
rampant in Pakistan's largest city.
</P>
<P>
The violent incident occurred at 8:20 a.m. in the southern port
city, and the five dead were identified as the employees of Union
Texas Pakistan (UTP), a subsidiary of Union Texas Petroleum
Holdings Inc.
</P>
<P>
Sources from Karachi said the four Americans, who were on a
visit in connection with some official work at the company, were
shot dead on their way from Karachi Sheraton Hotel to their office
about three kilometers away.
</P>
<P>
According to eyewitnesses, the attackers were in a red Honda
Civic, which was later found abandoned in the south of the city.
</P>
<P>
The incident came only one day after a 12-member American jury
declared a Pakistani national, Aimal Kansi, guilty of killing two
agents of the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) and wounding three
others in a shooting outside the CIA Headquarters in January 1993.
</P>
<P>
It is still unknown whether this incident has something to do
with the conviction of Kansi by the U.S. jury. An investigation is
under way and The Karachi police force has been put on full alert.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's Federal Cabinet, chaired by Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif, met here this afternoon to discuss the tragic incident.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet, voicing its shock and anguish over the attack,
directed the Sindh Provincial government to take all necessary
steps to track down the attackers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Pakistani President Farooq Leghari strongly
condemned the killing as a "despicable act" and said the
government is determined to arrest the gunmen.
</P>
<P>
"We are determined to apprehend the criminals swiftly and award
them severe punishment," Leghari said in a condolence message to
U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Sharif, in a message to Clinton, also strongly
condemned the "act of terrorism" and said he was deeply shocked to
learn of the incident.
</P>
<P>
"We will spare no endeavor to apprehend and punish the
perpetrators of this heinous crime," Sharif said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan said Pakistani authorities
"will leave no stone unturned in apprehending the criminals who
carried out this dastardly act and exemplary punishment would be
given to them."
</P>
<P>
A. G. Hoffman, president of Union Texas Pakistan, has termed
the killing of five of its employees as "terrible and tragic."
</P>
<P>
The company does not know the reason behind the attack, said
Hoffman, adding that his company is fully cooperating with local
officials in their investigation.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Embassy officials here declined to make any comment on the
killing, saying only that they were still gathering details of the
incident.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Karachi Stock Exchange (KSE) 100-Index plunged
across the board on the news of the killing this morning.
</P>
<P>
KSE 100-Index fell by 39.43 points to 1,827.07 as prices of 79
companies dipped and only 28 were up.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Large Majority of UK Voters Back Privacy Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Nearly nine out of 10 British
people support a privacy law to protect public figures against
media intrusion, according to an opinion poll published today.
</P>
<P>
The new Guardian/ICM poll, which interviewed a random sample of
1,200 adults across the country, showed that 87 percent to 10
percent voters back a privacy law.
</P>
<P>
It also found that nearly six out of 10 people think the
current system of self-regulation operated by the Press Complaints
Commission is not working, indicating that people's resentment
against tabloids has not diminished in the two months since
Princess Diana's death.
</P>
<P>
As to the question of who should be protected by such a new
law, more than 80 percent believe the private lives of the royal
family in particular should be included.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some 55 percent to 42 percent also believe that the
private lives of public figures such as pop stars and celebrities
should be given the protection of the law.
</P>
<P>
However, a clear majority said that the private lives of
politicians and crime suspects should not be protected.
</P>
<P>
The poll also showed that some 55 percent now think Britain
would be worse off without the royal family, compared with only 48
percent in August, but still far short of the 70 percent plus
support given to the royals as recently as in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
