<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada to Have "Virtual" National Securities Commission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Canada's provincial securities
regulators are prepared to set up a "virtual" national securities
commission by the end of next year, a report said today.
</P>
<P>
Now they are in the process of harmonizing many of their rules
and procedures, and designing a national framework for mutual
reliance.
</P>
<P>
A memorandum of understanding is expected to be signed next
spring, with the new initiatives to be in effect by the end of
next year, the Financial Post newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
That would mean many areas previously handled provincially,
such as prospectus review, registration of brokers and dealers,
exemption applications, will be consistent and run by a lead
regulator with the help of improved technology.
</P>
<P>
The virtual commission will achieve most of the efficiences
that would have been obtained through a national securities
commission, an idea that has been talked for some 30 years but has
yet to find enough political support.
</P>
<P>
Stock trading in Canada is now regulated by 12 jurisdictions,
making it heavily relied on local regulators.
</P>
<P>
The virtual national securities commission will help eliminate
inefficiencies while preserve the role of local regulators to deal
with local market issues, according to Bill Hess, chairman of the
Alberta Securities Commission.
</P>
<P>
For investors, it will mean more protection, since provincial
commissions can free up resources that are duplicating efforts of
other jurisdictions and enhance enforcement and compliance, Hess
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
