<HEADLINE> Angola to Train Congo (K) Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Angola would help train rapid
intervention police and frontier police for Democratic Congo (K)
starting from the later half of the month, a senior official said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Pitra Retroff, Angola's Internal Minister revealed this news
to reporters before he left Luanda for a Lusaka visit.
</P>
<P>
Retroff said that they are doing this to guarantee the safety
and peace along their border, adding that an official from the
Internal Ministry of Congo (K) had paid a visit to Angola to
acquaint himself with the specific conditions for the training.
</P>
<P>
He said the training program was outlined in a cooperation
agreement between Angola and Congo (K) during Congolese President
Laurent Kabila's first visit to Angola on August 5-6.
</P>
<P>
Retroff, who is to attend the defense and security conference
of the Southern African Development Community (SADC) in Lusaka,
said he would brief the participants on the current situation of
Angola's peace process and appeal to them to cooperate with
Angola in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He said the situation along the government controlled borders
is peaceful and stable, but things are quite different along the
northern and northeastern boundaries with Congo (K).
</P>
<P>
Unidentified aircraft have been spotted flying over the
northern and noutheastern parts of the country bordering Zambia,
which is under the control of the former rebel movement of the
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola, he said.
</P>
