<HEADLINE> France Denies Interfering in Algeria's Internal Affairs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, November 12 (Xinhua) -- France today denied that it had
interfered into the internal affairs of Algeria with the holding
of "One Day for Algeria" demonstrations in Paris and other French
cities Monday by tens of thousands of French people in support of
Algerian people.
</P>
<P>
"It is the solidarity which should be our primary priority
toward Algeria," said French Minister for European Affairs Pierre
Moscovici.
</P>
<P>
The Algerian government has expressed regret that the French
government actually "supported" the demonstrations which were
initiatived by non-governmental groups of France to show
solidarity of the French people with the Algerian people.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators, called by trade unions, humanitarian
organizations and associations, also urged the international
community to launch an inquiry into the massacres of civilians in
Algeria.
</P>
<P>
"What is clear today is that the French society expresses its
most entire solidarity with the Algerian people. It did it under
the form of associations. It is not interference but well and
truly solidarity," said Moscovici.
</P>
<P>
French government spokeswoman Catherine Trautmann and a Foreign
Ministry spokeswoman had expressed support to the demonstrations,
triggering criticism from the Algerian government, who said that
it contradicted with the repeated promise by France not to
interfere into the internal affairs of Algeria.
</P>
<P>
Moscovici recalled that the French government had never ceased
to condemn terrorism and what he called "blind violence which is
striking Algeria."
</P>
<P>
He said that the Algerian people were subjected to murder and
sufferings, and they hoped more than ever to be living in peace.
</P>
<P>
"They need protection and security. We don't know what is going
on in Algeria. We need more information, transparency and that
comes first and foremost by the possibility that foreign media
work more (in Algeria)," said the minister.
</P>
<P>
He said that "non-interference, solidarity, transparency and
security" were the principles which would guide France in its
policy toward Algeria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
