<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guiding Principles of Development of China-Japan Ties Noted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng, who is
on a six-day official good-will visit to Japan, today pointed out
several basic principles of guiding the development of China-Japan
ties.
</P>
<P>
Delivering a speech here at a welcoming reception jointly held
by Japan-China friendship organizations, Li Peng said that the
first principle is mutual respect and non-interference in each
other's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
The two countries should respect each other's choice regarding
the paths of development, which are made according to the
country's national conditions, Li said.
</P>
<P>
The differences between the two countries' social systems,
values and ideologies should be surpassed and development of
bilateral friendly ties should be based on the Five Principles of
Peaceful Coexistence, he added.
</P>
<P>
The second principle is to seek common ground while reserving
differences, and to handle the differences properly, Li said.
</P>
<P>
The two countries must strictly adhere to the principles
enshrined in the Sino-Japanese Joint Statement and the China-Japan
Treaty of Peace and Friendship, the Chinese premier noted.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng called for the removal of disturbances between the two
countries and the proper settlement of problems through peaceful
consultations and from a strategic perspective of maintaining
China-Japan friendly ties.
</P>
<P>
"The differences between the two countries should not become
obstacles in the way of developing bilateral relations," he added.
</P>
<P>
The third principle is to increase dialogue and promote mutual
understanding, Li said.
</P>
<P>
The two countries should increase dialogue and exchanges at all
levels and in different fields, and enhance mutual trust and
expand common understanding through timely exchanges of views on
issues of common concern, he added.
</P>
<P>
The fourth principle is to develop bilateral economic
cooperation on the basis of equality and mutual benefit, Li said.
</P>
<P>
The two countries should expand their economic and trade
cooperation from a long-term perspective and further raise the
level of cooperation through an exchange of each other's
experience and advantages, he added.
</P>
<P>
The fifth principle is to carry forward the tradition of
friendly cooperation between the two countries and educate the
young generation with correct historic concepts so as to have the
Sino-Japanese friendship passed on from generation to generation,
Li said.
</P>
<P>
Emphasizing the importance of China and Japan in Asia and the
world, Li said that with profound changes in the world and the
growing trend of multipolarization, the two countries should
establish and develop long-term, stable and friendly cooperative
ties.
</P>
<P>
"Such relations are not only in the fundamental interests of
the two peoples, but conducive to peace and development in the
Asia-Pacific region and the world," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Should Pay Down National Debt: OECD </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Canada should use its budget
surplus to begin paying down its massive national debt, said the
Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD).
</P>
<P>
In its latest survey of the Canadian economy, the OECD noted
that the country's federal and provincial governments are well on
their way to balancing their annual fiscal deficit and surpluses
may start to emerge.
</P>
<P>
Canada now leads the Group of Seven countries in terms of the
federal government's fiscal performance. Before the 1990s, its
fiscal record was the worst in the G7.
</P>
<P>
Canada has a national debt of 600 billion dollars (430 billion
US dollars). Its debt-to-GDP ratio, which stood at 73.1 percent at
the end of March, is the third highest among OECD countries.
</P>
<P>
"Given the relatively high level of public debt... priority
should be given to using these surpluses to put the ratio on a
clear downward trend," the organization said.
</P>
<P>
A lower debt-to-GDP ratio would reduce the risk premium on
Canada's debt and its vulnerability to future economic shocks.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian government has said that the debt-to-GDP ratio
will be lowered over time by running balanced budgets in the near
future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
