<HEADLINE> Lebanon Imposes Military Rule Against Revolt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The Lebanese government today
decided to impose a three-month military rule in eastern region
of Baalbek-Hermel as of today in a bid to crush a
four-month-old anti-government revolt.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made at today's three-hour cabinet session
chaired by Prime Minister Rafik Hariri and in the presence of
President Elias Hrawi.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, the president said that it is unacceptable
to call for civil disobedience mutiny. He warned parliamentary
members and cabinet ministers not to visit the Bekka-Hermel
region.
</P>
<P>
He referred to radical Shitte Muslim cleric Sheikh Sobhi
Tufaili who is leading the civil disobedience mutiny which started
on July 4.
</P>
<P>
Tufaili, former general secretary of pro-Iranian Hezbollah,
accused the government of neglecting the impoverished rural
areas and focusing the attention mainly on large cities.
</P>
<P>
He called on the residents in the Baalbek-Hermel to refuse to
pay electricity bills and occupy public properties.
</P>
<P>
Over the weekend, his self-styled "hunger revolt" came to a
head-on collision with the government when he sent his followers
to set up checkpoints on all approaches of Baalbek, declaring
an entry ban against Hariri and his 29 cabinet ministers as well
as "unsympathetic" parliament members.
</P>
<P>
"The move aims at grabbing the whole region from the
government and the Lebanese people," Hrawi said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the situation compels us to take action to
prevent any activity from threatening the country's stability
and security.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese Arabic-language radio The Orient said that the
leaders of the government will meet again within the next two
weeks to discuss an emergency U.S. aid worth 100 million
U.S. dollars to the region in order to balance the military
crackdown. 
</P>
</TEXT>
