<HEADLINE> SPD-Greens Coalition Government Takes Over in Hamburg </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Social Democrat (SPD) Ortwin
Runde was today elected new mayor of the northern German
city-state of Hamburg, heading a coalition government with the
envonmentalist Greens.
</P>
<P>
This makes Hamburg the fifth out of 16 federal states ruled
now by alliance of the two German opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
Runde's cabinet will have eight SPD ministers, three Greens
ministers and one independent member. The two parties signed the
coalition agreement last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Runde succeeded outgoing veteran SPD mayor Henning Voscherau,
who stepped down after the SPD received its worst postwar result
in regional elections in Hamburg, which used to be its northern
stronghold.
</P>
<P>
The SPD saw its share of the vote in the September elections
down to 36.2 percent. Chancellor Helmut Kohl's Christian
Democratic Party (CDU) obtained 30.7 percent of the vote while the
Greens won 13.9 percent. All the other parties failed to meet the
5 percent mark to qualify for representation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
