<HEADLINE> Sudan Govt Rejects Confederation Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese government
negotiators, led by Foreign Minister Ali Osman Mohammad Taha,
today rejected rebel's demand for forming a north-south
confederation in Sudan where civil war has lasted for 14 years.
</P>
<P>
The proposal, presented by the Sudan People's Liberation Army
(SPLA) at the talks with the government which started here on
October 29 and ending Tuesday, is "irrelevant and illogical",
Taha said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
"This demand is illogical because the concept of confederalism
can only exist between sovereign states but Sudan is still one
country," he said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The talks, the first since 1994, lasted nearly two weeks with
only one agreement reached by the two sides -- The peace talks is
to resume in April next year.
</P>
<P>
"Talks have been a positive exercise whereby the bottom line
of each side has been investigated, but not yet clearly marked.
The exchange of views here will definitely help," Taha said.
</P>
<P>
At the talks brokered by the Inter-Governmental Authority of
Development (IGAD), Khartoum accepted the principle of
self-determination as a means of resolving the 14-year conflict,
but asking a federation instead of confederation.
</P>
<P>
Peace talks on Sudan stalled in 1994 when Khartoum refused to
accept an IGAD-drafted document containing the principle of
self-determination for south Sudan, but recent military defeats
and international pressures forced it back to the negotiating
table late September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
