<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Meets Senior Japanese Statesmen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese Premier Li peng
met with a group of senior Japanese statesmen and the relatives of
some late Japanese officials here today.
</P>
<P>
Quoting a Chinese saying which means not to forget those who
dug the well when drinking water, Li said China and Japan can not
develop without those who made great efforts to the normalization
of relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Li, who is on a six-day official good-will visit to Japan, said
it was former Prime Ministers Kakuei Tanaka and Ohira Masayoshi
who worked with the late Chinese leaders Mao Zedong and Zhou Enlai
to realize the normalization of ties. Former Chief Cabinet
Secretary Nikaido Susumu did a lot to help realize the
normalization of China-Japan relations, he added.
</P>
<P>
Also, Li reminded the effort of Mr. Takasaki Tatsunosuke who
helped forge the trade ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Li said it is because "there are many friends who strived for
Sino-Japanese friendship" that bilateral relations have developed
so far.
</P>
<P>
In the future, he went on to say, a younger generation should be
nurtured and educated to carry on the cause of the Sino-Japanese
friendship. He expressed the hope that the old friends and their
relatives can make their contributions in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Eighty-eight-year-old Susumu, who participated in the
negotiations between Japan and China on the normalization of ties,
said he will continue to work for Japan-China friendship.
</P>
<P>
Those who were present at the meeting also included former
Chairman of the Komei Party Takeiri Yoshikatsu, and the relatives
of former Prime Minister Masayoshi, former advisor of Japan-China
Association on Economy and Trade Okazaki Kaheita. 
</P>
</TEXT>
