<HEADLINE> France: Measures on Iraq Must Be Decided by UN Council </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, November 12 (Xinhua) -- France today insisted that any
new decision on Iraq must be taken within the framework of the
United Nations Security Council, after the U.N. council adopted a
watered down resolution on Iraq Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Anne Gazeau-Secret said
that the resolution adopted by the Security Council does not
"predict in any way the use of force" against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The resolution called for the tightening of sanctions on Iraq,
including the banning of travel abroad by some Iraqi leaders, but
dropped a warning of "serious consequences" against Iraq for its
expulsion of Americans from the U.N. inspection team of Iraq's
disarmament.
</P>
<P>
France has expressed several times its opposition to any use of
force against Iraq, while the United States and Britain have
warned Iraq of military actions.
</P>
<P>
"For our part, we estimate that any new measure (against Iraq)
should be taken uniquely in the framework of the (Security)
Council, and should be proportioned" to Iraqi cooperation with the
U.N. over disarmament, said the spokeswoman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
