<HEADLINE> Jordan Calls for Timetable to Lift Sanctions on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Jordan today urged the United
Nations Security Council to hammer out a timetable to lift the
sanctions imposed on Iraq since its invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Such a timetable was needed to convince the Iraqi leadership
that the sanctions would be lifted when it had complied with the
relevant U.N. resolutions, said Jordanian Foreign Minister Fayez
Tarawneh at a joint press conference with the visiting Canadian
Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy.
</P>
<P>
Tarawneh contended that this kind of timetable would help solve
the current crisis between Iraq and the United Sates.
</P>
<P>
Iraq decided on October 29 to expel the U.S. inspectors on the
U.N. weapons inspection teams overseeing the disarmament of Iraq.
And the U.S. had threatened to strike Iraq with force if Iraq took
actions against American inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Tarawneh said that Jordan opposed tightening the sanctions or
any military actions against Baghdad as they would affect the
Iraqi and Jordanian peoples as well as peace and security in the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
He called for continuous dialog instead of continuous sanctions
in a bid to solve the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Axworthy said that Canada would support any decision by the
U.N. Security Council to implement its resolutions and especially
supported the oil-for-food deal which helped the Iraqi people ease
their hardship.
</P>
<P>
Axworthy arrived here today for a short visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
