<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Central Bank Denies Speculations About Gold Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The German central bank, the
Bundesbank, today denied speculations that it is planning to sell
parts of its gold reserves, but admitted for the first time that
it would lend some of them.
</P>
<P>
In the runup to the 1999 start of the planned single European
currency, the Euro, the sale of the Bundesbank's gold reserve or
only a debate about this issue would be "psychologically
disastrous," said Bundesbank Vice President Johann Wilhelm Gaddum.
</P>
<P>
His remarks were made in reaction to speculations among gold
dealers in London that the Bundesbank was considering to join the
Belgian and Dutch central banks in selling parts of its gold
reserves.
</P>
<P>
The Bundesbank, however, confirmed today for the first time
that like other central banks it was participating in the gold
lending business.
</P>
<P>
But it declined to disclose how much of its 3,700 tons of gold
reserves would be lent, saying only it would only be "a limited
amount" used to help cover the costly holding of the gold
reserves.
</P>
<P>
Some German news reports said that the Bundesbank would
probably lend about 10 percent of the reserves to other central
bank, mining companies as well as jewelry makers.
</P>
<P>
At an average annual rate of 2 percent, the deals would yield
about 70 million U.S. dollars for the bank.
</P>
<P>
German Finance Minister Theo Waigel had proposed earlier this
year to sell parts of Germany's gold reserves to help the country
meet the strict qualification criteria to join the Euro.
</P>
<P>
But the plan was dropped eventually after meeting a storm of
outcries in Europe with critics condemning the move as a financial
trickery which would risk confidence in the Euro. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
