<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany's Trade With Africa Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The German Economics Ministry
said today that Germany's trade with Africa rose in the first
half of this year, with exports up 6.6 percent and imports up
nearly 10 percent compared to the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
German exports to Africa during the period were totaled 8
billion marks (4.7 billion U.S. dollars), while imports from
Africa increased to just over 8 billion marks.
</P>
<P>
Crude oil accounts for some 40 percent of Germany's imports
from Africa. Other main imports are cocoa, coffee, fruits and
gold.
</P>
<P>
South Africa remained Germany's biggest trading partner in
Africa. In the first six months of this year, German exports to
South Africa grew by some 3 percent to 2.8 billion marks while
imports reached 1.7 billion marks, up some 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
Libya became Germany's second biggest trading partner thanks to
an 18 percent increase in oil exports, which totaled over 1.5
billion marks. German exports to Libya were up 2.6 percent to
reach 447 million marks during the period.
</P>
<P>
Egypt followed Libya in trade with Germany, with imports from
Germany up 11 percent to 1.3 billion marks but exports to Germany
down 5 percent to 240 million marks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
