<HEADLINE> Toyota Invited to Set up Assembly Plant in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Japan's automobile giant Toyota
has been invited to establish an assembly plant in Nigeria, the
News Agency of Nigeria reported today.
</P>
<P>
The invitation was extended to Toyota Nigeria Limited at the
17th Lagos International Trade Fair by Colonel Mohammed Marwa,
the military administrator of Lagos State.
</P>
<P>
The administrator said such a move will enable Toyota to take
advantage of the huge market in the west Africa sub-region.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's automobile market had been dominated, until a few
years ago, by Peugeot cars from France, which has been operating
an assembly plant in Nigeria since 1977.
</P>
<P>
However, Japanese cars have been taking a large share of the
market from Peugeot over the recent years. A proof of this is the
establishment of the Toyota Nigeria Limited in 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to officials from the Peugeot Automobile Nigeria
Limited, the company produced only 4,000 cars in 1996, compared
to 60,000 cars in the best years.
</P>
<P>
The slide of Peugeot's fortune in Nigeria, of course, is more
a result of a sustained economic depression than the competition
of Japanese cars.
</P>
<P>
During the oil boom period in the 1970s, automobile producers
from Britain, Germany, Italy and France all had their assembly
plants in Nigeria. Peugeot is one of the very few that are still
operating. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
