<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Minister Speaks on Foreign Trade Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Russia's foreign trade volume
decreased in the first quarter of 1997 for the country's
positions in the world market are vulnerable, Russian Minister
for Foreign Economic Relations Mikhail Fradkov said here today.
</P>
<P>
According to the Interfax, for the first time in the past four
years, Russia's foreign trade turnover in the first half of 1997
decreased by 4 percent on the respective period of 1996, the
minister said at a meeting of the Coordinating Council for Foreign
Trade.
</P>
<P>
Fradkov said exports declined by 2 percent while imports went
down by 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
In his opinion, exports decreased mainly because the situation
on the world market worsened for the export of raw materials, and
these unfavorable changes again confirmed that Russian exports
hinge on three products -- gas, oil and petroleum products --
therefore Russia is vulnerable on foreign markets.
</P>
<P>
Fradkov said that imports have decreased because the investment
activity in the country remains low, the domestic market has been
filled with imported goods and measures of tariff and nontariff
regulation on imports have been tightened in order to protect
domestic producers.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the import indicators in 1997 were lowered
"artificially." "The flow of imports via unregistered channels --
through the `Belarussian corridor' and `shuttle trade' -- has
increased considerably as a result of the complex of protective
and administrative measures taken by Russia at the end of 1996 and
the start of 1997," he added.
</P>
<P>
The pace of decline in exports and imports has slowed in the
second half of the year, Fradkov said.
</P>
<P>
On the prospects for foreign trade next year, he noted, "The
stimulating influence on foreign trade of economic stabilization
in Russia, an increase in its credit rating, the country's
admission into leading international organizations such as the
Paris and London clubs and the agreements on the rescheduling of
Russia's foreign debt."
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Fradkov said, "One should not forget that
Russian foreign trade will be impaired further by the low level of
industrial production, insufficient state support for the
development of the country's export potential, weak investment
activity on the domestic market, low competitiveness of national
industrial products and the exhaustion of extensive growth factors
with regard to the export of fuel and other raw materials."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
