<HEADLINE> US Expects Approval of Resolution Against Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The United States said
today that the U.N. Security Council would pass a strong
resolution against Iraq for its defiance to comply with U.N.
weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
"We are working on the wording and we are satisfied the
Security Council will have a very strong resolution that condemns
action by the government of Iraq and demands a new course of
action that will allow mandated U.N. inspections to go forward,"
White House spokesman Mike McCurry told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He said a vote on the resolution was expected in the Security
Council later today and now diplomats were consulting on the
phrasing of the resolution.
</P>
<P>
McCurry disclosed that in addition to travel restrictions on
Iraqi officials there were extra measures to be imposed on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"It will also have other restrictions placed on Iraqi officials
and will make clear that if that doesn't work, further measures
are indicated," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I believe this will be a strong, unanimous statement by the
world community that Iraq needs to comply with relevant Security
Council resolutions," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqis said today that it would not bow to any new
"oppressive" U.N. resolutions imposed on their country and would
continue to bar Americans from taking part in U.N. weapons
inspection teams' work unless inspectors were neutral and a
timetable was set for lifting U.N. sanctions imposed after the
1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
"Even if America is able to gain... a new oppressive resolution
of a vicious international cover to strike against Iraq, it would
not force it to retreat from its decision," Iraq's newspaper
al-Thawra said.
</P>
<P>
Several thousand Iraqis demonstrated in front of a U.N. office
in Baghdad today and more and more Iraqi families shouting "Down
with America!" flocked to the presidential palace, acting as human
shields in case of an attack by the United States on these venues.
</P>
