<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Talks on S. Leone Ends with Little Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The two-day talks with the
military junta on the restoration of civilian rule in the country
between the west African peacekeeping force (ECOMOG) and the
military junta ended today but disputes over major issues still
remain.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG Force Commander Major-General Victor Malu, who led the
ECOMOG team to the meeting in Freetown, capital of Sierra Leone,
was back at its headquarters in Monrovia, Liberia. He said the
meeting was successful.
</P>
<P>
But the junta said he was making propaganda, the British
Broadcasting Corporation reported.
</P>
<P>
According to Malu, the two sides have agreed on the
disarmament of Sierra Leone's various combatants beginning next
month.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the presence of Nigerian soldiers, who constitute
the bulk of the ECOMOG troops, will no longer be objected by the
Sierra Leonean side as before and will be deployed around that
country very soon, Malu said.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed on such major issues as the enforcement of
sanctions against the junta imposed by west African countries and
the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
"We all agreed on that," Malu said, adding that he was even
looking forward to moving the ECOMOG headquarters to Sierra Leone
from Monrovia, where the Liberian government wants ECOMOG to
leave.
</P>
<P>
But dispute remains over who are the combatants to be disarmed
and the deployment of Nigerian army in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG insists the Sierra Leonean army be disarmed along with
other militias in the country while the junta said the
constitutional army should not be included.
</P>
<P>
Major John Milton, assistant director of information of the
junta's ministry of defense, had another view on the two major
issues, complaining that Malu was providing misinformation and
making hostile propaganda.
</P>
<P>
He said the two parties had not categorily decided which
combatants should be disarmed and insisted that disarmament
should not cover the Sierra Leonean army.
</P>
<P>
"We did not agree on disarmament...and also we did not agree
on the domination of the Nigerian contingent in ECOMOG," he said.
</P>
<P>
The military junta has softpedalled its opposition to the
presence of Nigerian soldiers in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Milton said: "We are not opposed to the Nigerian deployment in
Sierra Leone. What we are opposed to is the dominance of Nigeria
in ECOMOG and also in the pursuance of peace in Sierra Leone."
</P>
<P>
According to him, the junta only wants to see an expanded
ECOMOG with Nigerian involvement, not Nigerian dominance.
</P>
<P>
However, observers noted that Nigeria, as a sub-regional
power, is now the only country in west Africa with human and
material resources for such peacekeeping operations in Sierra
Leone as it did before in Liberia.
</P>
<P>
This will make it natural for Nigeria to dominate ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
Under a peace agreement, the junta is to hand over power to
the civilian government it ousted in the May 25 coup six months
later.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is to search for modalities to implement the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
As views are so different from the two parties, observers
doubted whether the peace plan can be carried out smoothly and
earnestly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
