<HEADLINE> European Shares Down on Wall Street, Asian Slide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe
kept on a trend of decline and all ended in the negative today,
depressed by the slide on Wall Street and Asian markets as well as
by concerns on US interest rates.
</P>
<P>
British shares on the London market ended more than 70 points
down but off their lowest levels of the session as Wall Street
nerves steadied after an initial tumble.
</P>
<P>
Overnight weakness of the Asian markets knocked sentiment as
Tokyo's Nikkei index fell 2.7 percent while Hong Kong's Hang Seng
plunged another 3.9 percent, suggesting the turmoil is not yet
over.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE 100 index took little comfort from the Bank of
England's quarterly inflation report today, which was less hawkish
than expected, and closed down 73.3 points at 4,720.4.
</P>
<P>
The DAX-30 index in Frankfurt ended at 3,659.27, down 71.81
points. Dealers said that Asian markets' decline and a weaker
dollar weighed heavily on share prices.
</P>
<P>
On the Paris bourse, which resumed trading today after a
four-day break, the CAC-40 index clawed back their early losses to
close at 2,696.60, only 3.11 points lower. The market was also
unsettled by the fresh downturn on Asian markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
