<HEADLINE> Israel, PNA Near Agreement on Code of Conduct </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Israel and the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) are close to formulating a code of
conduct to advance the peace process, visiting Luxemburg Foreign
Minister Jacques Poos said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference after his meeting with Israeli
Foreign Minister David Levy, Poos, current rotating President of
the Council of European Union (EU), said that an agreement on
formulating the code of conduct which was proposed by the EU might
be reached in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
The code of conduct, which was proposed by EU foreign
ministers early last month, is aimed at safeguarding all that has
been achieved in the peace process and introducing
confidence-building measures to bolster the fight against
unilateral activities that might damage peace progress.
</P>
<P>
Poos said that as Israel was marking the second anniversary of
the assassination of late prime minister Yitzhak Rabin, he took
the opportunity to urge the Israeli government to follow in
Rabin's path to continue the Oslo process.
</P>
<P>
"Rabin was the initiator of the peace process and I would like
to pay him tributes today. I think it's up to us to continue his
work, because his work will bring security to all and prosperity
to all, if it is well done," he said.
</P>
<P>
Poos also voiced support to the United States' efforts to push
the peace talks forward. "Exactly, the United States and the EU
think alike that the peace process has to continue step by step to
bring about a lasting and just solution for all the peoples in the
region," he said.
</P>
<P>
Under the auspices of U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, Levy and PNA deputy Mahmoud Abbas met in Washington
early this month and agreed to continue sub-committee negotiations
in the region to discuss interim-status issues.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the Middle East and North Africa Economic
Conference to be held in Qatar next week, Levy said he has still
not decided whether to attend the meeting, stressing that he
wanted to ensure such trip will be successful.
</P>
<P>
The conference is facing a boycott by most Arab countries led
by regional powers like Egypt and Saudi Arabia due to Israeli
participation.
</P>
<P>
Poos will meet PNA President Yasser Arafat tonight and will
also visit Syria and Lebanon during his Middle East tour. 
</P>
</TEXT>
