<HEADLINE> All-Lebanon Strike Called for Tomorrow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, November 12 (Xinhua) -- All Lebanese have been called
on to take part in a general strike Thursday to demand payment
increase.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference today, Lebanese General Workers
Confederation (GWC) leader Ghanim Zoghbi demanded all citizens
from fishermen to students to walk out.
</P>
<P>
He said tomorrow is the day on which people can say "no" to the
government's indirect taxes collection, extravagance and waste,
and say "yes" for the workers' and teachers' pay rise demands.
</P>
<P>
The move was taken following the failure of GWC's negotiations
with the government and the associations of bankers,
industrialists and merchants over the demands, which include a
raise of the monthly minimum wage from 200 U.S. dollars to 300.
</P>
<P>
The associations rejected the labor demands and urged
employees to ignore the call for strike. But the union of bank
employees have said all its members will stay away from banks
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
The union of fishermen also said yes to the call for strike.
</P>
<P>
Zoghbi said that the strike will not mean the closure of
the door of negotiation, adding that the new round of talks
with the government and associations of employers will start
early next week.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he threatened that if no progress is seen, another
two-day strike will follow on November 25 and 26. 
</P>
</TEXT>
