<HEADLINE> US Ready for Strike on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The United States is ready
with a range of contingency options to make a strike on Iraq when
necessary, but has not decided when to take a military action or
what kind of action will be taken, Pentagon officials said today.
</P>
<P>
"There have been no decisions, no alerts, no deployments
orders," one of the officials said. But he said there is a "list
of options" noting that Washington had in the past quickly sent
radar-avoiding F-117A stealth jets, bombers and troops to the Gulf
area.
</P>
<P>
"We feel we have an adequate force there now," another official
said. He was referring to 17 U.S. warships and 200 warplanes in
the gulf region, mostly in Saudi Arabia and Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
They include the aircraft carrier Nimitz and seven ships armed
with long-range tomahawk cruise missiles.
</P>
<P>
Another aircraft carrier the George Washington might be sent
from the Mediterranean into the Red Sea or the Gulf in case for
re-enforcement, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, four U.N. F-16 fighter jets and six KC-135 tanker
aircraft have recently been sent to Incirlik Air Base in Turkey,
but Pentagon spokesman Army Lt. Col. Steve Campbell said the
increase in the U.S. air activity at Incirlik was not connected to
the standoff with Baghdad, but was to expand patroling of the
northern no-fly zone.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has vowed to shoot down any U-2 spy planes when they fly
its territorial air, which the Iraqis deem as the invasion of its
sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
The United States has also vowed to retaliate to Iraq's
attempt.
</P>
<P>
A U-2 resumed reconnaissance flight on an order from the United
Nations Monday after one week's suspension. It faced no challenge
from Iraq's aircraft defense system. And one Pentagon official
said another U-2 flight might be expected "within the next several
days." 
</P>
</TEXT>
