<HEADLINE> Tanzania Eyes Kenyan Electricity Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania may sell
electricity to Kenya once the 150 megawatts Songosongo gas-fueled
power project and the 350MW Kihansi hydro-electric power projects
are completed.
</P>
<P>
The Songosongo project and the first phase of the Kihansi
project which has an installed capacity of 180 MW, are slated to
go on line in 1999, today's Financial Times quoted energy experts
as saying.
</P>
<P>
When the two projects are completed, total capacity of the
national power grid of Tanzania will reach 700 MW, compared with
500 MW of demand at present, the experts said.
</P>
<P>
Supply will be in surplus of the national power demand, since
effective consumption stands at 350 MW and is not likely to
exceed 500 MW in two years, Energy Ministry sources said.
</P>
<P>
Samuel Sitta, Director General of the Tanzania Investment
Center, recently mentioned the possiblity of selling power to
Kenya in talks with his Kenyan counterpart, Dr Joseph arap N'gok.
</P>
<P>
Kenya, whose power consumption is steadily growing, imports
about 30 MW of electricty from Uganda at present. 
</P>
</TEXT>
