<HEADLINE> Developed Nations Urged to Contribute to Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Developed nations
should take concrete actions in support of developing countries'
efforts to eradicate poverty, A Chinese delegate said here today.
</P>
<P>
Wang Qun, Deputy Representative of the Chinese Delegation to
the Second Committee (Financial and Economic) of the U.N. General
Assembly, said the problem of imbalance in development came to the
fore and the number of people subject to poverty continued to
increase as the process of globalization accelerated.
</P>
<P>
The problem of poverty in the developing countries is largely
the result of unfortunate historical experiences and an
unfavorable external economic environment, Wang said, adding that
it is important to strengthen the international development
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Despite a consensus on poverty eradication and action programs,
the international community is lacking determination, political
will and concrete actions to implement such consensus and measures,
he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Delegation appeals to the international community,
developed nations in particular, to take actions to implement
consensus in the core areas of funds, debt, trade and for
developing countries in their efforts to eradicate poverty, Wang
went on.
</P>
<P>
He said the Chinese Government has attached great importance to
poverty alleviation and the number of people in poverty in China
has dropped to 5.8 million from 250 million as recorded in late
1970s. 
</P>
