<HEADLINE> Iran, UN Sign Agreement on Repatriation of Afghan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Iran and U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) signed an agreement here today
to speed up the repatriation of Afghan refugees in Iran.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian official news agency IRNA reported that the
agreement would allow Iran to identify and persuade Afghan
refugees living in the country to return home voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, Iran and UNHCR would collaborate
to ensure that the exit channels for the return home of Afghan
refugees in Iran would offer them better service. The two sides
would oversee more departures with better facilities and faster
services.
</P>
<P>
The agreement also anticipates establishment of air travel
facilities from destinations in Iran to Mazar-e-Sharif, northern
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Iranian officials at the Interior Ministry and the UNHCR
officials started a two-day discussion Tuesday on ways to
voluntarily repatriate Afghan refugees in the country.
</P>
<P>
Head of Tehran-based UNHCR office Pierre Bertrand said the
UNHCR is determined to find a basic solution to the problem of
Afghan refugees in Iran.
</P>
<P>
Over 3 million Afghans fled into Iran since 1979 and Iranian
authorities said that about 1.28 million Afghan refugees are
still living in Iran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Security Council Adopts Resolution on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Security Council today adopted a resolution, imposing new
sanctions on Iraq against its violations of relevant U.N.
resolutions in weapons inspections in the country.
</P>
<P>
All of the 15 members of the Security Council voted for the
resolution.
</P>
<P>
The resolution demands that Iraq rescind immediately its
October 29 decision to ban Americans from the U.N. Special
Commission in charge of scrapping Iraq's chemical, biological and
missile stocks (UNSCOM). Iraq has repeatedly alleged that the
American inspectors are spies aiming at prolonging the U.N.
sanctions against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The resolution demands that Iraq cooperate fully and
immediately, and without conditions or restrictions with the
Special Commission.
</P>
<P>
The resolution decides that U.N. member states shall without
delay prevent the entry into or transit through their territories
of all Iraqi officials and members of the Iraqi armed forces who
were responsible for or participated in the instances of
non-compliance.
</P>
<P>
The draft resolution was co-sponsored by the United States,
Britain, Chile, Costa Rica, Japan, Poland, Portugal, Republic of
Korea and Sweden.
</P>
<P>
In a debate prior to the voting, a number of U.N. member states
stressed their positions that the current arms inspection crisis
in Iraq should be resolved through diplomatic consultation instead
of using force or threatening to use force.
</P>
<P>
During their contacts with representatives of some of the
Security Council members, Iraqi officials insisted that Baghdad
would not rescind its order to expel the Americans from the
country unless the members of the U.N Special Commission became
neutral and the United Nations set a timetable for the lifting of
the sanctions on Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Holds State Memorial to Rabin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Memorial ceremonies marking
the Hebrew anniversary of the assassination of late Israeli Prime
Minister Yitzhak Rabin were held today through the country.
</P>
<P>
In the presence of his families, the Knesset (Parliament) held
here its special memorial session this afternoon for Rabin, who
was felled by a right-wing Jewish gunman at a peace rally on
November 4, 1995.
</P>
<P>
The meeting opened with a minute of silence and was addressed
by President Ezer Weizman, Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu,
opposition Labor Party Chairman Ehud Barak and other senior
officials.
</P>
<P>
Weizman spoke of the legacy of Rabin as a solider and a
statesman. He said both Rabin was a victim of polemics of the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Contrary to early reports, the Labor Knesset members remained
in the chamber to hear Netanyahu's speech. Labor reportedly has
said that it would boycott the special session if the prime
minister refused to apology for his inciting remarking that
preceded Rabin's murder.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu stressed the need for soul searching in the wake of
the assassination, saying that "all of us, including me, must
consider past actions and think ways to heal the terrible rift in
the nation."
</P>
<P>
Also in a Likud convention Sunday, Netanyahu called for
national unity and praised the achievements of Labor movement
and other Left movements in the building of the country.
</P>
<P>
But opposition leader Barak said today that he is anxious for
national reconciliation, noting that "reconciliation is not just
words. We must all promise never again to match in perception with
symbol of death and violence and must never again with the words
of incitement."
</P>
<P>
For a memorial service at his grave on Mount Herzl in
Jerusalem, hundreds of former friends, colleagues, army comrades
and political allies and even rivals joined the family of
the slain late prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The half-hour ceremony began with lightening of an eternal
flame by Rabin's grandson Michael El. In place of government and
opposition leaders, former supreme court chief Meir Shargal, who
had led the probe into the Rabin's death, was the only public
figure to address the crowd.
</P>
<P>
He said that the nation had to learn lessons from the
tragic.
</P>
<P>
A dozen of wreaths were laid on the Rabin's tomb, and the
first two were placed by Weizman and Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
At Rabin Square in Tel Aviv, the very site of his murder two
years ago, some ten thousands of high school students gathered at
noon today to remember the slain leader.
</P>
<P>
In the gathering, Chief of Staff Amnon Shahak in the name of
Israel Defense Forces saluted Rabin, who had been Chief of Staff
and gained the Israeli greatest victory in the six-day war before
becoming prime minister and defense minister.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in honor of Rabin's assassination, flags through
the country flew at half-mast. And the entire school day was
devoted to his memory, and memorial ceremonies were also held
at all schools. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
