<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-12 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Free Trade Zones Absorb Foreign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Iran's free trade zones (FTZ)
so far have absorbed about 250 million U.S. dollars of foreign
investment, a senior Iranian official announced here today.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Iranian official news agency IRNA,
Morteza Alviri, advisor to the Iranian president and secretary of
the High Council of Free Trade Zones, said that negotiations were
underway for 5 billion dollars investments in the FTZs.
</P>
<P>
He said that an agreement would soon be signed with India to
build a chemical fertilizer plant at an estimated cost of 330
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Alviri noted that the recent ratification of monetary
policies to govern activities in the FTZs and establishment of
infrastructure there have spurred the recent negotiations to
attract new investments in the areas.
</P>
<P>
So far, Iran has received 2,200 applications for investment in
the FTZs, the Iranian official said, adding that the investments
have led to the establishment of 220 industrial units.
</P>
<P>
Alviri said that China, Japan, the United Arab Emirates,
India, Austria, South Korea, the Czech Republic, Lebanon,
Pakistan, Britian and Kuwait have invested in Iran's free trade
zones.
</P>
<P>
As to the recently approval of the Iranian cabinet to
transform the Bandar Rajaie port to a special trade zone, he said
that it was a major step to facilitate transfer of goods to and
from the Central Asian republics.
</P>
<P>
Alviri said the port's capacity for storage of goods would
increase to 40 million tonnes from the present level of 18 million
tonnes and the volume of goods transported via railway to Iran's
southern port of Bandar Abass would also increase, reaching 10
million tonnes in the future.
</P>
<P>
Iran has established several free trade zones to boost the
country's economy by attracting foreign investment, the most
important ones are the Qeshm Island, Kish Island in the Persian
Gulf and the Chabahar Port on the Oman Sea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
