<HEADLINE> Parliament Chief Sees New Era of Sino-S. African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 12 (Xinhua) -- South African National
Assembly Speaker Frene Ginwala said today that bilateral
relations between her country and China would enter a brand-new
era after the establishment of diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with head of a Chinese delegation in Cape Town,
she said she was pleased to see the two countries have signed a
series of contracts and trade and investment protocols during the
visit of the mission.
</P>
<P>
She hoped that the two countries could build up even closer
relations.
</P>
<P>
The speaker said she is looking forward to an official visit
to China after the normalization of relations.
</P>
<P>
South African President Nelson Mandela declared last November
that his country would sever ties with Taiwan and recognize the
People's Republic of China diplomatically.
</P>
<P>
Head of the Chinese trade and economic delegation, Shi
Guangsheng, said the establishment of diplomatic relations will
provide guarantee and good conditions for trade and economic
cooperation between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Shi, who is deputy minister of foreign trade and economic
cooperation, believed that bilateral trade and economic relations
will develop more quickly, thus contributing to the economic
development of the two countries and the improvement of the
living standards of the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
The 100-strong Chinese delegation, composed of government
officials in charge of trade and economic affairs and
representatives of more than 50 leading Chinese firms, is the
largest ever Chinese mission to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, businesses of the two countries signed 18 contracts
and protocols in Johannesburg totaling 540 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, South African Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo also
met with Shi and some other members of the delegation.
</P>
<P>
The delegation arrived last Wednesday for an 11-day South
African tour, which will also take them to Durban. 
