<HEADLINE> Sudan: Progress in Peace With Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Sudan said today that the
negotiation between the government and the outlawed Sudan People's
Liberation Movement (SPLA) had made progress by agreeing to give
the south the right of self-determination.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters upon return to the Khartoum airport from
Nairobi, Sudanese Minister of Foreign Affairs Ali Osman Mohamed
Taha said the government and the largest rebel group in southern
Sudan also agreed to settle conflicts between them through
peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
But he stressed that the government had rejected SPLA's demands to
set up a confederation between north and south, insisting on
maintaining the federal system in place.
</P>
<P>
The government and the SPLA, led by John Garang, held
negotiations from October 29 to November 7 in Kenyan capital
Nairobi to seek ways to end the 14-year old civil war. The two
parties are scheduled resume talks in April.
</P>
<P>
The SPLA has been fighting the Islamic government since 1983 to
press for an increased autonomy for the southern third of Sudan
dominated by Africans, Christians and animists.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 1.3 million people have died either in the
fighting or famine in this African largest country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
