<HEADLINE> British PM Promises to Reform Party Funding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 12 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair promised today to reform party funding in the country,
saying it was "long overdue."
</P>
<P>
While answering questions in the parliament, Blair said he had
asked the Committee on Standards in Public Life, a watchdog body,
to examine the whole issue of political funding and report back by
next Summer.
</P>
<P>
His move was taken after the opposition Conservative party
accused the government of breaking promises by allowing tobacco
sponsorship exemption for Formula One.
</P>
<P>
Opposition leader William Hague said today the government was
"breaking them for free all the time," including those on
pensions, tax and cold weather payments.
</P>
<P>
The government has suffered a rough ride from the media over a
controversial donation of one million pounds from millionaire
Bernie Ecclestone, president of Formula One Constructors
Association.
</P>
<P>
The government decided last week to scrap a proposed ban on
tobacco industry sponsorship of Formula One, citing the threat to
British jobs and the possibility the motor racing industry might
move abroad.
</P>
<P>
Blair said there was a collective Cabinet decision made last
week to seek a specific exemption for Formula One and then seek a
worldwide voluntary agreement to avoid Grands Prix in other
countries being shown here without restriction.
</P>
<P>
Such a ban would force Formula One to quit Britain and this
would "affect 8,000 jobs in the motor racing directly and many
more indirectly," he added.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also reaffirmed that the government would
speed up separate legislation to register political parties, ban
foreign donations and require publication of the names of donors
of more than 5,000 pounds (8,510 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The government has promised early this week to pay back
Ecclestone's donation, which was donated before the May 1
election, on advice from Sir Patrick Neill, chairman of the
Standards Committee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
