<HEADLINE> U.S. Federal Reserve Decide to Maintain Current </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Federal Reserve
decided today to leave short-term interest rates unchanged despite
some people's concern that the robust economic growth could soon
stimulate inflation.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. central bank said it had concluded a three-hour,
10-minute closed-door meeting of its policy-making Federal Open
Market Committee and had nothing more to say.
</P>
<P>
The committee's statement indicated it has left the benchmark
rate on overnight loans between banks unchanged at 5.5 percent. An
increase would have raised borrowing costs for millions of
American consumers and businesses.
</P>
<P>
The decision to maintain rates steady was widely expected, in
view of the recent tumult in the U.S. stock markets over the past
three weeks in reaction to currency crises in some Asian nations.
</P>
<P>
Before the turbulence, Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan had been
warning that a developing labor shortage had put the economy on an
"unsustainable track."
</P>
<P>
Economic experts believed that U.S. Fed policy-makers were
confronted with conflicting economic trends.
</P>
<P>
On one hand, the lowest unemployment rate in 24 years and the
fastest wage gains in eight years suggested they ought to raise
rates to keep inflation contained. But on the other hand, the
tumultuous stock market, gyrating at each new development in Asia,
argued for caution.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts believed the central bankers probably were
looking ahead to when they can raise rates in a calmer financial
atmosphere. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
