<HEADLINE> US Tells Iraq: Not to Down Spy Planes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, November 12 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. military commander
today warned Iraq against firing at U.S. U-2 spy planes flying
over Iraq on U.N. arms inspection mission, saying Baghdad would be
"stupid" if it makes such attacks.
</P>
<P>
General A.K. Richardson, commander of the Nimitz, which was
deployed in the Gulf waters a month ago told reporters on board
the aircraft carrier that any attack on the spy planes would
cause U.S. retaliation.
</P>
<P>
"The carrier is ready to face the worst possibilities and
American pilots have absolute rights to protect themselves when
they come across danger," the Bahraini News Agency quoted the
general as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Baghdad would be stupid if it makes the choice (of attacking
U-2s)," he said.
</P>
<P>
Richardson pointed that his carrier is watching the situation
very closely and he believed Nimitz has "full capabilities of
protecting U-2 spy planes and foiled any attempt to shoot down the
planes."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. general made the remarks after Baghdad threatened to
attack the U-2 spy planes.
</P>
<P>
Iraq said earlier that anti-aircraft systems were on alert to
shoot down "any hostile target."
</P>
<P>
Baghdad's threat came with an order to deport U.S. arms
inspectors in charge of espionage. The order has sparked a crisis
between the U.N. and Iraq. 
</P>
