<HEADLINE> Chinese Athletes Enhance Performance With Hard Training </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, November 13 (Xinhua) -- An official for doping
control said here on Thursday that the striking perfromance of
Chinese athletes at the recently-ended Eighth National Games were
enhanced by incredible hard training.
</P>
<P>
Nils Lindstedt, Chief Representative of the International
Doping Tests and Management at China, told Sweden Daily which
published Thursday that the Chinese distance runners utilized a
Spartan way in training, which was too hard for western athletes to
bear.
</P>
<P>
What the Swede indicated was the women runners from Liaoning
Province coached by Ma Junren, who pressed his proteges to run one
and a half marathons a day.
</P>
<P>
Ma's protege Jiang Bo broke the women's 5,000 meters record in
the finals on October 23 with 14 minutes 28.09 seconds, beating
the previous world mark of 14:31.27, which had been established by
teammate Dong Yanmei in the heats just two days before.
</P>
<P>
Jiang, 20, also won the 1,500m gold in 3:50.98, only 0.52
second short of the world mark, which was set by Ma's another
deciple Qu Yunxia in Beijing four years ago.
</P>
<P>
Lindstedt added the other factor that Chinese athletes achieved
remarkable results in the Games was that govenments at all levels
across China attached great importance to sports development.
</P>
<P>
Lindstedt, 34, has occassionally conducted out-of-competition
random doping tests on Chinese athletes at the request of IAAF and
FINA since he took the post three years ago.
</P>
<P>
He usually mailed the urine samples for test to the
International Olympic Committee (IOC)-designated laboratories in
Barcelona, London or Cologne, Germany.
</P>
<P>
Lindstedt has taken away the urine samples of some top swimmers
and runners during the Eighth National Games including those of
Jiang Bo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
