<HEADLINE> Chinese Employees Sign Agreements to Protect Company Secrets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, November 13 (Xinhua) -- The Chunlan Group, China's largest
air conditioner manufacturer, recently signed agreements with its
employees to protect its technology and commercial secrets.
</P>
<P>
Chunlan and other 17 enterprises in Taizhou in Jiangsu province
are the first to sign the Contract of Intellectual Property
Protection of Enterprises, which states that employees have an
obligation to protect the enterprise's patents, trademarks,
technology, and commercial secrets.
</P>
<P>
Economists say the contract is a milestone in intellectual
property rights protection in China.
</P>
<P>
The contract calls for a grace period of three years after an
employee leaves the company, calling it a confidence period when
he or she is not allowed to get involved in any related or similar
business, or work for the competition.
</P>
<P>
The company is also required to pay a certain sum of money to
the employee as compensation, a month after the confidence
period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
