<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Wants to Work With UNSCOM Without Americans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, November 13 (Xinhua) -- Iraq reaffirmed it would
continue to cooperate with the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) if
American inspectors were excluded, the Iraqi News Agency (INA)
reported today.
</P>
<P>
This was included in a message sent by Iraqi Foreign Minister
Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf to the United Nations Security Council
president, according to INA.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sahhaf said in the message that ever since UNSCOM resumed
its work on November 3, it has been informed by Iraq that no
Americans should exercise inspection, but the other members of the
inspection teams were free to carry out their missions.
</P>
<P>
Iraq decided on October 29 to expel the Americans working on
the U.N. weapons inspection teams, and has since barred American
inspector from entering suspected sites along with the U.N. teams.
</P>
<P>
UNSCOM must verify that Iraq has eliminated all its long-range
missiles and nuclear, chemical and biological weapons before the
U.N. Security Council can decide to lift the crippling sanctions
imposed on Iraq since its invasion of Kuwait in 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
