<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, Yugoslav Presidents Hold Talks in Beijing (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 13 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
and Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, meeting in Beijing this
afternoon, agreed that China and Yugoslavia should develop
friendly relations of long-term, stable and comprehensive
cooperation, and bring peace and prosperity in Asia and Europe to
the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders discussed bilateral ties and the regional and
international situation and said they are satisfied with bilateral
co-operation in politics, the economy, culture, and education in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
This is Milosevic's first official visit to China. Jiang said
he believes it will bring Sino-Yugoslav friendly ties to a new
period of development, and that although the two are far from each
other, their similar historical experiences and common aspirations
for peace and development bring them closer.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said the two peoples are making unremitting efforts to
improve themselves, pursue a spirit of independence and
self-reliance, and stick to the development road they've chosen
for themselves.
</P>
<P>
Sino-Yugoslav traditional friendship has stood the test of
time, Jiang said, and on many major issues, the two understand and
support each other, and China regards Yugoslavia as an important
and friendly partner in the Balkan region.
</P>
<P>
He held that the Chinese government will continue to support
Yugoslavia's independence, sovereignty and territorial integrity,
and respect the policies the Yugoslav people have chosen.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said he appreciates Yugoslavia's "One China" policy and
its refusal to have any official contact or ties with Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic said that, although the two nations are far from each
other, their political relations are close, and that he believes
his talks with Jiang will serve to further consolidate bilateral
friendship and open up a new period of friendly co-operation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, Yugoslav Presidents Hold Talks in Beijing (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jiang said that, after the Cold War, rapidly developing
multipolarization has become a historical trend and that various
types of regional co-operation are without precedent, and the
strength of developing countries has increased.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the development of multipolarization is conducive
to world peace, stability and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
Each nation has chosen or is exploring a development road fit
to its own national situation, its own history, and its
traditions, he said, and this should be respected. All countries
should seek common ground while preserving their differences, and
coexist in peace.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic said that the integration process is increasing in
the world and that power politics attempts to affect this, so it
is even more important for countries to increase
co-operation. "Sino-Yugoslav co-operation can be called a good
example," he said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that, under Milosevic's leadership, the Yugoslav
people, in the complex and changeable Balkan situation, have made
unremitting efforts to have social stability, develop the economy,
and improve the living standard, and have made satisfactory
results.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese believe that, although ethnic groups differ, Jiang
said, they should be on equal footing. "As long as nationalities
live in peace and harmony, the country's unity, development and
prosperity can be secured."
</P>
<P>
Prior to the talks, Jiang presided over a ceremony to welcome
Milosevic and his entourage including Srdja Bozovic, chairman of
the Chamber of Republics of Federal Assembly, and Nikola Sainovic,
deputy prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Present at the welcoming ceremony were Vice-Premier Jiang
Chunyun, Vice-Chairman Wang Bingqian of the National People's
Congress Standing Committee, Vice-Chairman Yang Rudai of the
National Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference, and Wu Jichuan, chairman of the Chinese Government
reception committee and minister of Post and Telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
After the talks, Jiang and Milosevic signed a joint statement
on promoting friendly co-operative relations between the two
nations.
</P>
<P>
In the evening, Jiang hosted a banquet in honor of the
distinguished Yugoslav visitors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
