<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-Japanese Relations Have Broad Prospects, Li Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, November 13 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese Premier Li Peng
said here today that Sino-Japanese relations have good prospects
if Japan continues to develop along the path of peace.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with NHK of Japan, Li said China and Japan
should increase contacts, deepen mutual understanding and
strengthen cooperation.
</P>
<P>
As neighbors, China and Japan share similar interests in
security issues, and the two economies are highly complementary,
Li said. Japan is China's largest trading partner.
</P>
<P>
In the 50 years after World War II, Li said, Japan has
developed along a path of peace. And the development of
Sino-Japanese relations depends on what path Japan will take in
the future.
</P>
<P>
As the 21st century approaches, Li said, the leaders and
peoples of the two countries should consider what kind of
relations should be carried into the new century.
</P>
<P>
Asked to comment on his talks with Japanese Prime Minister
Ryutaro Hashimoto during his ongoing visit, Li said the talks were
held in a "warm and sincere atmosphere," increasing mutual
understanding and expanding common ground.
</P>
<P>
Li said the talks have covered a wide range of topics,
including bilateral relations and international issues.
</P>
<P>
Both China and Japan are important countries in the world and
in particular in the Asia-Pacific region, Li said. Therefore,
friendly cooperation between the two countries is of crucial
importance to international peace and development, he added.
</P>
<P>
Li said he and Hashimoto agreed that frequent contacts and
direct dialogues between the Chinese and Japanese leaders play a
positive role in increasing mutual understanding between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Referring to disputes between China and Japan resulting from
Japan-U.S. security cooperation guidelines, Li said Hashimoto
explained the issue to him in three points:
</P>
<P>
-- Japan-U.S. security cooperation is in conformity with
Japan's constitution;
</P>
<P>
-- The cooperation is of a defensive nature;
</P>
<P>
-- The cooperation does not run counter to the purpose of the
Japan-China Joint Statement and the Japan-China Treaty of Peace
and Friendship. The Japanese government sticks to the "one China"
position and recognizes the government of the People's Republic of
China as the sole legal government representing all of China.
</P>
<P>
Li said: "It would be perfect if Prime Minister Hashimoto would
add one point, clarifying that Japan-U.S. security cooperation
does not include Taiwan."
</P>
<P>
Asked to comment on the recent China-U.S. summit and the
China-Russia summit and the talks between Chinese and Japanese
prime ministers, Li said that normal friendly relations and
cooperation among different countries should be maintained after
the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
The development of relations between these countries should be
constructive and the framework of any bilateral relations should
not target a third country, Li added.
</P>
<P>
The development of such state-to-state relations is conducive
to peace and development in the Asia-Pacific region and the world
as a whole, and is in the trend of multipolarization, Li said.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the human rights issue would become an obstacle to the
development of Sino-U.S. relations, Li said it is natural that
differences exist on this issue since China and the United States
have different national conditions, social systems, ideologies,
values, cultural traditions and different levels of economic
development.
</P>
<P>
Differences can be narrowed and common grounds can be expanded
through dialogues, Li said, adding that the human rights issues
should not be used as a pretext for interfering in other country's
internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
When asked to give China's position on Russia's request to join
the APEC, the premier said China takes a positive attitude on this
matter since Russia is located across the European and Asian
continents.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the situation on the Korean Peninsula, Li said
China hopes to see peace and stability in that area.
</P>
<P>
The four-party talks on the Korean Peninsula issue are
proceeding and China is ready to play a constructive role in the
issue, he added.
</P>
<P>
The premier stressed that it is only when a new peace mechanism
is established through dialogues and negotiations can peace and
stability on the Korean Peninsula be ensured.
</P>
<P>
He hoped Japan would take more initiative measures to develop
relations with the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
On China's domestic situation, Li said the 15th National
Congress of the Communist Party of China (CPC) recognized Deng
Xiaoping's Theory as the guidelines of China's work in all areas.
</P>
<P>
The CPC congress also elected the new leadership, with
President Jiang Zemin at the core, thus offering a guarantee for
China's stability and development in the future, he added.
</P>
<P>
He noted that China will continue to implement its policies of
reform and opening up to the outside world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
