<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China-EU Law Symposium Opens in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 13 (Xinhua) -- The China-European Union Law
Symposium opened here today.
</P>
<P>
Close to 100 law experts from Britain, Belgium, France,
Germany, Italy, Austria, Spain, Switzerland, the Netherlands,
Denmark, Finland and China gathered to discuss the "role of rule
by law in economic development".
</P>
<P>
Ren Jianxin, President of the Supreme People's Court of China,
said at the opening ceremony that countries and nationalities have
their own historical and cultural traditions and democratic and
legal systems, and therefore they should respect, learn from, and
help each other.
</P>
<P>
Ren said that China needs to understand the legal systems of
the EU countries, because they are all advanced countries where
market economy has developed for more than 200 years and where
legal systems for market economy are relatively mature.
</P>
<P>
He said that China is the world's largest developing country,
with a long history and a large population, and it has made great
headway in democratic and legal development since the founding of
the People's Republic in 1949, and especially since the
implementation of the reform and opening-up policy in 1978.
</P>
<P>
China now has a socialist legal framework which is based on the
Constitution and which contains a series of important laws, he
said.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that it is in the interests of China and the EU
countries to increase cooperation in the law and to learn from
each other.
</P>
<P>
He urged both China and the EU countries to respect each other,
safeguard friendship, increase understanding and cooperation in
the law, and put aside political, economic and social
differences.
</P>
<P>
The symposium was sponsored by the China Law Society, the
Sino-British Culture Association, and the Sino-Belgian Economic
and Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
Present at the opening ceremony were Chinese Minister of
Justice Xiao Yang, executive vice-president of the China Law
Society She Mengxiao, and Jeffrey Howe, head of the EU delegation
and former British deputy prime minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
