<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 13 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
news items in leading U.S. newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times
</P>
<P>
-- Four Americans and their Pakistani driver were shot and
killed as they drove through Karachi's central business district.
The assailants fled, but police officials suspected they were
avenging the conviction of a Pakistani citizen this week for
killing two CIA employees in Virginian in 1993.
</P>
<P>
-- The U.N. Security Council voted unanimously to impose new
sanctions on Iraq for failing to cooperate with a United Nations
disarmament commission. The sanctions included a ban on foreign
travel by Iraqi officials, but Baghdad said it would ignore the
ban and again barred a team of inspectors from entering sites they
wanted to investigate.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post
</P>
<P>
-- Ramzi Ahmed Yousef, an electrical engineer who prosecutors
said masterminded the World Trade Center bombing because he
"wanted to make Americans feel terror," was found guilty Wednesday
of conspiracy in the 1993 bombing and faces life in prison.
</P>
<P>
-- President Clinton and Vice President Gore gave separate
interviews Tuesday afternoon to Justice Department officials
probing whether either man may have broken the law by making
telephone fund-raising solicitations from the White House.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal
</P>
<P>
-- The Energy Department predicted a sharp drop in coal and
electricity prices will increase power use and make it harder to
meet Clinton's proposed emissions targets to fight global warming.
The survey projects 2010 carbon-dioxide emissions will be 34
percent higher than in 1990.
</P>
<P>
-- Westinghouse is close to selling its conventional
power-generation business to Germany's Siemens for about 1.5
billion dollars, plus debt assumption, people familiar with the
matter said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kodak's job cuts appear to total 8,000 or even fewer,
rather than the 10,000 announced by the imaging concern, because
some of the cuts involve employees moving to joint ventures.
</P>
</TEXT>
