<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Adopts Proposal to Grant More Aid to Ukraine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, November 13 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission (EC)
today adopted a proposal to grant a loan of up to 150 million ECUs
(approximately 190 million U.S. dollars) to Ukraine with a maximum
duration of up to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
The assistance is aimed to sustain the economic reform course
of Ukraine and alleviate its social costs.
</P>
<P>
The loan, initiated by Yves-Thibault de Silguy, EU commissioner
responsible for economic, monetary and financial affairs, will be
made available subject to a review of Ukraine's economic
performance for 1997-1998.
</P>
<P>
The program is also supported by the International Monetary
Fund and the World Bank, said the commission, an executive body of
the European Union (UN).
</P>
<P>
Total assistance provided to Ukraine by the EU and EU member
states has amounted to 4.02 billion ECUs (about 4.60 billion
dollars) since 1991, exceeding the aid of any other donor.
</P>
<P>
The Commission noted that the transition process in Ukraine has
been accelerated following the election of President Leonid Kuchma
in 1994 and considerable progress has been achieved since,
especially in stabilization and liberalization of the economy.
</P>
<P>
But the economic situation remains difficult in the country,
with its GDP declining by another 10 percent in 1996 to stay at
approximately one third of the 1990 level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
