<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Compensate Bomb-Affected Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, November 13 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government has
decided to give 1.5 billion rupees (25.4 million U.S. dollars) in
compensation to companies which suffered severe property losses in
a bomb blast in the capital on October 15.
</P>
<P>
The compensation package proposed by President Chandrika
Kumaratunga was approved at a special cabinet meeting Wednesday
night, Media Minister Mangala Samaraweera said today.
</P>
<P>
The move is to maintain the status of the Fort area, the
business center in Colombo and the site of the blast, as the
country's financial hub, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The landmarks of the Galadari Hotel, the Hilton, the World
Trade Center and the Bank of Ceylon in the area sustained heavy
damages in the blast.
</P>
<P>
Samaraweera said the government made the decision because
insurance covers for the damaged buildings were not enough for the
operators to carry out rehabilitation work.
</P>
<P>
Estimated damages to the World Trade Center and the Hilton
stood at 700 million rupees (11.9 million dollars) and 600 million
rupees (10.2 million dollars) respectively, while the insurance
available for them was only 180 million rupees (3.05 million
dollars) and 12 million rupees (0.2 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Samaraweera said the government will also provide a 15-year
loan to the affected companies with an annual interest rate of 2
percent.
</P>
<P>
He said that other companies which had property losses in
previous terrorist bomb blasts in 1996 will also be compensated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
