<HEADLINE> UNITA Condemned for Beating UN Soldier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, November 13 (Xinhua) -- U.N. peace keeping force in
Angola has condemned Angola's former rebel movement UNITA for
beating up one of its peace keepers, according to Angolan News
Agency today.
</P>
<P>
Zambian soldier Warner Chinder, who serves at U.N. peace
keeping force at Jamba in Angola's southeastern province of
Kuandokubango responsible for the disbandment of the ex-soldiers
of the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola
(UNITA), was seriously wounded after eight UNITA army men
suddenly attacked him Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Chinder was rushed to a nearby hospital for treatment.
</P>
<P>
One official from the World Food Program and his assistant
were also beaten on the occasion. But they were not seriously
wounded.
</P>
<P>
David Wimhurst, spokesman for the U.N. observation team in
Angola, said it is unbearable to see peace keepers here being
beaten up, and that such things should never happen again.
</P>
<P>
He said U.N. special representative Blondin Beye has sent a
message to report the event to UNITA Chairman Jonas Savimbi.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said none of the projects outlined in the peace
process such as the restructuring of state institutes in
UNITA-held areas and the disbandment of its soldiers has been
accomplished since October 30 when the U.N. Security Council
imposed sanctions agains UNITA. 
</P>
