<HEADLINE> S. Leone Paper Shut Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, November 13 (Xinhua) -- The military government in
Sierra Leone today ''temporarily suspended'' the thrice weekly
Standard Times newspaper from further publication, state radio
said.
</P>
<P>
A government statement was quoted as charging that the paper
''is formenting strife between friendly neighboring countries
through the use of fictitious stories.''
</P>
<P>
The paper in its Wednesday edition claimed that Liberian
President Charles Taylor and the military rulers in Sierra Leone
were assisting the son of late Guinean leader Sekou Toure to
"invade Guinea and overthrow the government of Lansana Conte."
</P>
<P>
''This is a vicious piece of propaganda that exists within the
mentality of the editor and the paper,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that the recent discovery of arms in parts of
Sierra Leone were meant to be used in the operations.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said the Standard Times has been one of the
foremost critics of the military government since it took power
in May and has continued to advocate for an ECOMOG military
intervention in Sierra Leone to wrestle power from the junta.
</P>
<P>
However, the paper's editor, Abdul Sesay defended himself by
telling xinhua, ''we are surprised over this development as we
were undertaking normal news coverage.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
