<HEADLINE> Bad Weather Slows Down Kenya's Fresh Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 13 (Xinhua) -- Kenya has failed to maintain
its annual 15 to 20 percent increase of horticultural exports due
to adverse weather conditions early this year.
</P>
<P>
The country exported 62.1 million kilograms of fresh
vegetables, fruits and cut flowers in the first nine months this
year, up only 1.1 percent from 61.4 million kilograms in the same
period in 1996, according to the latest official data available.
</P>
<P>
The fresh exports reached 54.4 million and 40.1 million
kilograms in the first nine months of 1995 and 1994 respectively.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that exporters who sold sub-standard produce
like immature fruit to capitalize on short term demand overseas
just ended up denting the country's image in Europe last year.
</P>
<P>
However, the Agricultural Ministry has recently urged the
Fresh Produce Exporters Association of Kenya, the umbrella body
in the industry, to strictly implement its code of practice and
blacklist errant members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
