<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Welcomes Efforts to Set up Asian Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 13 (Xinhua) -- International Monetary
Fund (IMF) Managing Director Michel Camdessus said today the IMF
welcomed efforts including the setting up of a proposed Asian Fund
to help prevent and react to a financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at a press conference after meeting
Malaysian Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim here today.
</P>
<P>
At the press conference, Camdessus was asked to comment on
whether the IMF will allow a separate Asian Fund being proposed by
some countries to have slightly differing conditionalities from
IMF programs to reflect the social diversity in the ASEAN
(Association of Southeast Asian Nations) region.
</P>
<P>
He said the setting up of Asian Fund was an extremely good idea
for countries to take extra efforts to help prevent and react to a
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out that while financial instruments were
not lacking in tackling the currency crisis in ASEAN, what was
lacking was a regional surveillance of each other's impending
financing crisis.
</P>
<P>
There is "unanimity among Asian countries in this region to
avoid creating whatever soft conditionalities for programs because
it was important for markets to rectify this kind of programs," he
said, adding that otherwise, "you would have spent the money and
increase the indebtedness without establishing confidence in the
market."
</P>
<P>
On the IMF's study on controls of currency trading as proposed
by Malaysia, he said preliminary findings would be revealed at an
ASEAN finance ministers' meeting scheduled for December 1-2 here.
</P>
<P>
He said the full findings of the study, which will include
lessons to be learnt from the recent monetary and financial crisis
affecting several developing countries, will be presented to the
IMF Board and the international community either by the end of
January or early February next year.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus said Malaysia's tradition of building on long term
macroeconomic stability and prudent financial management would
allow it to cope with the current problems.
</P>
<P>
He praised Malaysia for implementing measures to further
strengthen and consolidate its financial sector, saying the steps
taken in the 1998 Budget such as calling for greater disclosure
and regulatory moves in the finance sector including increasing
the provisions for bad loans and cuts in loan growth "would allow
Malaysia to resist this turmoil."
</P>
<P>
Camdessus said the IMF felt reassured by Malaysia's commitment
to curbing credit expansion and steps taken to overcome the
current account deficit by deferring large projects and reducing
imports.
</P>
<P>
He said the prudential regulations and transparency being
pushed by the Malaysian government and moves towards greater
disclosures would place the country in a better position to handle
the financial crisis plaguing regional economies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
