<HEADLINE> Egyptian Doctor Sentenced to Death for Aiding Bus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 13 (Xinhua) -- The Egyptian Higher Military
Court today sentenced a mental hospital director to life
imprisonment for his misconduct of freeing his patient who
attacked a German tourist bus in downtown Cairo on September 18.
</P>
<P>
Doctor Nessim Abdel Malek Nessim was found guilty for freeing
Saber Farahat from his Cairo's Khanka Asylum where Farahat stayed
under the pretext of mental treatment before being set free to
carry out the fatal attack that killed nine German tourist and
their Egyptian driver, the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Doctor Sayed el-Qut, director general of mental health at the
Health Ministry, standing trial on bribery charges, was acquited.
</P>
<P>
Of other suspects including patients, physicians and orderlies
implicated in the case, eight were sentenced to prison terms
ranging between three to ten years while two others were acquited.
</P>
<P>
Saber was confined to Khanka Asylum when he was proved
insane in the wake of the 1993 killings of three foreigners at
Cairo's Semiramis Hotel.
</P>
<P>
He has told reporters that his family bribed Sayed el-Qut to
set him free before last month's attack on the German tourists.
</P>
<P>
The Farahat brothers were sentenced to death and hanged last
week on conviction of premeditated murder and the use of violence
to harm the Egyptian economy.
</P>
<P>
Six co-defendants got various prison terms ranging between
three to ten years with hard labor for supplying them with
ammunition and weapons used in the tourist bus shooting and
fire bomb attack.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-six other people were wounded in the fatal attack
outside the Egyptian Museum, which houses some of the world's
greatest Pharaonic treasures.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian authorities have denied that the attack was
carried out by Islamic militants fighting Mubarak's government
since 1992, and described it as an isolated case carried out by a
lunatic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
