<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 13:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AL Chief: AL Not to Take Part in Doha Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 13 (Xinhua) -- Arab League (AL) Secretary
General Esmat Abdul Meguid said here today that the league will
not attend the Middle East and North Africa (MENA) Economic
Conference to be opened Sunday in Doha, Qatar.
</P>
<P>
Meguid told reporters that he will not take part in the
three-day gathering nor will the league send any delegation there
due to no tangible progress in the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the decision was in line with the
resolution adopted on September 20 at the League's Council that
linked its participation in the conference to achieving progress
in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the Arab League chief sent a message to Qatar on
the stance towards the conference that involves Israel, saying
that he will not reveal the final word until today when Qatari
Foreign Minister Sheikh Hamad Bin Jassim Bin Jabir al Thani
receives the letter.
</P>
<P>
The Arab countries have been split over whether to attend the
Doha conference as the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks have ground
to a virtual halt and the peace process on the Lebanese and Syrian
tracks have been on ice since 21 months ago.
</P>
<P>
The League's stance came in line with the majority of Arab
countries that announced their boycott of the conference, namely,
Egypt, Syria, Palestinian National Authority, Saudi Arabia,
Morocco, the United Arab Emirates, Lebanon, Sudan, Iraq, Libya and
Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
So far, only Jordan, Kuwait, Oman, Yemen and Tunisia of the 16
Arab countries invited decided to show up.
</P>
<P>
The annual MENA conference, which has been held in Casablanca,
Amman and Cairo, was initiated in 1994 to integrate Israel into
the regional economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leaning of Ancient Pagoda in East China Controlled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, November 13 (Xinhua) -- Successful efforts to control
earth subsidence have extended the life of an ancient leaning
pagoda in east China's Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
The Huqiu Pagoda, located some 3.5 km northwest of Suzhou, is
the oldest large pagoda built with bricks south of the Yangtze
River.
</P>
<P>
Recent checks have revealed that a four-year effort carried out
by scientists in the 1980s has basically controlled the subsidence.
</P>
<P>
The checks also revealed that the pagoda is now in relatively
good condition.
</P>
<P>
The pagoda, constructed some 1,038 years ago, has been
subjected to centuries of earth subsidence.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Jobless Rate Unchanged for Three Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, November 13 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) said
its jobless rate stood at 10.6 percent at the end of September
1997, unchanged from that of August and July.
</P>
<P>
The seasonally-adjusted figure was 10.9 percent in the
corresponding month last year, said the Eurostat, the EU's
statistical office based in Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
The unemployment rate reached 10 percent in Germany after
rising continuously since the beginning of 1995. It was also 10
percent in Ireland, though the figure has been falling in the
country since mid-1993.
</P>
<P>
Four member states had rates above the EU's average. The rate
 was 19.9 percent in Spain. The figure, though it has been under
20 percent for three months in a row, remains the EU's highest
jobless rate. The other three countries are Finland with 13
percent, France 12.6 percent and Italy 12.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
The lowest rates in September were registered in Luxembourg
with 3.7 percent and Austria with 4.5 percent. Eurostat estimated
that 17.9 million people were unemployed in the EU in September.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
