<HEADLINE> Sino-American Symposium And Cardiovascular Disease Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 13 (Xinhua) -- A satellite symposium helped
acquaint doctors in the Chinese Cities of Beijing, Shanghai, and
Guangzhou with a meeting of the American Heart Association (AHA)
via a satellite downlink today.
</P>
<P>
More than 600 doctors were given information about recent
cardiovascular disease research by two Chinese doctors who are
attending the meeting in Orlando, Florida in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Kou Wenrong of Beijing Fuwai Hospital discussed a
cholesterol-reducing medicine, Pravastatin, made by Bristol-Myers
Squibb, which can reduce the incidence of strokes and heart
attacks by 20 percent and 29 percent respectively. Deaths from
heart attack also dropped by 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
The study, which involved 9,000 patients over a seven year
period, was conducted by an independent group of New Zealand and
Australian researchers under the auspices of the National Heart
Foundation of Australia with a grant from Squibb.
</P>
<P>
The "landmark study" is useful to people with or without heart
disease, and with varying cholesterol levels, said Prof. Gong
Lansheng of Shanghai Ruijin Hospital, and it is significant in
China because cardiovascular disease is the No.1 killer in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Experts have warned that the incidence of cardiovascular
disease will continue to rise in China because of changing
lifestyles and other factors.
</P>
<P>
Pravastatin is made in China by Shanghai Squibb Pharmaceuticals
Ltd., a Sino-American joint venture.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood Victims in Somalia Appeal for International </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, November 13 (Xinhua) -- At least 23 people were
drowned in flood waters following successive days of heavy rain
in Somalia's southwestern region of Bakol, reports from the area
said.
</P>
<P>
Sources said the deaths occurred in seven villages including
Bur Dhuhunle and Morogabey where inhabitants are now scattered on
the nearby mountains without shelter or food.
</P>
<P>
Elders from the Bur Dhuhunle who contacted reporters today via
VHF Radio said more than 1,075 head of goats and camels also died
in the waters.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that 335 houses and grain depots containing
31,300 quintals of sorghum were also destroyed by the floods in
the village.
</P>
<P>
The flood outcries are also coming from the coastal towns for
the first time since the heavy rains of the Deyr season began
some 45 days ago.
</P>
<P>
The white minority community of Baravani is now facing
difficulties created by the rains and began to flee the town by
the hundreds.
</P>
<P>
Amin Mohamed Nur, one of the prominent figures of the
community, told reporters that rain waters descended from the
mountains north of the town had washed away many old houses
including three Mosques.
</P>
<P>
Nur has appealed to the United Nations Educational, Scientific
and Cultural Organization (UNESCO) to campaign for the
preservation of the old, ancient and historic buildings of Brava,
225 km south of the capital.
</P>
<P>
Many more buildings are also likely to collapse owing to their
age and the strong winds accompanied with the rains, he noted,
adding that the main street linking the town of Brava to the
southern regions of the country is also endangered by the floods.
</P>
<P>
In response to the flood outcries, the European Commission has
confirmed to allocate an initial sum of 2.5 million U.S. Dollars
to the region with Somalia being the main focus.
</P>
<P>
A statement by the European Union today said this fund will go
through the European Community Humanitarian Office and the food
security unit of the European Commission to support emergency
humanitarian interventions through the Somalia aid coordination
body.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, this is also in response to the
appeals by the U.N. agencies and international aid organizations.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, only two small planes by United Nations
Children's Fund and World Food Program are reported to have
started bringing in blankets, nutritious biscuits and plastic
sheets for the flood displaced people in Gedo region in response
to the flood devastated communities of southern Somalia.
</P>
<P>
However, a large scale humanitarian assistance to southern
Somalia still requires much greater efforts, since there isn't
enough dry land for the planes to touch down and road
communication has been disrupted for more than a month now.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that so far the floods have claimed the lives
of nearly 150 people, killing thousands of animals and destroying
dozens of villages. Nearly one million people are believed to
have been displaced by the floods in southern Somalia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
