<HEADLINE> Chinese President Meets U.S. Senate Delegation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 13 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
said here today that China and the United States should join in a
concerted effort to maintain the good momentum in the development
of Sino-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
Jiang made the remarks during a meeting with Frank Murkowski,
chairman of the Energy and Natural Resources Committee of the
U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
Jiang welcomed the delegation led by Chairman Murkowski, the
first group of American guests to visit China since Jiang's recent
state visit to the United States.
</P>
<P>
Jiang expressed sincere gratitude for the warm welcome he
received from President Clinton, the U.S. government, the Congress
and the American people.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that he and President Clinton reached an important
consensus on the framework and orientation for developing
bilateral relations in the 21st century. Countries worldwide have
reacted positively to his U.S. visit and the improvement of
the Sino-U.S. relations, said Jiang.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that this fact alone serves as a proof that the
establishment of the Sino-US healthy and stable relations fully
conforms to the fundamental interests of the two peoples and
accords with the common desire of the people throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the U.S. Congress plays an important role in both
internal and external policy-making, and should thus play a
positive role in promoting, improving and developing
Sino-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that many U.S. senators support the advancement of
the Sino-U.S. relations and have made positive contributions in
this regard. He expressed the hope that more senators will visit
China so as to enhance mutual understanding, eliminate
misunderstanding and expand common ground.
</P>
<P>
There is vast potentials for China and U.S. to develop
cooperation in many fields, particularly in the environmental
protection and energy sectors, said Jiang.
</P>
<P>
Murkowski congratulated President Jiang on the success of his
recent state visit to the United States, and noted that
the visit has brought the two countries closer together. The visit
had also conveyed a strong message to the American and Chinese
peoples, as well as the people throughout the world, that both the
United States and China are devoted to developing a friendly
cooperative relationship, he added.
</P>
<P>
Murkowski shared Jiang's view concerning the potential for
cooperation in the energy and environmental protection
sectors. Murkowski pledged to use his position as chairman of
the Senate Energy and Natural Resources Committee to exert a
positive influence on the expansion of the Sino-U.S. cooperation in
the aforementioned sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
