<HEADLINE> Japan, Russia Agree to Start Peace Treaty Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, November 13 (Xinhua) -- Japan and Russia today agreed to
start talks for the final conclusion of a bilateral peace treaty
by the year of 2000, foreign ministry officials said.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Foreign Minister Keizo Obuchi and his Russian counterpart
Yevgeny Primakov made the consensus at a regular meeting in
Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
The talks will be held in January in Moscow at the vice foreign
ministerial level.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto
and Russian President Boris Yeltsin decided at an informal summit
meeting in Krasnoyarsk, eastern Siberia, to make utmost efforts to
sign a peace treaty by the year of 2000.
</P>
<P>
Japan and Russia have not yet sign a peace treaty for more five
decades mainly due to a territorial dispute over a chain of
Russian-held islands off northern Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
