<HEADLINE> Meeting to Be Held Again to Press S. Leone into </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, November 13 (Xinhua) -- West African Peace-keeping
Force (ECOMOG) commanders said today they are to hold another
meeting soon with representatives of the military government "to
assess how decisions taken will get into concrete action."
</P>
<P>
One of the commanders told Xinhua here, "we are anxious to
deploy troops very quickly and the implementation program will be
carried out with the assistance of a United Nations team."
</P>
<P>
He said the ECOWAS Committee of Five is now in New York for
discussions with the U.N. Security Council for it to put a team
in place to work alongside them.
</P>
<P>
The Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS)
empowered Nigeria, Ghana, Cote d'Ivoire, Guinea and Liberia as
the Five of Committee to carry out talks with Sierra Leone's
military junta on the issue of returning power to ousted
President T. Kabbah who was toppled in a May 25 coup.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, there are some controversies over some aspect of
the agreement reached between ECOMOG and the Sierra Leone junta
at last Tuesday's meeting in Grafton, 13 miles east of the
capital Freetown.
</P>
<P>
The ECOMOG delegation was led by field commander, general
Victor Malu.
</P>
<P>
The chief of staff of the military headquarters, Colonel
Gabriel Mani told Xinhua, "General Malu has given a wrong
impression to the outside world about certain aspects of the
meeting. I told Malu at the meeting that the Sierra Leone army
will not agree to be disarmed."
</P>
<P>
After that Malu said there was no point in going on with the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Director of Defense Information, Major John Milton said,
"the Sierra Leone army is a national institution and will
therefore not be allowed to be disarmed."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, officials from the ministry of children's affairs
are undertaking a registration of all children under arms as from
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We are covering the 12 districts and the western area,
including the capital, for one week and we shall meet with
paramount chiefs, religious leaders, the people's army, the
police and the Kamajors to get them to help," said Samuel Kaikai,
who is leading the exercise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
