<HEADLINE> Israeli Public Health Services Paralyzed by </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 13 (Xinhua) -- More than 15,000 operations
have been postponed in Israeli public hospitals in the past nine
weeks amid repeated protests by the Israel Medical Association
(IMA), local newspaper The Jerusalem Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the surgicals will be shut again in public
hospitals today except for emergencies, as part of a series of
protests launched in September by the IMA against the Treasury's
refusal to carry out an agreement to pay for hiring 360 more
doctors.
</P>
<P>
IMA Chairman Yoram Blachar said that the number of doctors per
hospital bed in Israel was one of the lowest in the world. "We
are fighting not for increased salaries but for improved medical
treatment and relieving overcrowding in the internal medical
departments," he said.
</P>
<P>
Blachar accused the Treasury of reducing the number of
hospital beds per 1,000 residents to 2.3, as compared with 3.5 in
the United States, 3.9 in Greece and seven in Germany.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Health Minister Yehoshua Matza also confronted Finance
Minister Yaakov Neeman about the issue during the Israeli Cabinet
meeting Wednesday, and demanded immediate action to resolve the
dispute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
