<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Man Wins SAARC Youth Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, November 13 (Xinhua) -- A Bangladeshi man has won
the 1997 Youth Award of the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation (SAARC) for his "outstanding service in community
welfare," said a press release issued today by the Kathmandu-based
SAARC Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
Sukur Salek, a doctor in medicine, is the first recipient of
such an award, which includes a SAARC gold medal and a cash prize
of 500 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The SAARC Youth Awards Scheme was initiated by the SAARC
Ministerial Conference on Youth in South Asia in Male, the
Maldives in May 1994, and was approved by the SAARC Council of
Ministers in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The award aims to encourage the youth of SAARC countries to
excel in different fields, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 18 nominations were fielded for the award from the
seven member countries of the SAARC -- Bangladesh, Bhutan, India,
the Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
The award will be given to Salek at the 19th session of the
SAARC Council of Ministers to be held in Male on November 29-30,
said the press release.  
</P>
