<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Full Text of Sino-Yugoslav Joint Statement (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 13 (Xinhua) -- The following is the full text
of a Sino-Yugoslav joint statement on bilateral friendship and
relations of cooperation signed here this afternoon by Chinese
President Jiang Zemin and Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
during the latter's state visit to China:
</P>
<P>
 JOINT STATEMENT OF THE PEOPLE'S REPUBLIC OF CHINA AND
</P>
<P>
THE FEDERAL REPUBLIC OF YUGOSLAVIA ON BILATERAL
</P>
<P>
 FRIENDSHIP AND RELATIONS OF COOPERATION
</P>
<P>
The People's Republic of China and the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia (hereinafter abbreviated as "the two sides"), on the
basis of the traditional friendship, especially the fruitful
cooperation in the fields of politics, economy, science,
technology, culture and education between the two countries,
starting from the aspiration of developing a long-term, stable and
all-round bilateral relationship, in accordance with the practical
principles of international laws, aimed at promoting the peace and
prosperity in Asia and Europe permanently into the 21st century
and further strengthening and enhancing bilateral ties established
on the basis of friendship, understanding, equality and mutual
benefit, state as follows:
</P>
<P>
1. The two sides hold that the multipolarization tendency in
the world is speeding up and developing countries, as a whole, are
playing an increasingly important role in international affairs;
regional economic cooperation organizations are showing their
great vitality; the development of politics, economy, and culture
in different countries are varied in form.
</P>
<P>
The consensus of mutual respect and mutual benefits instead of
interfering in the other's internal affairs and of imposing one's
will on others, dialogue and cooperation instead of confrontation
and conflict is being reached by more and more countries.
</P>
<P>
The two sides oppose the use of force or the threat of using
force in international relations.
</P>
<P>
The two sides hold that the present international situation is
generally more relaxed, and peace and development are the main
themes of the current times. But Cold-War thinking, hegemonism and
power politics still exist. The world economy is developing in an
imbalanced way and the gap between rich and poor is still widening.
</P>
<P>
The People's Republic of China and the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia are willing to further increase their consultations and
cooperation in international affairs and strive for establishing
a peaceful, stable, fair, and just new international political and
economic orders, and for safeguarding world peace and promoting
the joint development of mankind.
</P>
<P>
2. The Chinese side respects the independence, sovereignty and
territorial integrity of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia,
respects the way of development chosen by the Yugoslav people,
speaks highly of the independent foreign policy pursued by the
Federal Republic of Yugoslavia and its tremendous efforts and
contributions to consolidating the peace process in
Bosnia-Herzegovina and resolving peacefully the crisis in the
former Yugoslavia region.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side appreciates the active efforts by the Yugoslav
side in stabilizing the situation in southeastern Europe and
reiterates its support for the return of the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia to the international community.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Full Text of Sino-Yugoslav Joint Statement (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
3. The Yugoslav side reiterated its elaborated principled stance
on the Taiwan issue, emphasizing that there is only one China in
the world. The Federal Republic of Yugoslavia recognizes that
there is only one China and that Taiwan is an inalienable part of
the People's Republic of China and that the government of the
People's Republic of China is the sole legal government that
represents the people of China as a whole. The Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia will not set up official relations or have official
contacts with Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav side values the active role that the People's
Republic of China plays in international affairs, highly praises
the contributions that the People's Republic of China has made to
maintaining the peace and security in Asia and even in the world,
and highly appreciates the independent foreign policy of peace
that the People's Republic of China pursues.
</P>
<P>
4. The People's Republic of China and the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia are friends. The two countries and the two peoples
share a deep friendship of long tradition. The two sides expressed
satisfaction with their cooperation in the fields of politics,
economy, culture and education in recent years.
</P>
<P>
They both agreed that developing friendship and relations of
cooperation between the two countries on a long-term, stable and
comprehensive basis is in conformity with the common aspiration of
the two peoples and in the fundamental interests of the two
countries, and also beneficial to peace and development of Asia
and Europe.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed to strengthen and expand political
dialogues, including high-level and top-level dialogues, and to
support contact and cooperation between the parliaments of the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
5. In line with the principles of market economy and common
interests, the two sides will encourage their enterprises and
companies to conduct mutually beneficial cooperation and trade and
to develop various forms of cooperation and professional training,
and to set up joint venture enterprises in fields of common
interest and cooperate in the area of developing markets in a
third country.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will expand mutually beneficial cooperation in
the fields of science, technology, crafts, culture, arts,
education, sports, news and protection of biological environment,
health and cooperation between humanitarian and other
organizations.
</P>
<P>
6. The two sides will conduct cooperation in the aspects of law
and consular affairs and provide convenience for mutual visits by
the citizens of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will strengthen cooperation in their struggle to
crack down organized crime, international terrorism, illegal drug
trafficking and arms sales, bank note counterfeiting, historical
relics smuggling and threats against civil aviation safety.

President of the People's President of the Federal
Republic of China Republic of Yugoslavia

Jiang Zemin Slobodan Milosevic
</P>
<P>
Beijing, November 13, 1997
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Non-Communist Party Holds National Congress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 13 (Xinhua) -- The Seventh National Congress
of the China Democratic National Construction Association (CDNCA)
opened today in the Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
CDNCA, mainly composed of members of the economic sector, was
founded in Chongqing in December 1945 by national industrialists,
businessmen and intellectuals.
</P>
<P>
Wen Jiabao, a member of the Political Bureau and the
Secretariat of the Central Committee of the Chinese Communist
Party, sent a congratulatory message to the congress.
</P>
<P>
Wen noted the CDNCA has close relations with the nation's
economic sector and has performed important functions in the realm
of economic construction and services.
</P>
<P>
He urged the association to play an even more active role in
China's economic restructuring and development, as well as in the
establishment of the modern enterprise system and effort to reform
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Jing Shuping, chairman of the All-China Federation of Industry
and Commerce, presented a congratulatory address on behalf of his
federation and all other China's non-communist parties.
</P>
<P>
Cheng Siwei, executive chairman of the 6th CDNCA Central
