<HEADLINE> Asian Strength Halts Australian Stocks' Slide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 13 (Xinhua) -- Australian stocks ended
trading marginally down but well off their intraday lows after a
firmer than expected performance by Asian markets lifted midday
gloom.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index ended 6.9 points down at 2,504.0.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index dropped 1.9 points to 4,214.0 and all
resources slipped 11.7 to 1,148.0.
</P>
<P>
"All things considered it is a pretty good performance,
especially since we were down 30 more points at lunchtime," a
Lodge and Partners broker said.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index touched a low of 2,468.3 earlier in
the day as the market was gripped by fears that Tokyo and Hong
Kong would suffer after Wall Street's near 160 point fall
overnight.
</P>
<P>
The resources sector was again the hardest hit today with
industrial stocks slipping only marginally and bank and media
stocks among the best performers.
</P>
<P>
Bellwether BHP ended 15 cents lower at 14.30 Australian
dollars, well off its opening low of 14.051 Australian dollars but
still well down from the week's peak of 15.06 Australian dollars
reached on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Global miner Rio Tinto also softened, ending below 17.00
Australian dollars again for the first time since the October 28
crash. It fell 8.5 cents to 16.955 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Industrial stocks closed down marginally with most of the gains
in banking and media stocks.
</P>
<P>
All the majors apart from Westpac bank gained, with ANZ bank,
up 27 cents to 10.00 Australian dollars, leading, but Commonwealth
bank, 13 cents stronger at 17.20 Australian dollars, and NAB bank,
1.7 cents higher at 20.795 Australian dollars, also improved.
</P>
<P>
Westpac fell 6.2 cents to 8.678 Australian dollars, and brokers
said the interest in Commonwealth continued to be sparked by its
buyback scheme announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
News Corp led media stocks higher as it gained 10.7 cents to
7.25 Australian dollars and its preferred shares put on 16 cents
to 6.56 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover exceeded 305 million shares and valued at
more than 635 million US dollars, with falls outnumbering rises
by 624 to 378.
</P>
<P>
Gold stocks again followed the precious metal down as it
slipped 1.65 US dollars to 307.60 US dollars in Sydney trading.
</P>
<P>
The gold index dropped 18.2 points to 1,008.8.  
</P>
</TEXT>
