<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerians Called to Depend Less on Foreign Goods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 13 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Head of State General Sani
Abacha has called on his countrymen to reduce dependence on foreign
goods in the process of improving their standard of living.
</P>
<P>
It is important to ensure the success of the Family Economic
Advancement Program designed to harness all the potentials that abound
in the country with a view to establishing family-based cottage
industries, mainly in rural areas, said General Sani Abacha.
</P>
<P>
The government believes the program will advance the much desired
economic empowerment of the rural populace, Abacha said on Wednesday
while inaugurating the governing board of the program in the capital
Abuja.
</P>
<P>
He therefore called on members of the governing board to be
selfless and dedicated in carrying out their assignment.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has a population of about 100 million, most of who live in
the countryside where life is hard for the people due to lack of
development.
</P>
<P>
The overdependence on oil production also leads to insufficient
evolvement of the manufacturing industry. As a result, the country has
to import most of the daily necessities to meet the domestic need.
</P>
<P>
The program, which has been incorporated in the country's long-term
socio-economic development program known as Vision 2010, is expected
to lead to the setting up of many small industries to produce locally
needed goods with rich natural and human resources.
</P>
<P>
With the participation and support of banks, technological
institutions and related government departments, the program would
help remove the impediments to family economic empowerment and uplift
rural dwellers economically, said Abacha.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
