<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Weaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 13 (Xinhua) -- Firming expectations that the
Reserve Bank of Australia would leave interest rates unchanged in
the near term failed to shake the Australian dollar out of the
doldrums today.
</P>
<P>
Foreign exchange traders said the fallout from the turmoil on
Asian financial markets continued to be the pervading influence on
the local currency which settled at 69.28 US cents, down from
69.85 Wednesday despite a short-covering rally late in the
session.
</P>
<P>
The currency had struggled from the beginning of the local
session when it opened more than half a US cent lower in line with
a falling gold price.
</P>
<P>
Colonial State Bank foreign exchange manager Peter Whitley said
the market had already factored in the likelihood of no further
rate cut due to the volatility in the Australian dollar and,
therefore, today's news did not carry much weight.
</P>
<P>
"We saw a little bit of a short-covering rally after the market
tested 69.00 US cents," Whitley said.
</P>
<P>
"Nevertheless, the outlook for the Australian dollar remains
extremely negative.
</P>
<P>
"The possibility of the Asian debacle flowing through to our
economy is outweighing any internal factors completely."
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar also finished at 86.91 Japanese yen, from
87.60 yen in Sydney previously, and at 1.1924 German marks from
1.1934 marks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
