<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 10:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq not for Confrontation but Cooperation with UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, November 13 (Xinhua) -- The Iraqi government does
not expect any conflict but is ready to cooperate with the
United Nations over the arms inspection, a senior Iraqi diplomat
said here today.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Xinhua, Iraqi charge d'affaires
Salah Noor Samarmad said the Iraqi government expected that the
five permanent members of the U.N. Security Council would have
equal right to join the U.N. inspection team monitoring Iraq's
disarmament.
</P>
<P>
Samarmad said that so far most members of the U.N. inspection
teams are Americans, who "gather secret information about Iraq and
had activities which had no connection with the arms inspection."
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi government does not want to have any conflict with
the U.N. or the U.S., Samarmad stressed, on the contrary, Baghdad
hopes the U.N. embargo on the country to be lifted through "normal
cooperation" between Iraq and the U.N. and "in this way to give
the Iraqi people a normal life."
</P>
<P>
Samarmad attacked the U.S. for putting pressure on the U.N.
to impose new sanctions against his country, saying that
Washington's real objective "was to destroy our government and
our nation."
</P>
<P>
About the U.S. threat to launch military attack on Iraq if
Baghdad continues to reject the Americans in the U.N. team,
Samarmad said Baghdad would not worry about the U.S. attack
and "we are ready to defend our country."
</P>
<P>
He said that most members of the U.N. Security Council
including Russia, China and France as permanent members, have
announced their opposition to the U.S. military attack.
</P>
<P>
Since October 29, the Iraqi government has been rejecting
U.S. members of the U.N. inspection team to join in the
U.N. missions in Iraq, triggering a new crisis between Baghdad
and the U.S..
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council Wednesday unanimously passed a
resolution condemning Iraq for rejecting American inspectors in the
U.N. mission and slapped a ban on travel abroad by Iraqi officials
impeding U.N. arms inspection teams from doing their duties.
</P>
<P>
However, the Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed Saeed al-Sahaf
reiterated early Wednesday that his government would not change its
stance, even if the U.N. imposes new embargo on his country
by barring travels of Iraqi officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
