<HEADLINE> Lebanon's Economy Improves in Third Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, November 13 (Xinhua) -- The Lebanese economy improved
during the third quarter of this year with an estimated 3.5
percent growth on an annual basis, up 0.5 percent over the first
half of this year, local newspaper The Daily Star reported today.
</P>
<P>
It quoted a report issued by the Lebanese biggest bank Audi
as saying that a relatively good tourist season and a rise in
investment are the main reasons for the growth.
</P>
<P>
The number of tourists in the third quarter increased by 76
percent over the second quarter, reaching 225,304. This brought
the total for the first nine months of 1997 to 437,997,
a 33 percent increase over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The report said that aircraft landings and take-offs in
Beirut increased 15 percent in the third quarter and 11 percent
for the first nine months. About 1.5 million passengers were
handled in the first nine months, a 19 percent increase over last
year.
</P>
<P>
The exports during the third quarter increased by 10.2
percent over the second quarter to 162 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The trade deficit of 5 billion dollars for the first nine
months was cushioned by a 5.8 billion dollars net capital inflow.
</P>
</TEXT>
