<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FIS: Downhill Compromise Not Enough </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, November 13 (Xinhua) -- International Ski Federation
(FIS) said on Thursday that a compromise proposal by the Nagano
Winter Olympics organisers over the start for the men's downhill
was not enough to end the row.
</P>
<P>
Nagano Organising Committee (NAOC) director-general Makoto
Kobayashi said, in a major reversal on Tuesday, he would not
oppose raising the start of the downhill to 1,740 meters, 60
meters short of the height demanded by the International Ski
Federation.
</P>
<P>
"I have heard 1,740, which as everyone knows is not acceptable
because it is a very steep part (of the mountain)," FIS
secretary-general Gian Franco Kasper told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"But I believe that it is a step forward from NAOC that they
are now ready to discuss the different possibilities and this
might be very helpful," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kobayashi said a higher starting point was possible as long as
the starting gate and the course both remained outside a national
park, which covers a section of the top part of the mountain.
</P>
<P>
That was a major public stepdown for Kobayashi, who has
strongly rejected FIS requests to raise the start to 1,800 metes,
saying that would break environmental laws by putting it into the
park.
</P>
<P>
FIS has argued it is unfair because recreational skiers already
use the park, and that because the area between the park and a
chairlift which runs along the edge of it is so narrow, it is not
possible to set up a course outside the park.
</P>
<P>
"There is no way, unfortunately, you can ski outside (the
park)," said Kasper, who is in Nagano to attend a meeting of the
International Olympic Committee radio and television commission.
</P>
<P>
But Kasper added that FIS would have course designer Bernhard
Russi inspect the mountain again, probably within the next two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
"I think we have to look at this (proposal) on the mountain.
It is purely a technical question," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the results of the inspection would go to a new
consultative committee seeking to unravel the protracted dispute
that has overshadowed preparations for next February's Games.
</P>
<P>
NAOC, the Japan Olympic Committee, and the Ski Association of
Japan decided on Tuesday to set up the committee, although it was
not given a clear mandate.
</P>
<P>
Under Kobayashi's proposal, the chairlift would have its chairs
and cables removed during the Olympics, creating a wider race
course area outside the park.
</P>
<P>
The current course starting at 1,680 meters has a racing time
of about one minute 30 seconds, about 15 seconds below the winning
time at the 1994 Winter Olympics.
</P>
<P>
NAOC says a 1,740-meter start would add about nine or 10
seconds to the race. 
</P>
</TEXT>
