<HEADLINE> Nigerian-British Trade Expands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 13 (Xinhua) -- Trade between Nigeria and the
United Kingdom of Britain has been growing in the first eight
months of this year, despite their rows over democracy and human
rights.
</P>
<P>
Figures provided by the British High Commission in Lagos show
that British exports to Nigeria totalled 460 million U.S. dollars
in the first eight months, exceeding that of the same period of
1995 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
There is no figure concerning Nigeria's export to Britain, but
the high commission estimated that it is the highest since 1993,
except 1996.
</P>
<P>
British exports to Nigeria are mainly machinery, transport and
other equipment, manufactured goods and chemicals.
</P>
<P>
According to David Pearey, Commercial Counsellor of the
British High Commission, British assets in Nigeria is worth of
about 3.5 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The counsellor continued that except in the oil and gas
sector, there is little new investment coming into Nigeria from
Britain due to the political and economic conditions in Nigeria,
which he said, are not attractive to potential investors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
