<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia's Trade with India to be Boosted: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 13 (Xinhua) -- India's decision to slash
trade restrictions, including quantitative ones, would boost
Australian exports by at least 30 million Australian dollars (21
million US dollars) a year, Deputy Prime Minister and Trade
Minister Tim Fischer said today.
</P>
<P>
"In the longer term it will be even more important and is
likely to lift our exports by some 140 million US dollars a year,"
Fischer said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"The agreement, which follows negotiations in the World Trade
Organization (WTO), could become effective as soon as next week."
</P>
<P>
Fischer also said Australia had used the WTO to negotiate
additional benefits on products of special interest to Australia.
</P>
<P>
"Some 177 of our priority products will be free of quantitative
restrictions before April 2000, including salmon, prawns,
scallops, grated cheese, orange juice, opals, sapphires and solar
water heaters," Fischer said.
</P>
<P>
India's restriction, in place for almost 40 years for
balance-of-payment reasons, have limited Australia's access to the
Indian market, the deputy prime minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
