<HEADLINE> Nigeria Seeks U.N. Assistance in Solving Sierra </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 13 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Foreign Minister Tom
Ikimi has called on the United Nations to extend military and
technical assistance to the Economic Community of West African
States (ECOWAS) in its efforts to return democracy to Sierra
Leone.
</P>
<P>
In a statement which was conveyed by Nigeria's permanent
mission to the U.N. on Wednesday, Ikimi said military assistance
is "highly desirable and necessary" so that an observers' group
could be deployed in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Such a group, he said, will provide assistance to the ECOWAS
peace-keeping force (ECOMOG) now already in Sierra Leone, in the
same way as the U.N. Observers' Mission in Liberia (UNIMOL).
</P>
<P>
Ikimi also called for technical and material assistance from
the U.N., saying that it will enable ECOMOG to enforce the
sanctions imposed on Sierra Leone and maintain peace and
security.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the Conakry agreement signed between ECOWAS and
the military regime of Sierra Leone, Ikimi said all the armed
persons in Sierra Leone will be disarmed by ECOMOG by the end of
December.
</P>
<P>
If attacked, he said, ECOMOG will normally defend itself in
conformity with the rules of engagement in peace-keeping
operations.
</P>
<P>
Ikimi also stressed the need for the international community
to provide relief materials to refugees who have fled to
neighbouring Guinea and Liberia.
</P>
<P>
If ECOWAS's collective efforts result in the final and
peaceful settlement of the crisis in Sierra Leone, the stability
of the west Africa sub-region would have been restored and the
way paved towards economic and zonal development, the Nigerian
Foreign Minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
