<HEADLINE> Australia to Step up Defense Ties with Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 13 (Xinhua) -- Australia is to step up
defense ties with Indonesia and other regional countries, through
more joint training, exercises and other activities, Defense
Minister Ian McLachlan said today.
</P>
<P>
McLachlan said the increase in regional activities would be
outlined in the forthcoming Australian government strategic
review.
</P>
<P>
He foreshadowed the increase in regional defense activities in
a statement detailing his meeting today with Indonesian Defense
Minister General Edi Sudradjat in northern Australia's coastal
city of Adelaide.
</P>
<P>
"In particular, increased emphasis in the next 12 months will
be given to officer exchanges at junior levels," he said in the
statement.
</P>
<P>
A new scheme, called the Defense Cooperation Scholarship
Scheme,
has been established to support post graduate study for young
military officers with leadership potential, McLachlan said.
</P>
<P>
"The defense ministers agreed that this was an important
investment in the long-term future of a close bilateral
relationship," he said.
</P>
<P>
In a major speech earlier this week, McLachlan outlined the
move to even greater regional defense cooperation, on the basis of
the steps taken by the previous Labor government.
</P>
<P>
McLachlan said today his meeting with General Sudradjat was
part of the annual bilateral talks on security and defense issues.
</P>
<P>
He said Indonesia was Australia's most significant regional
neighbor and regular open dialogue was important to the
maintenance of regional stability.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the two ministers also reviewed current
cooperative defense activities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
