<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Problems of Early Sexual Maturity Cited by Doctor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, November 13 (Xinhua) -- Shi Yumin, a paediatrician at
Shanghai Paediatrics Hospital (SPH), has expressed concern about
the growing number of children with signs of early sexual maturity.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Shi said one of the effects of early sexual development is
shorter stature. The final height of about 30 percent of
early-maturing girls does not exceed 150 centimeters (5 feet), he
said.
</P>
<P>
This early sexual maturity also can impair children's
psychological makeup, he said, particularly when children's
intelligence and sexual maturity levels are
incompatible. Depression in such children is one of the problems
that result, he added.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Shi said early sexual maturity can be traced to two main
reasons: pathological, such as an endocrine imbalance; and
external, such as ingesting medicine or food containing hormones.
</P>
<P>
Parents should keep medicine out of the reach of children and
be careful about their food intake, he said.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Shi said that Ginseng royal jelly has been proven through
testing to induce early sexual maturity. Milk, pork and chicken
may contribute, he said, but at this time there is inadequate
proof.
</P>
<P>
One SPH clinic, open one day a week, used to treat 500 to 800
such patients weekly. Now the department, open five days a week,
treats 150 patients daily. Four other hospitals in Shanghai, which
have similar departments, have reported similar patient loads.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
