<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hainan Province of China Controls Industrial Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAINAN, November 13 (Xinhua) -- China's southernmost island
province of Hainan has adopted stringent measures to control
industrial pollution, with the forced closure of 75 factories
creating serious wastes.
</P>
<P>
Approximately 33 percent of the province's rubber and cement
plants fulfill national standards. Control efforts have reduced
the annual discharge of liquid waste by 56 million tons and gas
emissions by 18 million cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
The province has also introduced a program to control pollution
created by 30 sugar refineries, which release more than 30
million tons of waste water annually.
</P>
<P>
The rubber, cement and sugar sectors are the backbone
industries in the province. However, related plants have seriously
polluted the environment due to obsolete equipment and
technology.  
</P>
</TEXT>
