<HEADLINE> Former LA Times Business Chief Arrested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Ex-editorial business
chief of the Los Angeles Times, the second largest newspaper in
the United States, was arrested today, the Associated Press
reported.
</P>
<P>
Charles Boesch, 53, was accused of stealing 800,000
U.S. dollars by billing the newspaper for free-lance articles that
were not written at all.
</P>
<P>
Boesch, who was fired in July, had been using fake invoices and
article summaries between October 17, 1993 and January 29, 1997,
and submitting them to the Times accounting department for payment
to outside accomplices, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Boesch's former son-in-law, Michael Coburn, was also arrested
as an alleged accomplice and being held in lieu of 500,000 dollars
bail. Jacqueline Barrios, a third defendant, was charged in the
case but remained at large. Each was charged with a single count
of grand theft.
</P>
<P>
Deputy District Attorney Brent Collier said that Boesch and
Coburn will face a maximum sentence of five years in prison if
convinced. Barrios could be sentenced to up to three years.
</P>
</TEXT>
