<HEADLINE> Russia to Return French Archives Seized in World War II </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, November 13 (Xinhua) -- Russia will return all French
archives seized by the Soviet troops in Berlin at the end of World
War II, Agence France-Presse (AFP) reported today.
</P>
<P>
A France-Russia commission will meet next month to study the
way to return these archives, which were taken to Germany from
France by German troops in 1940, and submit a report to the
parliaments of the two countries for approval.
</P>
<P>
French President Jacques Chirac personally asked Russia to
return the archives "as soon as possible" during his visit to
Moscow in September, said the French news agency.
</P>
<P>
Most of the archives, which numbered at more than 900,000 and
were dated between the two world wars, are on national security
issues, including the private archives of the well-known French
politician Leon Blum, the Rothschild family, the episcopate of the
Roman Catholic Church in Strasbourg and Jewish associations.
</P>
<P>
AFP quoted Vladimir Semago, member of the Russian State Duma
and coordinator of the France-Russia commission on the archives,
as saying that Russia had already sent back 95 percent of those
French archives.
</P>
<P>
He said that it is the moral obligation of Russia to return the
remaining French archives which belong to the French
people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu to Hold National Unity Talk With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 13 (Xinhua) -- In a step toward realizing
his call for national unity, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu is expected to hold a conciliation talk with opposition
Labor leader Ehud Barak late this month.
</P>
<P>
This was announced Wednesday night by lawmaker Yehuda Harel, a
senior member of the coalition party The Third Way which is
making intense efforts to create a national unity government.
</P>
<P>
Harel's statement came after Public Security Minister Avigdor
Kahalani, head of The Third Way, held a meeting with Netanyahu
Wednesday night to discuss the possibility of forming a unity
government between the largest parties the Likud and Labor.
</P>
<P>
Kahalani believed that a national unity government is
necessary at a time when the division among the society is
deepening and the peace process is facing tremendous difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Harel revealed that Netanyahu planned to invite Labor leader
Barak for holding a conciliatory meeting after his return from
the visit to the United States next week. Netanyahu departed
today for a visit to Britain and the U.S..
</P>
<P>
Kahalani also met with Barak after his meeting with Netanyahu
on the unity government talk, but it remains unclear whether Barak
has agreed to accept the Third Way initiative. Harel added that if
the Netanyahu-Barak meeting is held, it would be a step in the
direction of forming a national unity government.
</P>
<P>
Kahalani reportedly threatened to recommend that his party
leave the coalition unless a unity government is formed.
</P>
<P>
Kahalani's initiative was launched at a time when Israel is
marking the second anniversary of the assassination of later
Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin.
</P>
<P>
Rabin was killed two years ago by Yigal Amir, a radical Jew who
was widely believed to be incited by the rightist activists who
depicted Rabin as a Jewish traitor because of his peace policies.
</P>
<P>
Then Likud leader Netanyahu was held for partially responsible
for launching the inciting campaign against Rabin that led to his
assassination.
</P>
<P>
The leftist camp is taking advantage of the second anniversary
of Rabin' death to pressure Netanyahu to offer an official apology
for his role in Rabin's murder, but was turned down. The rightist
camp charged the leftists for politically exploiting the murder of
Rabin to launch an inciting campaign of its own.
</P>
<P>
Security experts warned recently that because of the deepening
division of the Israeli society and the political tension,
political assassinations are possible to occur.
</P>
<P>
To prevent further internal division, some politicians issued
calls for national conciliation. Netanyahu in recent speeches has
calmed his tone and called for national reconciliation, saying he
is extending his hands out to the opposition for that sake.
</P>
<P>
Knesset (Parliament) Speaker Dan Tichon, spoke at the ceremony
marking Rabin's death, urged the Likud and Labor to join hands in
forming a unity government to heal the internal division and deal
with the difficulties facing the Israeli-Arab peace process.
</P>
<P>
But Labor officials cast doubt over the possibility of forming
a unity government with Netanyahu-led Likud. Yossi Beilin, senior
Labor lawmaker, said national unity is important for the nation
but labor would not do so with Netanyahu, who he described as
"someone not fit to be premier." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
