<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Presents Positive Report on Israeli Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 13 (Xinhua) -- Israel's economy is
"generally positive" and the medium-term prospects are
"favorable," but only as long as the "right policies are
pursued," according to an International Monetary Fund's (IMF)
report.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post reported today that after 10 days of
meeting with Israeli government officials, businessmen and
economists, an IMF team handed its initial annual report to
Israeli Finance Minister Yaacov Neeman and Bank of Israel
Governor Jacob Frenkel.
</P>
<P>
The five-page document said "the Israeli current fiscal policy
is well on its way to meeting the deficit target despite
difficult economic circumstances."
</P>
<P>
Inflation has been brought within the target range, the
current-account deficit has become more manageable and the
slowdown in economic growth appears to have come to a halt, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
However, it said that as labor force growth slows, economic
growth will have to rely on faster labor productivity growth,
which can only be achieved through greater investment and
technical progress.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government needs to do more than merely achieving
its fiscal aim of a budget deficit of 1.5 percent of the gross
domestic product by 2001, the report said, adding that there is
"a strong case for greater fiscal adjustment, namely to achieve,
at a minimum, approximate balance in terms of the government's
accounting system by 2001."
</P>
<P>
It is now time for Israel to act as part of the advanced world
and "play its leadership role in promoting better economic
performance world over through its own unwavering efforts to
stick to appropriate policies," the report noted.
</P>
<P>
The four-member IMF team will work out the final version of
the report on the Israeli economy in Washington in the coming
months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Chief Calls for Setting Up Surveillance Group </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, November 13 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) said here today that Asian
countries are more in the need of setting up a regional
surveillance group, than a regional fund, in order to prevent
another currency crisis from reoccurring.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Michel Camdessus, Managing
Director of the IMF, said that this surveillance system will serve
Asia better than the proposed Asian Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus, who arrived here on Wednesday on a two-day visit as
part of his Southeast Asia tour, said regional countries should
look at prevention rather than the creation of a standby fund to
bail out another crisis in the future.
</P>
<P>
He therefore called for the establishment of a regional
surveillance system so that Asian economies can use "peer
pressure" to alert each other of potential problems.
</P>
<P>
The IMF leader noted that from his recent experience in trying
to work out assistance packages for countries such as Thailand and
Indonesia that the regional financing was not in short supply to
bail out troubled economies.
</P>
<P>
Instead, what was missing was a regional surveillance system to
alert countries to potential trouble, he stressed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
