<HEADLINE> Digital Broadcasting to Be Launched in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 13 (Xinhua) -- Direct digital broadcasting
via satellite is scheduled to be launched next year in Nairobi to
enable customers' access to more programs with better quality,
according to a Daily Nation report today.
</P>
<P>
The digital broadcasting is sponsored by the Washington-based
WorldSpace which is aimed at providing affordable crisp-sounding
music and talk radio to 4.6 billion people in Africa, Asia, the
Middle East, the Caribbean and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
WorldSpace Chairman Noah Samara who is on a visit to Kenya
said Wednesday that once launched, the digital broadcasting would
enable customers to receive direct transmission of Kenya
Broadcasting Corporation programs anywhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
He noted that news and entertainment radio programs would be
transmitted to the satellite which is capable of broadcasting 288
channels and then beamed down over the vast regions.
</P>
<P>
The Nairobi launch will be followed by others in Asia and
Latin America in 1999, Samara said.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Minister for Information and Broadcasting Johnstone
Makau told Samara on Wednesday that "in this era of the
information superhighway, we are determined to be active
participants in the global village."
</P>
<P>
The minister stressed that "the (African) continent may find
itself unable to actively participate in the global economy if it
was left behind in terms of communications technology." 
</P>
</TEXT>
