<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Passes Law on Registration of Foreign Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, November 13 (Xinhua) -- The Iranian Majlis approved
a law Wednesday to allow foreign firms to register in the
country, the Iranian official news agency IRNA reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to the law, any legal foreign companies can
register their overseas branches or representative offices in Iran
within the framework of Iran's regulations.
</P>
<P>
However, the authorization is subject to reciprocal arrangements
with their respective countries, allowing Iranian firms to have
representation in those countries.
</P>
<P>
It also obligated the foreign firms to confine their
activities within the Iranian laws, rules and regulations.
</P>
<P>
The executive circular pertaining to the enforcement of the
law will be forwarded by the Ministry of Finance and Economic
Affairs to the cabinet ministers for final approval.
</P>
<P>
Since the Islamic Revolution in 1979, foreign firms were not
allowed to be legally represented and any activities in Iran
required a special authorization from the government.
</P>
<P>
The Approval of the law was considered here as a new step by
the Iranian government to attract more foreign investment in the
country's oil and gas industries, in an effort to defuse the
U.S. economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that the Iranian Oil Ministry would put forward
some projects for foreign companies to invest in Iran's offshore
oil and gas fields.
</P>
<P>
At present about 30 foreign companies are active in Iran.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 09:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Levy Waiting for Formal Invitation to Doha </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 13 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Foreign Minister
David Levy is still waiting for a formal invitation from Qatar to
attend the Doha conference, an unidentified Israeli Foreign Ministry
official said here today.
</P>
<P>
The Fourth Middle East and North Africa Economic Conference is
scheduled to convene in Qatari capital Doha Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The official said unless Levy receives a formal invitation from
the Qatari foreign minister requesting a one-on-one meeting,
Israel's delegation to the Doha conference would be led by a
lower-ranking official.
</P>
<P>
Levy's decision, which is expected to be announced today or
Friday, is also linked to the projected meeting of Israeli and
Palestinian joint committee chairmen in the West Bank city of
Jericho next Monday, a gathering to be attended by Levy and the
deputy head of the Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO) Mahmoud
Abbas, the official added.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli Foreign Ministry said earlier that Levy would
attend the opening ceremony of the Doha conference and then
return to Israel to attend the Jericho meeting.
</P>
<P>
Levy apparently has been troubled by the boycott of the
conference by a number of Arab countries, including Egypt, Syria,
Lebanon and Saudi Arabia and by the fact that those announcing
their participation -- Jordan, Kuwait and Oman -- are not sending
their foreign ministers.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Industry and Trade Minister Natan Sharansky would join
the delegation, which also includes dozens of government officials
and businessmen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
