<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Killing Incident Not Affect Albright's Visit: Pak FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, November 13 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister
Gohar Ayub Khan said here today the killing of four Americans will
cast no shadow over the forthcoming visit by U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright to Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
"The visit of U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright is
intact and she is scheduled to arrive here on Monday and hold
talks on Tuesday," Gohar said in a Senate session when answering
questions raised by opposition deputies.
</P>
<P>
The four Americans, who were employees of the Union Texas
Pakistan, and their Pakistani driver were gunned down early
Wednesday in Karachi, Pakistan's biggest port city, by some
unidentified gunmen. No individual or group has claimed
responsibility over the incident.
</P>
<P>
The investigation into the killing of four Americans is
progressing well and the government is following all possible
leads to track down the culprits, Gohar said.
</P>
<P>
"We are working on six or seven leads and hope will come to
some substantial outcome," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also disclosed that American investigation teams would be
arriving soon to Pakistan to coordinate into the probe.  
</P>
</TEXT>
