<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 09:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Against Azerbaijan's Oil Exploitation in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, November 13 (Xinhua) -- Iran has lodged a strong
protest to Azerbaijan's unilateral exploitation of oil from the
Cheragh reservoir of the Caspian Sea, Iranian official news agency
IRNA reported today.
</P>
<P>
The protest was made in a letter submitted to the
U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan Wenesday, in which Iran said
that Azerbaijan's unilateral exploitation of the mineral resources
in the seabed and the subsoil of the Caspian Sea was unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that Azerbaijan formally started its oil
exploitation in the Cheragh reservoir from Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The letter noted that Azerbaijan's decision contravened the
treaties and agreements signed between Iran and the former Soviet
Union during the past decades on exploitation of the mineral
resources in the Caspian Sea.
</P>
<P>
Those agreements are binding on the Republic of Azerbaijan,
one of the republics of the former Soviet Union, in accordance
with the customary norms of international law and the relevant
accords, the letter said.
</P>
<P>
It also warned that the full responsibility for consequences
of such illegal measures and actions, including damage caused to
other coastal states, rest with the states violating the legal
regime of the Caspian Sea.
</P>
<P>
The Caspian Sea is reported to have proven reserves of 16
billion barrels of crude oil and 8.3 trillion cubic meters of
natural gas. During the past years, Azerbaijan signed several
contracts with foreign companies to form a consortium to conduct
oil exploration and exploitation in the Caspian Sea, arousing
sharp criticism from other Caspian Sea states such as Iran.
</P>
<P>
Tehran stressed that a legal regime governing the Caspian Sea
should be reached unanimously by the five littoral states, namely,
Iran, Azerbaijan, Russia, Kazakhstan and Turkmenistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 09:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Bars US inspectors in Defiance of UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, November 13 (Xinhua) -- In defiance of a
U.N. resolution passed Wednesday, Iraq banned Americans today
from taking part in the U.N. arms inspections for the tenth time
running.
</P>
<P>
Five teams of the U.N. Special Commission in charge of
dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass destruction in Baghdad headed
this morning for a Baghdad site to carry out their mission, Iraqi
News Agency quoted an Iraqi official source as saying.
</P>
<P>
The source said that as the five teams arrived at the site,
the Iraqis in charge told them that they would be allowed to
enter with the exception of the Americans.
</P>
<P>
The source said that the U.N. inspectors decided to return to
their bases in Baghdad without carrying out any inspection of the
site.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council passed Wednesday unanimously a
resolution condemning Iraq for banning American U.N. arms
inspectors and slapped a ban on travel abroad by Iraqi officials
impeding U.N. arms inspection teams from doing their duties.
</P>
</TEXT>
