<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan Herdsmen Benefit From Cashmere Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, November 13 (Xinhua) -- Cashmere has become a new means
of improving the lives of Tibetan herdsmen.
</P>
<P>
For the past three years, herdsmen in Ngari Prefecture have
spent 3.84 million yuan on a breeding farm for cashmere production
and now have 376 households in cashmere production raising 70,000
sheep.
</P>
<P>
Last year, cashmere output in Ngari Prefecture was 234 tons and
the average income was 2,500 yuan per household.
</P>
<P>
Tibetan herdsmen have traditionally measured their fortune by
the number of head of cattle, and are now learning new technology
for raising livestock.
</P>
<P>
Gama Tarqin of Rutog County sold 60 head of cattle and bought
180 sheep over the past three years and now has more than 500
sheep, which brought his family more than 30,000 yuan last year.
</P>
<P>
With the profits he was able to buy a truck and tractor to
expand his cashmere business and explains, "I did not get rid of
poverty even though I had more than 300 head of cattle in the
past, but I am better off from cashmere production now."
</P>
<P>
Many herdsmen in Rutog County, like Gama Tarqin, have bought
tractors and trucks, and have built new houses that are furnished
with TV sets, washing machines and sewing machines. And they are
using new technology to expand cashmere production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li: China to Gradually Open Financial, Service Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, November 13 (Xinhua) -- China will gradually open its
financial, trade and other service sectors to foreign investors,
Chinese Premier Li Peng said here today.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese premier made the statement in a speech at a
luncheon hosted in his honor by the Federation of Economic
Organization of Japan.
</P>
<P>
Li said that China will take further measures to perfect its
laws and regulations and protect the rights and interests of
foreign investors, so as to create a better trade and investment
environment.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese premier, who arrived here Tuesday for a six-day
official good-will visit to Japan, said, "the world is quickening
its step toward multi-polarization. To strengthen economic and
technological cooperation among countries and seek common
development have become an important characteristic in
international relations."
</P>
<P>
Li said his country would firmly carry out its opening-up
policy. By the year 2000, the total trade volume of both import
and export is expected to reach 400 billion U.S. dollars, which
will provide more opportunities for China and other countries to
cooperate in economic and commercial fields.
</P>
<P>
China cut off its average tariffs once again recently
from 23 percent to 17 percent, a fall of 26 percent, nearing the
average level of the developing countries, Li said.
</P>
<P>
Li, "next year China will apply preferential
policies to foreign-invested projects which conform to Chinese
industrial policy, especially those of high and new technology and
imports of advanced equipment."
</P>
<P>
"China continues to encourage foreign investments in
agriculture, energy and transportation," Li said.
</P>
<P>
But the Chinese premier said China could not open its stock
market soon nor completely liberalize the exchange of the Chinese
currency to foreign ones, because China is at the stage of moving
from a planned economy to a socialist market economy.
</P>
<P>
The economic growth of China in 1997 is expected to exceed 9
percent and inflation will remain below 2 percent. The Chinese
economy is entering a good period characterized by a faster growth
but a relatively low inflation rate.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
