<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 30 Journalists to Be Tried over Rwanda Massacre </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, November 13 (Xinhua) -- At least 30 journalists
will be tried by the International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda
(ICTR) for their involvement in the 1994 genocide.
</P>
<P>
Craig McConaghy, the ICTR Legal Officer, said on Wednesday
that more than 30 journalists are suspected to have participated
in or encouraged the massacre.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian newspaper quoted the official as saying that the
ICTR, based in north Tanzania's Arusa, was holding two radio
journalists and two radio directors.
</P>
<P>
The remaining 26 were being held in Rwanda, allegedly for
participating in the massacre.
</P>
<P>
McConaghy, who is also responsible for investigating the role
of the media in the Rwanda genocide, said no print media
journalists had so far been identified to have been involved in
the genocide, saying "So far, most of the suspected journalists
come from radio stations only."
</P>
<P>
He said the suspects had made announcements aimed at promoting
political propaganda that fueled the massacre.
</P>
<P>
McConaghy is attending the East African Media Workshop with
the theme of "Towards a Strong and Responsible Media in the
Region by the year 2000," organized by the Media Institute of
Southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
He said the journalists used Radio Television Libre Des Mille
Collines (RTLM) to urge the Hutu extremists to be aware of the
enemies and be prepared to fight a total war when the time came.
</P>
<P>
According to RTLM, the enemy was the Rwanda Patriotic Front
(RPF) and its accomplices who were Tutsis living within Rwanda as
well as moderate Hutus in favor of the democratic process.
</P>
<P>
During the genocide, Radio Rwanda which was used by Hutu
extremists and RTLM, broadcast calls for violence against Tutsi
population whereas RTLM targeted fat bellies for death.
</P>
<P>
Sometimes radio broadcasts even mentioned the names of
individuals being sought, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
