<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng Urges Japan to Export More High-tech to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, November 13 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng here
today called on Japanese businessmen to provide China with the
most advanced technology and products of the highest quality.
</P>
<P>
Li made the call in a speech at a luncheon hosted in his honor
by the Federation of Economic Organizations of Japan.
</P>
<P>
He said after about two decades of reform and opening up,
China's market has undergone profound changes and Chinese
consumers have greater demand for better products.
</P>
<P>
The premier suggested that Japanese businessman abandon their
old concept about China and grasp the opportunity by making their
capital, technology and service more competitive in the Chinese
market.
</P>
<P>
He urged Japanese businessmen to provide China with their most
advanced technology and brand-name products of the highest
quality, so that they can beat other foreign investors in the
competition.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese premier said as the biggest developing country in
the world, with rich natural and labor resources, China has an
economy that has gained unprecedented momentum, thus offering a
huge potential market for foreign capital.
</P>
<P>
Japan, as one of the most developed countries, has abundant
funds, advanced technology and rich experience in management, Li
added.
</P>
<P>
The two countries' economies are highly complementary and
therefore cooperation will surely benefit both.
</P>
<P>
There is a broad prospect for this cooperation, Li said. China
is now reforming its state-owned enterprises, a golden chance for
Japanese investors.
</P>
<P>
Li noted the smooth development of bilateral relations shows
that difference in social systems and ideologies should be no
obstacle to economic cooperation. China is opposed to placing
man-made hurdles to cooperation in trade and economy.
</P>
<P>
He said China appreciates the Japanese government's support for
China's entry into the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral trade between the two neighboring countries,
enormously boosted since the normalization of diplomatic relations
in 1972, has reached 60 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
China is now Japan's second largest trading partner while
Japan, which has been China's biggest trading partner for four
successive years, is China's second largest source of foreign
capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
