<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Chief Optimistic on Asian Economic Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, November 13 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) said here today that Asia will
quickly rebound from its current crisis and be able to return to
high rates of economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Michel Camdessus, Managing Director of the IMF, said at a press
conference that the achievements made by Southeast Asian countries
in the past decade were by no means wiped out by the developments
in recent months.
</P>
<P>
The region's long-term fundamentals, including high domestic
savings rates, strong fiscal position, dynamic private sectors and
recent gains in competitiveness, remained basically favorable.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus, who arrived here on Wednesday on a two day visit as
part of his Southeast Asian tour, said that his message to the
countries in the region is: "The crisis is not necessarily a
blight on the future but, more probably, a blessing in disguise".
</P>
<P>
"Indeed, after this period of adjustment, these economies will
emerge stronger than before," he stressed, adding that the turmoil
served as an eye-opener which helped countries in the region to
recognize the weaknesses in their economies.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus said that Southeast Asian countries still have a long
way to go to catch up with the advanced economies. Therefore, "the
potential for growth is there" and, with sound policies, countries
in the region should be able to sustain high rates of growth for
another two decades or more, he pointed out.  
</P>
</TEXT>
