<HEADLINE> Creditors' Meeting on Zambia Deferred </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, November 13 (Xinhua) -- A meeting of Zambia's
creditors scheduled for next month has been postponed because of
the slow pace of privatization in the country's copper mines, the
World Bank has said.
</P>
<P>
The Times of Zambia today quoted World Bank Deputy
Representative in Lusaka, Richard Beardmore, as saying that the
meeting has been put off until next year.
</P>
<P>
The action means that the Zambian government will have to draw
up its 1998 budget without guarantee of aid.
</P>
<P>
One third of the country's 1.1 billion U.S. dollars budget in
1997 was made up by aid.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank is waiting for the privatization of Zambian
Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM), Beardmore noted.
</P>
<P>
The country may go through part of 1998 without donor inflows,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank is also waiting for an assessment of the
country's macro-economic performance from the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) before calling the meeting of donors.
</P>
<P>
IMF representative Elwaleed Taha for Zambia said last week
that IMF was pleased with its economic performance over the past
several months.
</P>
<P>
Taha said IMF will resume negotiations with the government on
the country's enhanced structural adjustment facility in
December.
</P>
<P>
The consultative group of creditors traditionally meets in
December to make pledges to Zambia ahead of its announcement of
the annual budget in January.
</P>
<P>
In 1996 the consultative group meeting was deferred
indefinitely after donors cut aid to the country over governance
concerns. Aid has however resumed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
