<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Current Account Surplus Reaches $50 Billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, November 13 (Xinhua) -- Japan's current account surplus
for the first half of fiscal 1997 is 5,806.0 billion yen (48.98
U.S. billion dollars), or 75.7 percent up from a year earlier, the
Finance Ministry said in a preliminary report today.
</P>
<P>
The ministry attributed the rise, the first in eight half-year
periods since April-September 1993, to brisk exports of items such
as automobiles helped by the weak yen against the U.S. dollar and
by favorable economic conditions abroad.
</P>
<P>
In goods and services trading during the April-September
period, Japan produced a surplus of 2,914.4 billion yen (24.5
billion dollars), about 4.5 times the surplus of a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Export growth outpaced the rise in imports in merchandise
trade, while the deficit in services trading shrank from a year
before due partly to the increase in the number of foreigners
visiting Japan, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Japan's surplus in merchandise trade in the April-September
period rose by 52.7 percent from a year earlier to 6,249.3 billion
yen (52.6 billion dollars), the first increase in nine half-year
periods.
</P>
<P>
Exports expanded by 15.6 percent to 24,579.1 billion yen (206.9
billion dollars), rising for the seventh straight half-year
period, while imports advanced by 6.7 percent to 18,329.9 billion
yen (154.3 billion dollars), also up for the seventh successive
half-year period, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
In service trade, including tourism, Japan posted a deficit of
3,334.8 billion yen (28.1 billion dollars), down from a deficit of
3,444.1 billion yen (29.0 billion dollars) a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
The current account balance measures the flow of goods and
services as well as investment and other monetary transfers.
</P>
<P>
In September alone, Japan's current account surplus rose by
109.5 percent from a year earlier to 723.4 billion yen (6.1
billion dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Travel Agencies Expand, But Profit Margin Declines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 13 (Xinhua) -- Chinese travel agencies
handling overseas tourists have expanded, but their profit margins
have declined, a survey shows.
</P>
<P>
All the 959 "international travel agencies" operating in 1996
took part in an annual survey conducted by the China National
Tourism Administration.
</P>
<P>
The result of the survey announced recently indicates the gross
business of international travel agencies amounted to 20.2 billion
yuan (about 2.437 billion U.S. dollars) in 1996, a year-to-year
increase of 17.4 percent, while the average was 22.28 million
yuan, a rise of 20.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-three agencies exceeded 100 million yuan each,
accounting for 3.6 percent of the total; and 622 agencies ranged
between 1 million yuan and 22.28 million yuan each, accounting for
68.5 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
"This shows large travel agencies only make up a small portion
of the business in China," a tourist official said.
</P>
<P>
The survey also reveals that the profit margin for travel
agencies stood at 3 percent in 1996, 0.4 percentage point lower
than the previous year.
</P>
<P>
"This shows that with the constant expansion in business scale,
the competition has been getting tougher and tougher, triggering
the need for travel agencies to improve their way of doing
business," said the official.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
