<HEADLINE> NKP, DP Announce Merger Agreement in SKorea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, November 13 (Xinhua) -- New Korea Party (NKP) and
Democratic Party (DP) today announced an merger agreement, making
the NKP's Lee Hoi-chang the unified presidential candidate and the
DP's Cho Soon president of the united party.
</P>
<P>
Lee and Cho had agreed last Friday to merge their parties to a
unified party under a name of the Korea Democratic Party or New
Democratic Party, and to share the posts in the new party by the
NKP taking 70 percent and the DP claiming the rest.
</P>
<P>
The merger turns the December 18 presidential election into a
three-way race.
</P>
<P>
As former Seoul mayor Cho Soon, known as an economic expert and
honest administrator, gave up his presidential bid to support the
NKP's Lee Hoi-chang, Lee's lowest popularity is expected to boost.
</P>
<P>
Latest opinion polls, launched by major dailies over the
weekend, showed that Lee has regained over 20 percent support,
still trailing behind unified opposition candidate Kim Dae-jung
with 30 percent, but has narrowed the gap with Rhee In-je' 20 plus
percent.
</P>
<P>
Pollsters attributed Lee's surge in popularity to the merger
and NKP officials expected Lee's popularity to further improve.
</P>
<P>
At a joint press conference after the merger announcement, Lee
and Cho highlighted their united front against the opposition
alliance between the National Congress for New Politics (NCNP) and
the United Liberal Democrats (ULD) which supports NCNP leader Kim
Dae-jung.
</P>
<P>
They criticized that the opposition coalition is nothing more
than a strategy to extend the politics of the three Kims -
President Kim Young-sam, NCNP's Kim Dae-jung as well as ULD's Kim
Jong-pil who were active in the political stage through the past
three decades.
</P>
<P>
While the former ruling party appeals for the conclusion of the
three Kims era, opposition leading runner Kim Dae-jung appeals for
government transfer and 49-year-old Rhee In-je is asking for a
general innovation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
