<HEADLINE> Survey Finds Beijing Residents Becoming Environment-Conscious </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 13 (Xinhua) -- A recent survey shows that
most residents in the Chinese capital think the city has serious
environmental problems.
</P>
<P>
Eighty-nine percent of a total 2,317 people responding to an
environmental survey said they are dissatisfied or very
dissatisfied with Beijing's environmental quality.
</P>
<P>
The respondents listed air pollution, solid waste, water
contamination and noise as the top four environmental problems
that should be immediately addressed.
</P>
<P>
While only eight percent of the people said their present
living environment is okay, over 70 percent expressed their
confidence in the improvement of Beijing's environmental quality
by 2010, according to the survey which was conducted in Beijing
and its 18 satellite counties and towns by Beijing Environmental
Protection Bureau, Beijing Environmental Protection Fund and
Beijing Evening News.
</P>
<P>
The survey found more people are becoming environmentally
conscious: 92 percent of those surveyed said they would choose to
buy environmentally-friendly refrigerators despite the higher cost.
</P>
<P>
More than 60 percent said they would be willing to donate to
environmental protection causes.
</P>
<P>
When asked how they react to activities that cause pollution,
36 percent said they would get directly involved, while 45 percent
said they would report to authorities concerned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
