<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Analysis: Currency Worries Test Hong Kong's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 13 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's competitiveness,
which is arguably eroded by the high cost of wages and property
prices, is now facing a further challenge in the wake of the Asian
currency turmoil.
</P>
<P>
The city has become relatively expensive for foreign tourists
and overseas importers, as speculative attacks triggered the
depreciation of a string of currencies in the region and left
Hong Kong dollar's peg to the greenback unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Cheaper prices might improve exports, but economists here
warned that devaluation is not the right answer to
competitiveness. "A lower-price strategy will not be sustainable
if it is not matched by real gains in efficiency or productivity,"
said Dr. Chan Wai-kwan, assistant director of the Hong Kong
General Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
"Devaluation for its own sake is not competitiveness," said
Chan," it is beggar-thy-neighbor. If devaluation worked, then
economies would be competing to make their currencies cheaper."
</P>
<P>
A recent economic report by the Hong Kong and Shanghai Banking
Corporation (HSBC) says: "The immediate impact [of the devaluation
of Asian currencies] is not expected to be overly significant."
</P>
<P>
The report argues that there is a limited overlap between Hong
Kong products and that of the other Asian economies, and the
increasing demand for services from the China's inland areas will
partly offset the loss of business opportunities for Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Andrew Fernow, research head of Vickers Ballas Hong Kong
Limited also stressed the role of services, which now account for
more than 80 percent of Hong Kong's GDP, compared with less than
10 percent for manufacturing. "The issue of competitiveness must
be addressed in consideration of the city's role as one of the
world's leading financial and business centers," he said.
</P>
<P>
He did not think that substantial devaluation would attract
firms to move their headquarters and regional offices into
Southeast Asian countries where still lack the necessary
infrastructure and advanced information technology.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua, Prof. Y. C. Jao at the School of
Economics and Finance, University of Hong Kong, said: "Hong Kong's
advantage lies in its strong adaptability and high flexibility,
which have helped the city go through many difficult times and
quickly regain its strength over the past decades."
</P>
<P>
In his view, competitiveness should be achieved through raising
productivity, lowering costs, enhancing education, and applying
new technology.
</P>
<P>
High level of property prices has long been a worry for Hong
Kong's competitiveness. Prof. Jao argued that high prices,
determined by the market mechanism, indicate strong demand for
properties in Hong Kong, and the problem should be tackled still
by market forces, namely increasing supply.
</P>
<P>
Actually the interest rate-sensitive property sector has gone
downturn after Hong Kong's primary interest rates were pushed up
to fend off speculators. Prof. Jao said that the adjustment of
property prices, though painful, might be good for the long-term,
healthy development of Hong Kong's economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0238 </DOCNO>
