<HEADLINE> U.S.-Africa Trade Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 13 (Xinhua) -- James Carragher, Charge
d'Affairs of the United States embassy in Zimbabwe, said on
Wednesday that U.S. trade with Africa now stands at 21 billion
U.S. dollars, 18 percent higher than in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Carragher, said at a luncheon the U.S. hosted at its pavilion
at the Zimbabwe Business and Industrial Exhibition (ZIMBEX) in
Harare, that U.S.trade with the sub-Saharan Africa was
increasing, and the U.S. was Zimbabwe's fourth largest trading
partner.
</P>
<P>
"U.S. exports to Africa increased 14 percent above the 1995
level to 6.1 billion dollars," he said, adding that oil was
Africa's principal export to the U.S., which accounts for 90
percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
"U.S. direct investment in sub-Saharan Africa, which is
concentrated in petroleum, mining and manufacturing, grew from
3.6 billion dollars in 1995, or by 25 percent," noted Carragher.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the United States recently renewed its
program which allowed preferential entry of hundreds of new
products from developing countries, of which Zimbabwe is one of
the largest beneficiaries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
