<HEADLINE> Macedonian President Ends Visit to Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 13 (Xinhua) -- Macedonian President Kiro
Gligorov left here for home today after a four-day state visit to
Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
The visit witnessed the signing of two agreements -- one on
trade and the other on investment guarantee -- to expand bilateral
trade, economic and industrial cooperation between Macedonia and
Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
The Macedonia president held talks with Malaysian Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad on various bilateral political, economic
and trade issues.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Foreign Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi described the
talks as fruitful in terms of reinforcing bilateral ties and
identifying new areas of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Gligorov said at a press conference here Wednesday that more
joint banking services and other related facilities should be
established to boost trade between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He said that although there was already high level of political
cooperation between the two nations, similar understanding had yet
to be reflected in trade.
</P>
<P>
He invited Malaysian businessmen to participate in the
country's ongoing privatization program in nickel and zinc
production.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia was among the first Asia-Pacific countries to
recognize the Balkan state in 1992 following its emergence as a
free and independent nation of the former Yugoslavia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
