<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ to Boost Defense Spending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, November 13 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand will spend an
extra 663 million NZ dollars (411 million US dollars) over the
next five years, says a Government White Paper on defense released
this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The defense boost is aimed to soften critics who charge that NZ
is not contributing enough to the regional security. At present,
NZ spends 1.6 billion NZ dollars (990 million US dollars) a year
on defense.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Paul East said the extra spending provides a
much needed boost to NZ's essential defense requirements.
</P>
<P>
The extra money will be used to increase infantry numbers,
replace their old armored vehicles and buy new transport aircraft.
</P>
<P>
But the government will not buy any more Australian-made ANZAC
frigates. A plan to buy two more such warships has been turned
down by NZ First, the junior partner in the coalition.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand has already bought two ANZAC frigates at a total
cost of one billion NZ dollars (620 million US dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
