<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Cholera Cases Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, November 13 (Xinhua) -- A total of 139 cholera
positive cases have been reported since the epidemic was first
detected in September and the number of cholera cases is still
increasing, the Health Department said today.
</P>
<P>
Three or four new cases are reported daily. So far three
patients have died of the disease, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Chilaw in North Western Province where the first cholera
patient was found is the worst affected region.
</P>
<P>
Health Minister Nimal Siripala de Silva said his ministry had
adopted measures to avert a full blown cholera epidemic in the
country and called for public cooperation in combating the
epidemic.
</P>
<P>
A massive public education and health campaign had been
launched to contain the outbreak, he said.
</P>
<P>
A package of preventive methods were printed on the first pages
of local newspapers today, telling people to drink boiled water
and eat cooked food.
</P>
<P>
Local reports said the cholera bacteria was brought to Sri
Lanka by a group of people who had visited India on a pilgrimage
recently.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
