<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Schedules First Town Hall Meeting on Ethnicity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
has scheduled his first town hall meeting on race for December in
Akron, Ohio, and met with aides Wednesday to refocus his national
initiative to promote racial harmony in the country.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, along with Vice President Al Gore, made the
announcement at a meeting in the White House's Cabinet Room with a
half-dozen key aides and several members of his race advisory
board's staff.
</P>
<P>
Akron has took measures to deal with its racial problems. The
White House was impressed with a program called the Coming
Together Project, aimed at promoting awareness of other cultures
through the arts, and with an Akron newspaper's year-long Pulitzer
Prize-winning examination of race.
</P>
<P>
"We think Akron as a community has really stepped up to deal
honestly and openly on race relations," White House spokesman Joe
Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
A medium-sized city, Akron is 73 percent white, 24.5 percent
black and 2 percent Asian, Hispanic and American Indian.
</P>
<P>
Since its formation in June, the seven-member race advisory
board, headed by historian John Hope Franklin, has met only twice,
with a third meeting scheduled for next week.
</P>
<P>
Gore identified two areas that need to be addressed, officials
said -- fostering a broader understanding of the "unique
suffering" of minority and ethnic groups and the "unique
contributions" made by these groups.
</P>
<P>
There was also a decision to acknowledge that not all Americans
are struggling with race but are resolving racial problems in
creative ways.
</P>
<P>
The advisory board has posted a list of "promising practices"
on its Internet site, so that local communities can duplicate
those efforts. Akron's Coming Together Project is among them.
</P>
<P>
Other efforts include Cleveland's Residential Housing and
Mortgage Credit Project, which works to identify and address home
mortgage discrimination; PRIDE, an effort in Philadelphia to
promote discussions on race and ethnicity; and Team Harmony, a
Boston program that gets young people of all races involved in
various projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
