<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vigorous Debate on NATO Expansion Expected in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. administration is
still headed for a vigorous debate on the expansion of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) despite some positive results,
a senior U.S. official said today.
</P>
<P>
"We are just finishing an important and very intensive period
in our efforts to enlarge NATO by adding Poland, Hungary, and the
Czech Republic to the alliance," Jeremy Rosner, special assistant
to the U.S. secretary of state for NATO enlargement ratification
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The Senate has had nine full committee hearings on the
alliance's enlargement over the last 30 days by three different
Senate committees and is expected to vote on it early next year.
</P>
<P>
A majority vote of two-thirds is needed for its ratification.
</P>
<P>
Rosner praised a letter by Chairman Jesse Helms of the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee and ranking Democrat Joseph Biden that
gives strong support to the alliance's expansion.
</P>
<P>
"We would certainly agree with those observations, and we view
them as quite significant," Rosner said.
</P>
<P>
"Even so, even with these very positive results and this very
positive letter from the chairman and the ranking member, we think
that we are still headed for a vigorous debate on this issue in
the public and on Capitol Hill,"
</P>
<P>
"We would not yet say that we have the necessary two-thirds
votes in hand, but we see encouraging signs of senators stating
support for this," he noted.
</P>
<P>
"We think there will be a number of amendments, reservations,
conditions, understandings likely to be raised as part of the
process," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Also speaking at the press conference, Deputy Assistant
Secretary of State for European and Canadian Affairs Ronald Asmus
said that the debate is "the most comprehensive debate" in the
U.S. on European security since the end of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
"We feel quite comfortable and confident that we are coming out
of this debate with that commitment reaffirmed in this country,
and in the leadership and in the population as a whole," he said.
</P>
<P>
The 16-member NATO will convene a ministerial meeting in
December in Brussels to sign the protocols of accession for the
three states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
