<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Trade Gap with India Narrows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, November 13 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh had a trade gap with
India of 37.389 billion taka (834.6 million U.S dollars) in the
1996-97 fiscal year, down by 4.577 billion taka (90.6 million
dollars) compared with the previous fiscal year, the independent
United News of Bangladesh (UNB) reported here today.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed on Wednesday by Bangladeshi Education
Minister ASHK Sadique while replying to a question on foreign
trade in the Parliament in the absence of the commerce ministers.
</P>
<P>
The education minister said the trade gap with India was 41.97
billion taka ( 937 million dollars) during the 1995-96 fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the trade gap to go-slow demand of Bangladeshi
products in the Indian market. "We hope our exports to India would
rise as the result of government initiatives," he added.
</P>
<P>
In a written reply to a written question, Bangladeshi Commerce
Minister Tofail Ahmed said the government has taken a number of
measures to narrow the existing trade gap with the neighboring
country.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the government has attached importance to increasing
exports to the northeastern states of India in an effort to reduce
the gap, the minister added.
</P>
<P>
Noting that Bangladesh earned export income of 779.2 million
taka (1.74 million dollars) from India during the July-September
period of the current fiscal year, the commerce minister told the
Parliament that no information about imports from India during the
three-month period has been received.  
</P>
</TEXT>
