<HEADLINE> First Computer Communication System Introduced in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, November 13 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar has introduced the
first computer communication system in the country to improve its
telecommunication links at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
The packet switching of the Mayangon computer communication
exchange, which was inaugurated here Wednesday, signifies a major
advance in Myanmar's communication, official newspaper The New
Light of Myanmar today quoted a senior official as saying.
</P>
<P>
U Soe Tha, minister for communications, posts and telegraphs,
said data could be sent and received through the computer network
with computers outside the country, enabling foreign investors in
Myanmar to do their business speedily and efficiently.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Myanmar also introduced the first CDMA
radio-telephone system in the country last month, initiating a
total of 3,000 lines at two township stations in the capital of
Yangon.
</P>
<P>
Other communication systems such as digital micro-wave links
have already established in Myanmar since 1995, connecting the
capital of Yangon with nine other cities in the country.
</P>
<P>
An official report said that the local satellite stations
linking Yangon with 14 remote towns have been built and 64 more
ground stations for micro-wave links are under construction in the
country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
