<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crisis Speeds ASEAN Financial Liberalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, November 13 (Xinhua) -- The Asian financial crisis is
forcing ASEAN members to liberalize their financial sector earlier
than the World Trade Organization's required schedule, according
to Krirk-krai Jirapaet, Thai ambassador to the WTO.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN (the Association of Southeast Asian Nations) groups
Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Krirk-krai was quoted today by local press as saying that it
was unnecessary for developed countries to put pressure on ASEAN
members as the deadline for negotiations on liberalization had
been set for December 12.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund has urged ASEAN members to
accept its economic rescue package to allow foreigners to take
equity in local financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
Krirk-krai said the current economy would apply pressure on
Thailand, Malaysia and Indonesia to improve their offers on
liberalizing their financial sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
