<HEADLINE> Smog Comes to Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, November 13 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's Meteorological
Department has confirmed that many parts of the country have been
covered by a thin layer of smog coming from Indonesia over the
past few days.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Director of Meteorology Jayatilleke Banda today said the
smog layer was seen in satellite pictures they received Monday and
was confirmed Wednesday by the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration (NOAA) of the United States.
</P>
<P>
The cause of this smog is believed to have resulted from the
massive forest fires that erupted in Indonesia some weeks ago, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
He said the lifetime of the smog layer could not be counted.
</P>
<P>
The smog is spreading towards the Maldives and southern India
via Sri Lanka and the Bay of Bengal, according to the department.
</P>
<P>
Heavy smog produced by lasting fires in Indonesia has caused
severe disasters in Singapore, Thailand and other Southeast Asian
countries during the past weeks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
