<HEADLINE> News Analysis: El Nino Affects Asia's Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 13 (Xinhua) -- Eight months after it began to
hit Asian and Pacific Countries, the El Nino climate phenomenon is
expected to persist until next year and remains a big threat to
agricultural production in the region.
</P>
<P>
El Nino refers to the abnormal warming of sea surface
temperatures in the South Pacific, which erupts every two to seven
years and causes severe flooding and drought.
</P>
<P>
The 1982-1983 El Nino, the worst one in 100 years, caused 13
billion U.S. dollars in damage and killed 2,000 people in the
world.
</P>
<P>
However, experts warned that the current El Nino, which began
in March, could be among the severest in this century.
</P>
<P>
The worst effect will be felt over the next few months and
possibly extend into 1998 -- beyond its usual Christmas time peak,
they said.
</P>
<P>
During the past eight months, El Nino has unleashed severe
drought in parts of the Asian and Pacific region, affecting farm
production in Indonesia, Papua New Guinea, the Philippines,
Thailand, India, Australia and other countries.
</P>
<P>
In the northern Philippines, rainfall has been below normal
since May, affecting major rice and corn growing areas. The number
of typhoons, which bring significant amounts of rainfall, has been
fewer than normal in the whole country.
</P>
<P>
The Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) estimated that the
country's corn output in 1997-1998 will drop to 3.92 million tons
compared with the 4.22 million tons in the previous marketing
year.
</P>
<P>
Dry conditions in Indonesia would affect 300,000 hectares of
rice fields this year, according to the FAO.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's worst drought in half a century is expected to
continue into 1998, particularly in Southern Sumatra and
Kalimantan, Borneo, Java and eastern parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that Indonesia will have to import at least
300,000 tons of corn in the last quarter of this year to make up
for the shortfall caused by the drought.
</P>
<P>
In Papua New Guinea, about one million people have been hit by
the worst drought in 50 years and face food shortages. The FAO
reported that serious drought in this Pacific state would continue
until next January and possibly next March, and up to 50 percent
of the nation's coffee crop could be wiped out.
</P>
<P>
The most serious problem caused by El Nino is its effects on
the region's food production, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
But they also warned that El Nino will also cause serious water
shortages in some Asian and Pacific countries.
</P>
<P>
In the Philippine capital of Manila, the Metropolitan Water
Works and Sewerage System announced early this week that it will
reduce the water supply starting this month until July next year
due to the El Nino phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
"We have to reduce the supply because the current level of
water in Angat reservoir is now about 18 meters below the normal
level," said a spokesman of the company.
</P>
<P>
Facing a potential food and water crisis, countries in the
region have tried in one way or another to minimize losses caused
by El Nino.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government has allotted 2.2 billion pesos (about
65 million U.S. dollars) to combat the El Nino effects by building
9,000 wells and 20,000 small reservoirs and repairing irrigation
canals.
</P>
<P>
Countries such as Indonesia, Thailand and the Philippines have
started importing grains to ensure normal food supplies this year
and next.
</P>
<P>
At an El Nino conference here last week, experts discussed
strategies to cushion the El Nino effects.
</P>
<P>
They urged governments of drought-prone countries to encourage
farmers to diversify crops, plant drought-resistant varieties and
start water conservation programs.
</P>
<P>
Countries prone to flooding should strengthen drainage systems,
dams, canals and sea-walls to reduce the effects of destructive
floods, they suggested.
</P>
<P>
Other participants said that all countries should set up early
warning systems to detect damages to agricultural production and
its impact on food supply.
</P>
<P>
So long as people make better preparations, the El Nino effect
on Asia's agricultural production could be minimized, they said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
