<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Postal Workers Withdraw Strike Deadline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Canada's postal workers withdrew a
strike deadline for midnight today, saying it would present a new offer
to Canada Post.
</P>
<P>
"Based on our decision to break the impasse, we have decided to
withdraw the strike deadline," the Canadian Union of Postal Workers
said this evening.
</P>
<P>
Canada Post said it would examine the union's offer and make a
counter offer.
</P>
<P>
A postal workers' strike has threatened since the talks
between the union and the corporation broke off last weekend.
</P>
<P>
The talks stalled when the two sides disagreed on a
proposed 200 million dollars (140 million U.S.Dollars) reduction in labor
costs and wage increases.
</P>
<P>
The union said the reduction will mean 4,000 jobs lost, while the
corporation insisted no one will lose their job because work rules can
be adjusted to save money.
</P>
<P>
The union is asking for wage increases of more than eight percent
over 18 months, while Canada Post is offering increases of three
percent over two years.
</P>
<P>
The two sides are so far apart they need the threat of a strike or
lockout to reach an agreement, according to the conciliator appointed
to help settle the labour dispute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
