<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Parliamentary Leaders Hail Yeltsin's China Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Russian parliamentary leaders
said here today that President Boris Yeltsin's just-finished China
visit will further Russia-China ties to a higher level.
</P>
<P>
In a joint press conference, Vladimir Ryzhkov, first deputy
speaker of the Russian State Duma, and Vasily Likhachev, deputy
speaker of the Federation Council, expressed satisfaction with the
Russia-China summit, which ended Tuesday in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The two deputy speakers were members of Yeltsin's entourage on
his China trip.
</P>
<P>
Ryzhkov said Russia-China relations enjoy priority in Russian
foreign policies. There were not any political disputes between
Russia and China, and the Russia-China border issue had been
settled once and for all, he said.
</P>
<P>
The first State Duma speaker said Russia and China should
expand trade cooperation in a bid to push the bilateral trade
turnover to 20 billion U.S. dollars in the year 2,000.
</P>
<P>
Likhachev said Russian and Chinese leaders have already started
forging bilateral and international relations oriented to the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
He said the upper house adopted a positive attitude toward
cooperation between Russia and China.
</P>
<P>
During Yeltsin's November 9-11 China tour, the two sides signed
a series of agreements to enhance bilateral trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin and Chinese President Jiang Zemin also declared that
the surveying and marking of the eastern border between the two
nations had finished and work on the west part would finish in the
near future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
