<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek Cabinet Approves 1998 Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The Greek cabinet has approved
the 1998 budget today with an aim of consolidating national
economic stability.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after the cabinet session on the budget, government
spokesman Dimitris Reppas said the budget is "consistent,
efficient, growth-oriented and equitable."
</P>
<P>
Noting that it would help reach targets set by the Greek
government for joining the European Union's Economic and Monetary
Union (EMU), he said the package represents a continuation of the
1997 budget.
</P>
<P>
Greece plans to enter the EMU by 2001 but will keep the Drachma
out of the Exchange Rate Mechanism (ERM) before joining the EU's
single currency.
</P>
<P>
Greek Finance Minister Yiannos Papantoniou said today that the
budget also aims to keep the deficit at 2.4 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Under the budget, consumer price inflation, currently 4.7
percent, will fall to 2.5 percent by the end of 1998, and
unemployment, now 9.7 percent, to 9.2 percent, while GDP growth
rate will go up from the present 3.5 percent to 3.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Innovations in the budget are the introduction of an inflation-
linked tax scale of up to 5.7 percent, and a new flexible tax on
mobile phones to be determined by use.
</P>
<P>
The budget also supports the young unemployed by planning to
create 200,000 jobs by 2000.
</P>
<P>
The Greek government will speed up its privatization program by
abolishing or merging 1,750 public sector agencies in order to
increase revenue and cut spending. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
