<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Calls For Peaceful Settlement of Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November 13 (Xinhua) -- Concerned about developments
in Iraq, Indonesia urged all parties involved to exercise
self-restraint and immediately end their conflicts to avoid a
possible recurrence of the Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
"We (Indonesia) do not want to see a war again in the region or
arms being used like several years ago," Foreign Minister Ali
Alatas said here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He said increasing sanctions on Iraq was not the answer to the
problem but would even complicate the situation, adding that the
sanction imposed so far had not met any target or fulfilled the
hopes but had caused grief among the civilian population,
including women, children and old people.
</P>
<P>
"So I think increasing sanctions is not the way out although I
admit that the problem is complicated," officials at the Foreign
Ministry today quoted the minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
Alatas said Indonesia hoped Iraq would meet its obligations in
line with the UN resolution as its defiance would only be used by
other countries to take actions against it.
</P>
<P>
The United States has continued to ask the UN Security Council
to impose a new sanction to make Iraq willing to accept the UN
weapon inspectors to take a close look at the country's weapon
system.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has banned U.S. weapon inspectors from entering into Iraq.
The United States has not ruled out the use of military forces in
retaliation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
