<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mercosur to Raise Tariffs on External Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Countries of the
Southern Common Market (Mercosur) will sign an accord to increase
the External Common Tariff (ECT) applied to imports from other
countries, imports, Brazilian Foreign Minister Luiz Felipe
Lampreia confirmed today.
</P>
<P>
Lampreia said Argentina has proposed a three percent rise in
ECT, and this is being considered by Brazil.
</P>
<P>
By 2001, most of the ECT charges will be rescinded, and those
applied to telecommunications and computing will disappear in 2006.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said the increase of the tariff was part
of Brazil`s efforts to increase tax-related public income, and to
help improve the trading balance. Paraguay and Uruguay had also
shown their agreement with the measure.
</P>
<P>
Mercosur, the largest trade bloc in South America, groups
Brazil, Argentina, Uruguay and Paraguay, with its associate
members being Chile and Bolivia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> El Nino to Blame for Food Shortage: FAO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, November 12 (Xinhua) -- El Nino, the adverse weather
phenomenon that brings disasters to many countries, is to be
blamed for the increasingly chronic global food shortage, a food
report said today.
</P>
<P>
The report, released by the Rome-based United Nations Food and
Agriculture Organization (FAO), said: "Although in developing
countries, cereal production in 1997 is forecast to decline only
slightly from last year's good level, the number of countries
facing food emergencies in 1997 has increased to 29, compared to
25 in 1996."
</P>
<P>
A FAO expert said the increase was "a most disturbing trend and
must be reversed to comply with the commitments and objectives of
the world food summit".
</P>
<P>
El Nino can affect food production in different ways.
</P>
<P>
Large stretches of crop field can be devastated by strong winds
or damaging floods, the report said..
</P>
<P>
In Southern Africa, "there is considerable concern over the
possible adverse effect of El Nino on the 1998 coarse grain
crop. Experts predict a strong possibility of poor rainfall for
the planting season which is soon to start."
</P>
<P>
In many Asian countries, El Nino "could lead to a delay in
re-planting, resulting in a switch to early maturing but lower
yielding varieties", the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
