<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Port Seeks More Business from China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, November 13 (Xinhua) -- A visiting Japanese
delegation has expressed the hope that more Chinese ships would
call Oita, an emerging Japanese port.
</P>
<P>
The chief attraction of the port of Oita, located in the
northern part of Kyushu, Japan, lies in its new container
terminal, according to Tatewaki Masato, deputy governor of Oita
Prefecture, who heads the delegation.
</P>
<P>
The port's Ozai Container Terminal, completed in November last
year, has two berths so far. One of them has a water depth of 14
meters and is able to accommodate 50,000-ton ships. And the
terminal's stack yard has space for 4,755 standard containers, the
largest in Kyushu. In 1996, the port of Oita handled 53 million
tons of cargo, according to Mr. Masato.
</P>
<P>
"The port of Oita operates 24 hours a day all the year round
and charges low fees. We hope more Chinese ships would use it,"
Masato said at a get-together with Shanghai port officials held at
the New Jingjiang Hotel here yesterday evening.
</P>
<P>
A shipping route with two monthly sailings has connected Oita
with Shanghai since last July, according to Mr. Masato.
</P>
<P>
The 18-member Japanese delegation has visited harbors, the
Waigaoqiao Container Terminal and the Suzhou New and High-Tech
Development Zone, among others. members said they were favorably
impressed by what they had seen.
</P>
<P>
Cai Meiyi, deputy director of the Shanghai Port Authority, said
that the Japanese delegation's visit was of great significance for
future cooperation between Shanghai and Oita. 
</P>
</TEXT>
