<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy to Begin 40-hour Work Week 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Rome, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Italy's major trade unions and
employers association, the Confindustria, reached an agreement here
today on reducing the work week to 40 hours, as demanded by the
European Union directives.
</P>
<P>
The accord, reached after 17 months of negotiations, officially
abrogates the 1923 regulation fixing the legal work week at 48
hours.
</P>
<P>
It also fixes vacation time at four weeks, sets limits on
overtime and regulates overnight work.
</P>
<P>
Walter Cerfeda, a trade union official, said the agreement will
make it easier to achieve a 35-hour working week, though "there
was an enormous difference between 48 and 35 hours."
</P>
<P>
Recent debate has focused on the government's commitment to
reducing the work week by law to 35 hours by the year 2001, in an
attempt to boost employment.
</P>
<P>
The commitment is the result of last month's compromise between
the government and the Communist Refoundation in order to avoid
political crisis over the 1998 budget draft.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, expected to be signed next week, should be
converted into a decree by the government at the beginning of next
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
