<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Revises Seismic Code for Buildings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 13 (Xinhua) -- China is revising its national
code for the seismic design of buildings in a bid to help
disseminate the experience and expertise in resistance to
earthquakes accumulated during the past decade.
</P>
<P>
"We embarked on the revision of the National Code for the
Seismic Design of Buildings (GBJ11-89) in September, with support
from the Ministry of Construction," Wang Yayong, a senior
anti-earthquake expert, was quoted by today's China Daily as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark GBJ11-89 code, laid down in 1989, has played a
significant role in minimizing losses caused by earthquakes, said
Wang, also director of the Institute of Earthquake Engineering
under the ministry-affiliated China Academy of Building Research.
</P>
<P>
In the 1996 tremors in Lijiang in southwest China's Yunnan
Province, three hospitals which were constructed according to the
code requirements did not collapse.
</P>
<P>
Since 1989, the number of buildings constructed with new
materials and using new construction methods has increased in
China.
</P>
<P>
China has made strenuous efforts in earthquake resistance,
particularly in enabling public and civil buildings to withstand
earthquakes measuring up to six on the Richter Scale.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1989 code was promulgated, the country has devised
and applied leading-edge quake-fighting techniques, including
rubber base-isolator, energy dissipation and structural control,
according to Wang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
