<HEADLINE> Costa Rica's Opposition Presidential Candidate Leads in Surveys </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The presidential candidate of
the opposition Social Christian Unity Party (PUSC) gained the lead
in the presidential race in Costa Rica with 11 percent of votes
more than the ruling National Liberation Party candidate,
according to a survey released today.
</P>
<P>
Miguel Angel Rodriguez, the PUSC candidate, got 35.3 percent of
the electoral preferences, while Jose Miguel Corrales, the ruling
party candidate, won 24.5 percent, a survey conducted by Unimer
said.
</P>
<P>
In another survey, the opposition candidate obtained 31.3
percent of the support and Corrales 20.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The presidential elections will be held on February 1,
1998 and candidate who leads in the surveys usually turns out to
be the winner in the final.
</P>
<P>
But about 36 percent of the surveyed said neither of the
candidates is reliable and honest, and 50.4 said the candidates
would not fulfill their promises. 
</P>
