<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fujian Takes to Expand Cargo Transport Through Ports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, November 13 (Xinhua) -- Fujian, an important eastern
China export-oriented province, has benefited from efforts to
upgrade its port facilities and improve software services.
</P>
<P>
In the first three quarters of this year the province
transported 15 million tons of cargo, up from 13.9 million tons
for all of 1996, according to official statistics. The tonnage for
the the first three quarters reflects a 50 percent increase over
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Officials with provincial customs predicted that the total for
this year would reach 20 million tons.
</P>
<P>
With its upgraded facilities, Fujian now has 10 state
category-A seaports and 32 category-B ports. More than 160
shipping routes have been opened linking the province to ports in
more than 60 countries and regions. In the first nine months,
9,140 cargo ships passed through ports in Fujian.
</P>
<P>
Local ports are competing to provide good services. The Xiamen
Port has simplified check-in procedures from three-to-four days to
a half-day, and Quanzhou has exempted container trucks from tolls.
</P>
<P>
Fujian officials have pledged to make provincial ports more
open to the outside in an effort to maintain sustainable economic
growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
