<HEADLINE> U.S. Won't Penalize Chilean Salmon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The United States has decided
not to charge compensatory duties for alleged subsidies for
Chilean salmon, Chilean Foreign Minister Jose Miguel Insulza said
here today.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said his government "is satisfied with the
decision because this proves the assertion we have always made --
Chile does not give subsidies."
</P>
<P>
He said the success of the industry is all to the merit of the
private sector, without any kind of help from the government.
</P>
<P>
"Our country will continue its cooperation with the U.S.
Department of Commerce to allow it to verify and confirm its
decision," he added.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government had accused Chile's salmon producers of
being able to dump their products because of state subsidies
received. It threatened to impose extra-tariffs and duties on
Chilean shipments of the product. 
