<HEADLINE> Ukraine's 1997 GDP Shrinks Further </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine's Finance Minister, Igor
Mityukov, said here today that the government's wishful estimate
of a 0.3-percent gross domestic product (GDP) growth for 1997 will
certainly fall flat.
</P>
<P>
The real GDP in the first nine months of this year dropped by
five percent compared with the same period of 1996, he said in an
explanation to the parliament about the draft 1998 budget.
</P>
<P>
He added that the state would have an income of 18.5 billion
gryvnas (14.7 billion dollars) predicted by the 1997 budget.
</P>
<P>
The failure to meet the GDP target was caused by the 2.4
percent decline in industrial production in 1997, the finance
minister explained.
</P>
<P>
Mityukov said the failure to meet the estimate was also caused
by unpaid taxes. The state budget had lost 113 million gryvnas
(60.4 million dollars) in unpaid value-added taxes (VAT), and 86
million gryvnas (about 46 million dollars) in unpaid income tax.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, the draft 1998 budget which is currently under
debate in the parliament, forecasts revenues of 28.8 billion
gryvnas (15.4 billion dollars), 1.4 billion gryvnas(749 million
dollars) more than the present budget.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the 1.4 billion gryvnas will come from
heavier taxes and excise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
