<HEADLINE> Car Sales Continue to Drop in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 13 (Xinhua) -- Largely due to the current
currency crisis, car sales in the Philippines fell 10.7 percent to
65,937 units during the last ten months this year from the
year-ago figures, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Citing figures from the Chamber of Automotive Manufacturers of
the Philippines Inc. (CAMPI), the reports said that for the month
of October alone, car sales slumped 39.9 percent, the largest
decline this year, to 4,762 units compared with the year-ago level
of 7,925 units.
</P>
<P>
CAMPI attributed weaker sales during the period to higher
interest rates and the de facto devaluation of the Philippine
peso.
</P>
<P>
Car assemblers were quoted as saying that their dealers were
informing them many customers with already approved retail
financing withdrew their application because of high interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
Monthly car sales have been on the decline since July when the
Central Bank allowed the floatation of the peso. The peso has so
far depreciated nearly 27 percent against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Also contributing to the decline was the slow processing and
selective approval of banks and other financing institutions and
the increased down-payment requirements, the reports said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
