<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four Billion Yuan Investment In East China Embankment Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, November 13 (Xinhua) -- East China's Jiangsu province
plans to put four billion yuan into dyke and dam construction over
the next three to five years.
</P>
<P>
Jiangsu has more than 1,500 km of river and port embankments
and a nearly 1,000 km coastline.
</P>
<P>
The province has more than 300 large and medium-sized
enterprises along the Yangtze river, but floods and other natural
disasters often hit the area. After one typhoon this year, the
province reported 310 km of embankment damage and six million
cu.m. of earth and stone lost, meaning economic losses of 530
million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government decided to take steps to raise the
flood-prevention level to the kind of flood that occurs only once
in fifty years, over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
From 1998 to 2000, the province will arrange 200 million yuan
in loans every year for its embankment project, and most of the
money will come from cities and counties, sources said.
</P>
<P>
Most of the money will be used for dykes and dams, the
provincial government said, and a special provincial-level group
will be set up to take charge of the work.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Imports Up In October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, November 13 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's biggest
port, continued to increase its imports for a month after China
reduced its tariffs in early October.
</P>
<P>
According to Shanghai Customs, imports in October amounted to
2.24 billion U.S. dollars worth, up 5.4 percent from the same
period of last year.
</P>
<P>
In its total import volume, the general trade volume was 0.73
billion U.S. dollars, down 2.1 percent from the same period of
1996, and the processing trade volume reached 0.95 billion
U.S. dollars, up 19.6 percent according to the comparable figures
of last year.
</P>
<P>
Imports focus on raw materials, plastic, steel, computers and
auto parts. Light industry and household appliance imports were
not up appreciably, even though tariffs on these goods have been
reduced by a relatively wide margin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
