<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0130 GMT, November 13 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif has strongly
condemned the killing of four Americans in the southern port city
of Karachi on Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to U.S. President Bill Clinton, Sharif said he was
deeply shocked to learn of the death of the four U.S. citizens,
who were employees of Union Texas Pakistan and were gunned down by
unidentified gunmen near a five-star hotel in
Karachi. (Pakistan-Killing-Americans)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russia Wednesday asked Iraq to immediately end the
restrictions on the U.N. special commission in charge of ridding
Iraq of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Russian Foreign Ministry spokesman Valery Nesterushkin was
quoted by the Interfax news agency as saying that if Iraq did so,
the U.N. Security Council would rule out the need of further
coordination between the member states on the tightening of
sanctions against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Russia's view on the issue is that Iraq must be given a
realistic prospect of overcoming its economic problems provided it
meets the demands of the international community, Nesterushkin
added. (Russia-Iraq-U.N. Commission)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Chinese Premier Li Peng, who is on a six-day official
good-will visit to Japan, Wednesday pointed out several basic
principles of guiding the development of China-Japan ties.
</P>
<P>
Delivering a speech here at a welcoming reception jointly held
by Japan-China friendship organizations, Li Peng said that the
first principle is mutual respect and non-interference in each
other's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
The two countries should respect each other's choice regarding
the paths of development, which are made according to the
country's national conditions, Li said. (Japan-China-Principles)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The U.N. Security Council Wednesday
unanimously adopted a resolution which decides to impose new
sanctions on Iraq. (UN-Iraq) 
</P>
