<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Government Stimulating Underground Facilities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 13 (Xinhua) -- China will be digging deep to
expand living and production facilities beneath its crowded
cities, according to sources with a news conference hosted by
Chinese Ministry of Construction.
</P>
<P>
Chinese officials are implementing the nation's first
regulations, entitled "China Urban Underground Space Development
and Management Regulations", regarding development and management
of urban underground space.
</P>
<P>
Ye Rutang, Vice-minister of construction, said at the
conference held Wednesday: "Making use of urban underground space
is a strategic option China adopts to maintain sustainable
development in the upcoming century."
</P>
<P>
Chinese cities, undergoing rapid growth, have experienced
"urban symptoms", namely shrinking construction land, a
deteriorating environment, traffic congestion and aging
infrastructure, Ye said.
</P>
<P>
The ministry's figures suggest that China's urbanization rate
will rise to 45 percent by 2010, when 630 million people will be
living in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
Ye pointed out that exploiting underground space is an obvious
solution to relieve the "symptoms".
</P>
<P>
Urban underground space, deemed by the United Nations in 1981
to be an important natural resource, refers to the subterranean
areas of a city's planned zones.
</P>
<P>
The minister said: "Developing the underground will not only
substantially ease the shortage of land for construction, but also
contribute to improvement and protection of historical relics."
</P>
<P>
In addition, underground buildings and facilities are not
susceptible to air raids and earthquakes, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
China has already benefited from underground projects,
especially raid shelters, which have been dug throughout the
country in past decades. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central American Countries Sign Security Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, November 12 (Xinhua) -- A Central American security
pact began to take effect as Nicaragua, the last one, signed it
today.
</P>
<P>
The Armed Forces Conference of Central America (CFAC) had been
signed by presidents of Guatemala, Honduras and El Salvador in
their respective capitals.
</P>
<P>
The pact said "its objective is making a steady effort to
achieve a strong integration and cooperation of armed forces" of
the Central American countries for overturning eventual attacks
against the sovereignty of the region.
</P>
<P>
Joaquin Cuadra, military chief of Nicaragua, said "the CFAC is
not a new offensive military alliance that gets us to old models
--like the extinct Central American Security Council established
in 1969-- that history has left behind."
</P>
<P>
He noted that the CFAC is an institution compatible with the
new challenges and demands of the upstart Central American
democracy, in search of the welfare and stability of the people
and nations of the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
