<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Artists Perform on Ukraine's Political Stage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian parties have drafted
several singers, poets and other celebrities on their tickets in a
bid to win votes in the next parliamentary elections, scheduled
for March 29 and 30, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Gregory Surkis, owner of the famous Dynamo Kiev soccer club,
will run for the Social Democrat Rukh party, while the nationalist
democratic Rukh party has placed poet Ivan Drach and singer Nina
Matvienko the fourth and eight respectively on its list of 225
candidates.
</P>
<P>
The Gromada party, led by ex-Prime minister Pavel Lazarenko,
has singer Dmytro Gnatyuk in the fourth slot, and the Christian
Democrats list poet Yury Demydenko the fifth.
</P>
<P>
Not everyone welcomes the trend. "Making parliament members
out of artists and poets is like nominating politicians for
literature awards," said Sergy Odarych, head of the Ukrainian
Perspective think tank.
</P>
<P>
Party officials disagreed, arguing that everyone is entitled to
run for office. "It does not matter what people are, what they
will do in parliament is the important thing," said Drach.
</P>
<P>
"Nina Matvienko is a great patriot who sings the Ukrainian idea
all over the world," said Viacheslav Koval, head of the Rukh
secretariat.
</P>
<P>
Poet Demydenko said artists are still under-represented on
party list. "I'm generally against artistic people becoming
lawmakers. But there are so few people who protect people's
souls, culture and spirituality," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mykola Mykhalchenko, spokesman of the Christian Democratic
party, fell in with Demydenko's views. He said the primary reason
for including the poet on the ticket was to get someone
representing artists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0301 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central Bank Issues Regulation on Assets Supervision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 13 (Xinhua) -- The People's Bank of China
(PBC) will strengthen its control over the wholly state-owned
commercial banks by appointing a board of supervisors to oversee
the quality, preservation and development of their assets.
</P>
<P>
According to a regulation issued by the PBC Wednesday, the
board is expected to provide a further line of defense against
financial risks, and will be significant to the improvement of
the commercial banks' operation and asset quality.
</P>
<P>
Yang Kaisheng, vice president of the Industrial and Commercial
Bank of China (ICBC) said he believed that the board of
supervisors would not hamper the commercial banks' operational
autonomy.
</P>
<P>
The performance of the four state-owned banks -- ICBC, Bank of
China, China Construction Bank and Agricultural Bank of China -- is
at present overseen by the supervisory departments in the PBC, the
central bank, and the commercial banks themselves.
</P>
<P>
According to the regulation, the major responsibilities of the
board will include: checking the financial reports provided by the
wholly state-owned commercial banks, supervising and assessing the
quality of the banks' credit assets, management of the asset
liability ratio and preservation and development of state-invested
property, examining and appraising the performance of the board
directors and bank presidents.
</P>
<P>
Insiders said the regulation has been published at a time when
the country is stepping up its campaign against financial risks
and to improve the performance of state-owned banks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971113.0302 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-13 </DATE_TIME>
