<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright: U.S. Lead in Building Peace in Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The United States should
play a leading role in building peace in Europe though it can not
and should not bear the burden of keeping peace alone, said U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Joint Armed Services Officers' Wives Meeting,
Albright stressed that building peace in Bosnia is "a
multinational, multi-faceted enterprise with military and numerous
civilian elements."
</P>
<P>
"Now there are those who say that Bosnia is Europe's problem
and that America has no stake. But history teaches us that there
is no natural political or geographic end point to violence in the
Balkans," she noted.
</P>
<P>
However, she noted that the U.S. allies should contribute to
the peace-building.
</P>
<P>
"America neither can nor should bear the burden of building
peace in Bosnia alone -- nor are we. We have more than two dozen
partners," she said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. administration has vowed to continue to have a
military presence in Bosnia after the current mandate of the
NATO-led peacekeeping force expires in June next year.
</P>
<P>
Early this year, Secretary of Defense William Cohen said that
the U.S. will pull all its some 8,000 troops out of Bosnia by the
deadline and the Europeans should take up the peace-keeping
mission.
</P>
<P>
"But as NATO's leader, we cannot walk away from a challenge
NATO has accepted. We have made a commitment, which we should
keep, to assist and persist in the healing process," Albright
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
