<HEADLINE> Dow Plunges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, November 12 (Xinhua) -- New York stocks fell sharply
today, with the Dow Jones industrial average plunging nearly 160
points as another bad day on foreign markets.
</P>
<P>
The Dow, which by midday had nearly recovered from an opening
88-point slide, dropped 157.41, or about 2.1 percent, to 7,401.32.
</P>
<P>
The news that the Fed let the interest rates unchanged was
overshadowed by the continued turmoil on the foreign stock
markets.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list fell 17.85 to 905.93, and
the NYSE composite index fell 8.73 to 476.93.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index fell 43.15 to 1,541.71, the fourth
biggest point loss ever.
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 9.99, or 2.3
percent, to 423.44; and the small-company dominated American Stock
Exchange composite index fell 12.39 to 668.04.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume totaled 584.60 million shares as of 4 p.m., up
sharply from the sluggish Tuesday trading of 434.61 million.
</P>
<P>
The news today that the Fed let the interest rates unchanged
was overshadowed by the continued turmoil on the foreign stock
markets.
</P>
<P>
The Tokyo Stock Exchange's main index plunged 2.7 percent
today, sinking to its lowest level in more than two years. In Hong
Kong, the main stock index plunged nearly 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in Brazil, the main stock index fell more than 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
The turmoil in Asia again spread to Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
