<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Rallies Against Japanese yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar on Wednesday
surged past 126 yen for the first time in more than six months on
concerns about a recovery in the Japanese economy.
</P>
<P>
The U.S currency also rose against the German mark. But some of
that rise was trimmed by speculation that Germany may raise
interest rates before the United States does.
</P>
<P>
In late New York trading, the dollar settled at 126.32 yen, up
from 125.03 late Tuesday. It was the first time it had surpassed
the 126 level since May 5. The dollar settled at 1.7183 marks, up
from 1.7077 marks.
</P>
<P>
Also lifting the dollar against the yen was continued turmoil in
Asian financial markets. Hong Kong shares fell 4 percent Wednesday
and Tokyo's Nikkei Stock Average dropped 2.73 percent, falling to
its lowest close since July 1995.
</P>
<P>
The dollar rose against the mark, supported by the strong U.S.
economy against Germany's economic climate. Traders speculated
that Germany may soon raise interest rates to give a push to its
economy. The U.S. Federal Reserve on Wednesday left short-term
interest rates unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The British pound was quoted at 1.7033 U.S. dollars, down from
1.7044 U.S. dollars late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Tuesday:
1.3927 Swiss francs, up from 1.3893; 5.7564 French francs, up from
5.7217; 1,682 Italian lire, up from 1,673; and 1.4079 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.4068.  
</P>
</TEXT>
