<HEADLINE> Security Tightened at Trial on CIA Killing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Following the killing of
four Americans in Pakistan, the executive of the Fairfax County
near Washington, D.C. today warned the county's employees of
safety risks due to the capital murder conviction of Mir Aimal
Kasi.
</P>
<P>
County Executive Robert O'Neill Jr. asked employees to be aware
of suspicious packages or events around him, and that he "may find
it necessary to institute a higher level of security" at selected
county buildings.
</P>
<P>
Security is already tight at the courthouse where a jury is
determining the fate of Kasi, who was convicted of killing and
wounding Central Intelligence Agency agents in 1993.
</P>
<P>
A Fairfax County jury declared on Monday that the Pakistan-born
Kasi was convicted in the 1993 deaths of two CIA employees and
wounding of three others. The jury is now hearing testimony to
determine if Kasi will spend life in prison or be executed.
</P>
<P>
Bomb-sniffing dogs patrolled the grounds around the Judicial
Center where the trial was held. Hundreds of large concrete
planters are positioned on many service roads to protect against
unauthorized cars.
</P>
<P>
A large mechanical roadblock is put near the Fairfax County
Circuit courthouse, where guards have cordoned off most parking
spots.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the State Department warned Americans abroad to be
on alert for possible retaliation against Kasi's guilty verdict.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Judge J. Howe Brown ordered that the names and
addresses of the jury be sealed permanently. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
