<HEADLINE> Military Action Against Iraq not Ruled out, Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 12 (Xinhua) -- The United States on
Wednesday hailed a unanimous approval by the U.N. Security Council
of condemning Iraq and warned military action still was an option
if Iraqi President Saddam Hussein continues to bar Americans from
taking part in U.N. weapons inspection teams' work.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry said the unanimous vote
reflected determination to get Iraq to comply with the U.N.
resolutions. "Any sign that they are not ready to comply will be
read for what it is ... an act of defiance and an act that
requires further measures," he added.
</P>
<P>
The resolution passed by the Security Council condemned Iraq
for its Oct.29 order to expel American weapons inspectors from
the country and demanded the order be rescinded immediately and
unconditionally.
</P>
<P>
The resolution also imposed a travel ban on Iraqi officials
who interfere with U.N. inspections and suspended further
Security Council reviews of economic sanctions on Iraq until the
weapons inspectors certify that Baghdad is cooperating with
them.
</P>
<P>
The resolution warned of "further measures" against Iraq if it
refuses to comply but does not include an unequivocal threat to
use military force.
</P>
<P>
However, U.S. State Department spokesman James Rubin said
Washington had not ruled out military responses to Iraq's any
further defiance.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after the Security Council's vote, Iraqi Deputy
Prime Minister Tareq Aziz said in New York that Baghdad would
neither back down nor rescind its order to expel the American
inspectors.
</P>
<P>
"Iraq will continue to explain its just case and this
resolution will not scare it," Aziz said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
In response, McCurry said: "that would be a very serious
breach of Iraq's obligation to the international community."
</P>
</TEXT>
