<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Australian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 13 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Australian newspapers published today:
</P>
<P>
The Australian
</P>
<P>
-- People power is forcing the republican movement in Australia
to seriously consider changing course to embrace a compromise plan
that would enable a popular vote to select an Australian head of
state.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald
</P>
<P>
-- Prime Minister John Howard yesterday called his predecessor
Paul Keating "a super racist" for Keating's 1993 Native Title Act,
and urged the opposition not to call the recently proposed
amendments to the native title "racist".
</P>
<P>
The Canberra Times
</P>
<P>
-- Australian civilian officials and not soldiers will
participate in a peace-monitoring operation on the troubled island
of Bougainville in Papua New Guinea (PNG) to oversee a peace deal
to be finalized early next year between the PNG government and
rebels on the island.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review
</P>
<P>
-- Mortgage interest costs will be removed by the Australian
Bureau of Statistics from the Consumer Price Index as part of one
of the biggest shake-ups of the key indicator of inflation and the
cost of living in Australia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
