<HEADLINE> Qin: China Supports Full Implementation of UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, November 12 (Xinhua) -- Qin Huasun, Chinese
Permanent Representative to the United Nations, stressed here
today that China always supports the inspection work of the United
Nations Special Commission in charge of scrapping Iraq's chemical,
biological and nuclear weapons, and has made constructive efforts
for the full implementation of the relevant U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese ambassador made the remarks at the consultation of
the U.N. Security Council on the crisis of arms inspections in
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Qin, who is also the current rotating chairman of the 15-member
Security Council, said that China is deeply concerned at the
development of the crisis and backs the consistent efforts made by
U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan and parties concerned.
</P>
<P>
The crisis came after Iraq decided on October 29 to expel
Americans working in the U.N. inspection team from the country and
later threatening to shoot down American U-2 planes supporting the
U.N. inspection operations in the region.
</P>
<P>
Qin said he believes that the relevant resolutions on Iraq
adopted after Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in 1990 should be fully
and seriously implemented.
</P>
<P>
China has once and again called on Iraq to resume cooperation
with the United Nations and fully fulfil its obligations, Qin
noted.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, China always believes that the sovereignty,
territorial integrity and Iraq's reasonable concerns about its
security should also be respected, and the progress which Iraq has
been made in its cooperation with the U.N. Special Commission in
the past few years should get a just and objective acknowledgment,
the Chinese ambassador added.
</P>
<P>
Qin said that the reasons for the current crisis are
complicated and multiple.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council should hear the opinions of both the U.N.
Special Commission and Iraq on the arms inspections, which began
after the Gulf War in 1991, in order to get a objective and
proper judegement on the inspections, Qin said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that problems arising in the weapons inspections
should be resolved through dialogue and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"We are against use of forces and threat of using forces which
would only lead further escalation of the tensions," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We do hope that all parties concerned should exercise
restraint, resolve the problems through dialogue and cooperation
and avoid escalation of the disputes, especially avoid armed
conflicts," Qin added.
</P>
<P>
Qin said that seeking a solution to the crisis, a pressing
matter of the moment is to keep diplomatic efforts and
promote the cooperation between Iraq and the U.N. Special
Commission instead of making the problems more complicated and
adding difficulty to the solutions.
</P>
<P>
Qin expressed the hope that the resolution unanimously passed
at the Security Council on Iraq today would help a proper
resolution of the problem.
</P>
<P>
In order to promote the solution, China voted for the
resolution cosponsored by the United States, Britain and some
other nations, he explained.
</P>
<P>
But the Chinese ambassador noted that the voting did not
indicate any change of the Chinese positions on the U.N.
sanctions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
