<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Disappointed at Egypt's Boycott of Doha Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 12 (Xinhua) -- the United States on
Wednesday expressed disappointment over Egypt for its boycotting a
Middle East and North Africa economic conference in protest of
Israel's negative position on peace negotiations with the
Palestinians, syrians and lebanese.
</P>
<P>
Egypt made the announcement of boycott to the economic
conference scheduled on Sunday in Doha, the capital of Qatar, on
Tuesday because of Israel's refusal to move forward in its peace
talks with Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
President Hosni Mubarak recently described as "meaningless" the
conference, which is aimed at develop economic cooperations
between Arab nations and Israel as a means to keep a loose
coalition intact, formed during the Gulf War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
"The aim of an economic conference is to build cooperation
between Israel and the Arab community, and this is linked to
progress towards peace. But so far no progress at all has been
achieved," Mubarak said.
</P>
<P>
Responding to Egypt's boycott, U.S. State Department spokesman
James Rubin said: "We are disappointed with this decision by the
Egyptian government. There are many issues on which we and Egypt
agree, but this is not one."
</P>
<P>
Rubin said there were only four Arab nations -- Jordan,
Tunisia, Yemen and Kuwait -- which have decided to attend the Doha
economic conference.
</P>
<P>
American officials said they were prepared for many Arab
nations to stay away from the conference, but not Egypt.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will attend the
conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
